68#define IS_RAW_DATA(d) ((d.d)->flags & QArrayData::RawDataType)
69#define REHASH(a) \
70 if (sl_minus_1 < sizeof(std::size_t) * CHAR_BIT) \
71 hashHaystack -= std::size_t(a) << sl_minus_1; \
72 hashHaystack <<= 1

85enum StringComparisonMode {
86 CompareStringsForEquality,
87 CompareStringsForOrdering

90template <typename Pointer>
91char32_t foldCaseHelper(Pointer ch, Pointer start) = delete;
92
93template <>
94char32_t foldCaseHelper<const QChar*>(const QChar* ch, const QChar* start)
95{
96 return foldCase(ch: reinterpret_cast<const char16_t*>(ch),
97 start: reinterpret_cast<const char16_t*>(start));
98}
99
100template <>
101char32_t foldCaseHelper<const char*>(const char* ch, const char*)
102{
103 return foldCase(ch: char16_t(uchar(*ch)));
104}
105
106template <typename T>
107char16_t valueTypeToUtf16(T t) = delete;
108
109template <>
110char16_t valueTypeToUtf16<QChar>(QChar t)
111{
112 return t.unicode();
113}
114
115template <>
116char16_t valueTypeToUtf16<char>(char t)
117{
118 return char16_t{uchar(t)};
119}
120
121template <typename T>
122static inline bool foldAndCompare(const T a, const T b)
123{
124 return foldCase(a) == b;
125}
126
127/*!
128 \internal
129
130 Returns the index position of the first occurrence of the
131 character \a ch in the string given by \a str and \a len,
132 searching forward from index
133 position \a from. Returns -1 if \a ch could not be found.
134*/
135static inline qsizetype qFindChar(QStringView str, QChar ch, qsizetype from, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
136{
137 if (-from > str.size())
138 return -1;
139 if (from < 0)
140 from = qMax(a: from + str.size(), b: qsizetype(0));
141 if (from < str.size()) {
142 const char16_t *s = str.utf16();
143 char16_t c = ch.unicode();
144 const char16_t *n = s + from;
145 const char16_t *e = s + str.size();
146 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive) {
147 n = QtPrivate::qustrchr(str: QStringView(n, e), ch: c);
148 if (n != e)
149 return n - s;
150 } else {
151 c = foldCase(ch: c);
152 auto it = std::find_if(first: n, last: e, pred: [c](const auto &ch) { return foldAndCompare(ch, c); });
153 if (it != e)
154 return std::distance(first: s, last: it);
155 }
156 }
157 return -1;
158}
159
160template <typename Haystack>
161static inline qsizetype qLastIndexOf(Haystack haystack, QChar needle,
162 qsizetype from, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
163{
164 if (haystack.size() == 0)
165 return -1;
166 if (from < 0)
167 from += haystack.size();
168 else if (std::size_t(from) > std::size_t(haystack.size()))
169 from = haystack.size() - 1;
170 if (from >= 0) {
171 char16_t c = needle.unicode();
172 const auto b = haystack.data();
173 auto n = b + from;
174 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive) {
175 for (; n >= b; --n)
176 if (valueTypeToUtf16(*n) == c)
177 return n - b;
178 } else {
179 c = foldCase(ch: c);
180 for (; n >= b; --n)
181 if (foldCase(valueTypeToUtf16(*n)) == c)
182 return n - b;
183 }
184 }
185 return -1;
186}
187template <> qsizetype
188qLastIndexOf(QString, QChar, qsizetype, Qt::CaseSensitivity) noexcept = delete; // unwanted, would detach
189
190template<typename Haystack, typename Needle>
191static qsizetype qLastIndexOf(Haystack haystack0, qsizetype from,
192 Needle needle0, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
193{
194 const qsizetype sl = needle0.size();
195 if (sl == 1)
196 return qLastIndexOf(haystack0, needle0.front(), from, cs);
197
198 const qsizetype l = haystack0.size();
199 if (from < 0)
200 from += l;
201 if (from == l && sl == 0)
202 return from;
203 const qsizetype delta = l - sl;
204 if (std::size_t(from) > std::size_t(l) || delta < 0)
205 return -1;
206 if (from > delta)
207 from = delta;
208
209 auto sv = [sl](const typename Haystack::value_type *v) { return Haystack(v, sl); };
210
211 auto haystack = haystack0.data();
212 const auto needle = needle0.data();
213 const auto *end = haystack;
214 haystack += from;
215 const std::size_t sl_minus_1 = sl ? sl - 1 : 0;
216 const auto *n = needle + sl_minus_1;
217 const auto *h = haystack + sl_minus_1;
218 std::size_t hashNeedle = 0, hashHaystack = 0;
219
220 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive) {
221 for (qsizetype idx = 0; idx < sl; ++idx) {
222 hashNeedle = (hashNeedle << 1) + valueTypeToUtf16(*(n - idx));
223 hashHaystack = (hashHaystack << 1) + valueTypeToUtf16(*(h - idx));
224 }
225 hashHaystack -= valueTypeToUtf16(*haystack);
226
227 while (haystack >= end) {
228 hashHaystack += valueTypeToUtf16(*haystack);
229 if (hashHaystack == hashNeedle
230 && QtPrivate::compareStrings(needle0, sv(haystack), Qt::CaseSensitive) == 0)
231 return haystack - end;
232 --haystack;
233 REHASH(valueTypeToUtf16(haystack[sl]));
234 }
235 } else {
236 for (qsizetype idx = 0; idx < sl; ++idx) {
237 hashNeedle = (hashNeedle << 1) + foldCaseHelper(n - idx, needle);
238 hashHaystack = (hashHaystack << 1) + foldCaseHelper(h - idx, end);
239 }
240 hashHaystack -= foldCaseHelper(haystack, end);
241
242 while (haystack >= end) {
243 hashHaystack += foldCaseHelper(haystack, end);
244 if (hashHaystack == hashNeedle
245 && QtPrivate::compareStrings(sv(haystack), needle0, Qt::CaseInsensitive) == 0)
246 return haystack - end;
247 --haystack;
248 REHASH(foldCaseHelper(haystack + sl, end));
249 }
250 }
251 return -1;
252}
253
254template <typename Haystack, typename Needle>
255bool qt_starts_with_impl(Haystack haystack, Needle needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
256{
257 if (haystack.isNull())
258 return needle.isNull();
259 const auto haystackLen = haystack.size();
260 const auto needleLen = needle.size();
261 if (haystackLen == 0)
262 return needleLen == 0;
263 if (needleLen > haystackLen)
264 return false;
265
266 return QtPrivate::compareStrings(haystack.left(needleLen), needle, cs) == 0;
267}
268
269template <typename Haystack, typename Needle>
270bool qt_ends_with_impl(Haystack haystack, Needle needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
271{
272 if (haystack.isNull())
273 return needle.isNull();
274 const auto haystackLen = haystack.size();
275 const auto needleLen = needle.size();
276 if (haystackLen == 0)
277 return needleLen == 0;
278 if (haystackLen < needleLen)
279 return false;
280
281 return QtPrivate::compareStrings(haystack.right(needleLen), needle, cs) == 0;
282}

284template <typename T, typename F>
285static void append_helper(QString &self, T view, F appendToUtf16)
286{
287 const auto strData = view.data();
288 const qsizetype strSize = view.size();
289 auto &d = self.data_ptr();
290 if (strData && strSize > 0) {
291 // the number of UTF-8 code units is always at a minimum equal to the number
292 // of equivalent UTF-16 code units
293 d.detachAndGrow(where: QArrayData::GrowsAtEnd, n: strSize, data: nullptr, old: nullptr);
294 Q_CHECK_PTR(d.data());
295 Q_ASSERT(strSize <= d.freeSpaceAtEnd());
296 const auto newEnd = appendToUtf16(self.data() + self.size(), view);
297 self.resize(newEnd - std::as_const(t&: self).data());
298 } else if (d.isNull() && !view.isNull()) { // special case
299 self = QLatin1StringView("");
300 }
301}

303template <uint MaxCount> struct UnrollTailLoop
304{
305 template <typename RetType, typename Functor1, typename Functor2, typename Number>
306 static inline RetType exec(Number count, RetType returnIfExited, Functor1 loopCheck, Functor2 returnIfFailed, Number i = 0)
307 {
308 /* equivalent to:
309 * while (count--) {
310 * if (loopCheck(i))
311 * return returnIfFailed(i);
312 * }
313 * return returnIfExited;
314 */
315
316 if (!count)
317 return returnIfExited;
318
319 bool check = loopCheck(i);
320 if (check)
321 return returnIfFailed(i);
322
323 return UnrollTailLoop<MaxCount - 1>::exec(count - 1, returnIfExited, loopCheck, returnIfFailed, i + 1);
324 }
325
326 template <typename Functor, typename Number>
327 static inline void exec(Number count, Functor code)
328 {
329 /* equivalent to:
330 * for (Number i = 0; i < count; ++i)
331 * code(i);
332 */
333 exec(count, 0, [=](Number i) -> bool { code(i); return false; }, [](Number) { return 0; });
334 }
335};
336template <> template <typename RetType, typename Functor1, typename Functor2, typename Number>
337inline RetType UnrollTailLoop<0>::exec(Number, RetType returnIfExited, Functor1, Functor2, Number)
338{
339 return returnIfExited;
340}
341} // unnamed namespace

343/*
344 * Note on the use of SIMD in qstring.cpp:
345 *
346 * Several operations with strings are improved with the use of SIMD code,
347 * since they are repetitive. For MIPS, we have hand-written assembly code
348 * outside of qstring.cpp targeting MIPS DSP and MIPS DSPr2. For ARM and for
349 * x86, we can only use intrinsics and therefore everything is contained in
350 * qstring.cpp. We need to use intrinsics only for those platforms due to the
351 * different compilers and toolchains used, which have different syntax for
352 * assembly sources.
353 *
354 * ** SSE notes: **
355 *
356 * Whenever multiple alternatives are equivalent or near so, we prefer the one
357 * using instructions from SSE2, since SSE2 is guaranteed to be enabled for all
358 * 64-bit builds and we enable it for 32-bit builds by default. Use of higher
359 * SSE versions should be done when there is a clear performance benefit and
360 * requires fallback code to SSE2, if it exists.
361 *
362 * Performance measurement in the past shows that most strings are short in
363 * size and, therefore, do not benefit from alignment prologues. That is,
364 * trying to find a 16-byte-aligned boundary to operate on is often more
365 * expensive than executing the unaligned operation directly. In addition, note
366 * that the QString private data is designed so that the data is stored on
367 * 16-byte boundaries if the system malloc() returns 16-byte aligned pointers
368 * on its own (64-bit glibc on Linux does; 32-bit glibc on Linux returns them
369 * 50% of the time), so skipping the alignment prologue is actually optimizing
370 * for the common case.
371 */
372
373#if defined(__mips_dsp)
374// From qstring_mips_dsp_asm.S
375extern "C" void qt_fromlatin1_mips_asm_unroll4 (char16_t*, const char*, uint);
376extern "C" void qt_fromlatin1_mips_asm_unroll8 (char16_t*, const char*, uint);
377extern "C" void qt_toLatin1_mips_dsp_asm(uchar *dst, const char16_t *src, int length);
378#endif

380#if defined(__SSE2__) && defined(Q_CC_GNU)
381// We may overrun the buffer, but that's a false positive:
382// this won't crash nor produce incorrect results
383# define ATTRIBUTE_NO_SANITIZE __attribute__((__no_sanitize_address__))
384#else
385# define ATTRIBUTE_NO_SANITIZE
386#endif

388#ifdef __SSE2__
389static constexpr bool UseSse4_1 = bool(qCompilerCpuFeatures & CpuFeatureSSE4_1);
390static constexpr bool UseAvx2 = UseSse4_1 &&
391 (qCompilerCpuFeatures & CpuFeatureArchHaswell) == CpuFeatureArchHaswell;
392
393[[maybe_unused]]
394static Q_ALWAYS_INLINE __m128i mm_load8_zero_extend(const void *ptr)
395{
396 const __m128i *dataptr = static_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr);
397 if constexpr (UseSse4_1) {
398 // use a MOVQ followed by PMOVZXBW
399 // if AVX2 is present, these should combine into a single VPMOVZXBW instruction
400 __m128i data = _mm_loadl_epi64(p: dataptr);
401 return _mm_cvtepu8_epi16(V: data);
402 }
403
404 // use MOVQ followed by PUNPCKLBW
405 __m128i data = _mm_loadl_epi64(p: dataptr);
406 return _mm_unpacklo_epi8(a: data, b: _mm_setzero_si128());
407}
408
409[[maybe_unused]] ATTRIBUTE_NO_SANITIZE
410static qsizetype qustrlen_sse2(const char16_t *str) noexcept
411{
412 // find the 16-byte alignment immediately prior or equal to str
413 quintptr misalignment = quintptr(str) & 0xf;
414 Q_ASSERT((misalignment & 1) == 0);
415 const char16_t *ptr = str - (misalignment / 2);
416
417 // load 16 bytes and see if we have a null
418 // (aligned loads can never segfault)
419 const __m128i zeroes = _mm_setzero_si128();
420 __m128i data = _mm_load_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
421 __m128i comparison = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: data, b: zeroes);
422 uint mask = _mm_movemask_epi8(a: comparison);
423
424 // ignore the result prior to the beginning of str
425 mask >>= misalignment;
426
427 // Have we found something in the first block? Need to handle it now
428 // because of the left shift above.
429 if (mask)
430 return qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: mask) / sizeof(char16_t);
431
432 constexpr qsizetype Step = sizeof(__m128i) / sizeof(char16_t);
433 qsizetype size = Step - misalignment / sizeof(char16_t);
434
435 size -= Step;
436 do {
437 size += Step;
438 data = _mm_load_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(str + size));
439
440 comparison = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: data, b: zeroes);
441 mask = _mm_movemask_epi8(a: comparison);
442 } while (mask == 0);
443
444 // found a null
445 return size + qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: mask) / sizeof(char16_t);
446}
447
448// Scans from \a ptr to \a end until \a maskval is non-zero. Returns true if
449// the no non-zero was found. Returns false and updates \a ptr to point to the
450// first 16-bit word that has any bit set (note: if the input is 8-bit, \a ptr
451// may be updated to one byte short).
452static bool simdTestMask(const char *&ptr, const char *end, quint32 maskval)
453{
454 auto updatePtr = [&](uint result) {
455 // found a character matching the mask
456 uint idx = qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: ~result);
457 ptr += idx;
458 return false;
459 };
460
461 if constexpr (UseSse4_1) {
462# ifndef Q_OS_QNX // compiler fails in the code below
463 __m128i mask;
464 auto updatePtrSimd = [&](__m128i data) {
465 __m128i masked = _mm_and_si128(a: mask, b: data);
466 __m128i comparison = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: masked, b: _mm_setzero_si128());
467 uint result = _mm_movemask_epi8(a: comparison);
468 return updatePtr(result);
469 };
470
471 if constexpr (UseAvx2) {
472 // AVX2 implementation: test 32 bytes at a time
473 const __m256i mask256 = _mm256_broadcastd_epi32(X: _mm_cvtsi32_si128(a: maskval));
474 while (ptr + 32 <= end) {
475 __m256i data = _mm256_loadu_si256(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m256i *>(ptr));
476 if (!_mm256_testz_si256(a: mask256, b: data)) {
477 // found a character matching the mask
478 __m256i masked256 = _mm256_and_si256(a: mask256, b: data);
479 __m256i comparison256 = _mm256_cmpeq_epi16(a: masked256, b: _mm256_setzero_si256());
480 return updatePtr(_mm256_movemask_epi8(a: comparison256));
481 }
482 ptr += 32;
483 }
484
485 mask = _mm256_castsi256_si128(a: mask256);
486 } else {
487 // SSE 4.1 implementation: test 32 bytes at a time (two 16-byte
488 // comparisons, unrolled)
489 mask = _mm_set1_epi32(i: maskval);
490 while (ptr + 32 <= end) {
491 __m128i data1 = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
492 __m128i data2 = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr + 16));
493 if (!_mm_testz_si128(M: mask, V: data1))
494 return updatePtrSimd(data1);
495
496 ptr += 16;
497 if (!_mm_testz_si128(M: mask, V: data2))
498 return updatePtrSimd(data2);
499 ptr += 16;
500 }
501 }
502
503 // AVX2 and SSE4.1: final 16-byte comparison
504 if (ptr + 16 <= end) {
505 __m128i data1 = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
506 if (!_mm_testz_si128(M: mask, V: data1))
507 return updatePtrSimd(data1);
508 ptr += 16;
509 }
510
511 // and final 8-byte comparison
512 if (ptr + 8 <= end) {
513 __m128i data1 = _mm_loadl_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
514 if (!_mm_testz_si128(M: mask, V: data1))
515 return updatePtrSimd(data1);
516 ptr += 8;
517 }
518
519 return true;
520# endif // QNX
521 }
522
523 // SSE2 implementation: test 16 bytes at a time.
524 const __m128i mask = _mm_set1_epi32(i: maskval);
525 while (ptr + 16 <= end) {
526 __m128i data = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
527 __m128i masked = _mm_and_si128(a: mask, b: data);
528 __m128i comparison = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: masked, b: _mm_setzero_si128());
529 quint16 result = _mm_movemask_epi8(a: comparison);
530 if (result != 0xffff)
531 return updatePtr(result);
532 ptr += 16;
533 }
534
535 // and one 8-byte comparison
536 if (ptr + 8 <= end) {
537 __m128i data = _mm_loadl_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
538 __m128i masked = _mm_and_si128(a: mask, b: data);
539 __m128i comparison = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: masked, b: _mm_setzero_si128());
540 quint8 result = _mm_movemask_epi8(a: comparison);
541 if (result != 0xff)
542 return updatePtr(result);
543 ptr += 8;
544 }
545
546 return true;
547}
548
549template <StringComparisonMode Mode, typename Char> [[maybe_unused]]
550static int ucstrncmp_sse2(const char16_t *a, const Char *b, size_t l)
551{
552 static_assert(std::is_unsigned_v<Char>);
553
554 // Using the PMOVMSKB instruction, we get two bits for each UTF-16 character
555 // we compare. This lambda helps extract the code unit.
556 static const auto codeUnitAt = [](const auto *n, qptrdiff idx) -> int {
557 constexpr int Stride = 2;
558 // this is the same as:
559 // return n[idx / Stride];
560 // but using pointer arithmetic to avoid the compiler dividing by two
561 // and multiplying by two in the case of char16_t (we know idx is even,
562 // but the compiler does not). This is not UB.
563
564 auto ptr = reinterpret_cast<const uchar *>(n);
565 ptr += idx / (Stride / sizeof(*n));
566 return *reinterpret_cast<decltype(n)>(ptr);
567 };
568 auto difference = [a, b](uint mask, qptrdiff offset) {
569 if (Mode == CompareStringsForEquality)
570 return 1;
571 uint idx = qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: mask);
572 return codeUnitAt(a + offset, idx) - codeUnitAt(b + offset, idx);
573 };
574
575 static const auto load8Chars = [](const auto *ptr) {
576 if (sizeof(*ptr) == 2)
577 return _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
578 __m128i chunk = _mm_loadl_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
579 return _mm_unpacklo_epi8(a: chunk, b: _mm_setzero_si128());
580 };
581 static const auto load4Chars = [](const auto *ptr) {
582 if (sizeof(*ptr) == 2)
583 return _mm_loadl_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
584 __m128i chunk = _mm_cvtsi32_si128(qFromUnaligned<quint32>(ptr));
585 return _mm_unpacklo_epi8(a: chunk, b: _mm_setzero_si128());
586 };
587
588 // we're going to read a[0..15] and b[0..15] (32 bytes)
589 auto processChunk16Chars = [a, b](qptrdiff offset) -> uint {
590 if constexpr (UseAvx2) {
591 __m256i a_data = _mm256_loadu_si256(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m256i *>(a + offset));
592 __m256i b_data;
593 if (sizeof(Char) == 1) {
594 // expand to UTF-16 via zero-extension
595 __m128i chunk = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(b + offset));
596 b_data = _mm256_cvtepu8_epi16(V: chunk);
597 } else {
598 b_data = _mm256_loadu_si256(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m256i *>(b + offset));
599 }
600 __m256i result = _mm256_cmpeq_epi16(a: a_data, b: b_data);
601 return _mm256_movemask_epi8(a: result);
602 }
603
604 __m128i a_data1 = load8Chars(a + offset);
605 __m128i a_data2 = load8Chars(a + offset + 8);
606 __m128i b_data1, b_data2;
607 if (sizeof(Char) == 1) {
608 // expand to UTF-16 via unpacking
609 __m128i b_data = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(b + offset));
610 b_data1 = _mm_unpacklo_epi8(a: b_data, b: _mm_setzero_si128());
611 b_data2 = _mm_unpackhi_epi8(a: b_data, b: _mm_setzero_si128());
612 } else {
613 b_data1 = load8Chars(b + offset);
614 b_data2 = load8Chars(b + offset + 8);
615 }
616 __m128i result1 = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: a_data1, b: b_data1);
617 __m128i result2 = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: a_data2, b: b_data2);
618 return _mm_movemask_epi8(a: result1) | _mm_movemask_epi8(a: result2) << 16;
619 };
620
621 if (l >= sizeof(__m256i) / sizeof(char16_t)) {
622 qptrdiff offset = 0;
623 for ( ; l >= offset + sizeof(__m256i) / sizeof(char16_t); offset += sizeof(__m256i) / sizeof(char16_t)) {
624 uint mask = ~processChunk16Chars(offset);
625 if (mask)
626 return difference(mask, offset);
627 }
628
629 // maybe overlap the last 32 bytes
630 if (size_t(offset) < l) {
631 offset = l - sizeof(__m256i) / sizeof(char16_t);
632 uint mask = ~processChunk16Chars(offset);
633 return mask ? difference(mask, offset) : 0;
634 }
635 } else if (l >= 4) {
636 __m128i a_data1, b_data1;
637 __m128i a_data2, b_data2;
638 int width;
639 if (l >= 8) {
640 width = 8;
641 a_data1 = load8Chars(a);
642 b_data1 = load8Chars(b);
643 a_data2 = load8Chars(a + l - width);
644 b_data2 = load8Chars(b + l - width);
645 } else {
646 // we're going to read a[0..3] and b[0..3] (8 bytes)
647 width = 4;
648 a_data1 = load4Chars(a);
649 b_data1 = load4Chars(b);
650 a_data2 = load4Chars(a + l - width);
651 b_data2 = load4Chars(b + l - width);
652 }
653
654 __m128i result = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: a_data1, b: b_data1);
655 ushort mask = ~_mm_movemask_epi8(a: result);
656 if (mask)
657 return difference(mask, 0);
658
659 result = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: a_data2, b: b_data2);
660 mask = ~_mm_movemask_epi8(a: result);
661 if (mask)
662 return difference(mask, l - width);
663 } else {
664 // reset l
665 l &= 3;
666
667 const auto lambda = [=](size_t i) -> int {
668 return a[i] - b[i];
669 };
670 return UnrollTailLoop<3>::exec(l, 0, lambda, lambda);
671 }
672 return 0;
673}
674#endif
675
676qsizetype QtPrivate::qustrlen(const char16_t *str) noexcept
677{
678#if defined(__SSE2__) && !(defined(__SANITIZE_ADDRESS__) || __has_feature(address_sanitizer))
679 return qustrlen_sse2(str);
680#endif
681
682 if (sizeof(wchar_t) == sizeof(char16_t))
683 return wcslen(s: reinterpret_cast<const wchar_t *>(str));
684
685 qsizetype result = 0;
686 while (*str++)
687 ++result;
688 return result;
689}
690
691/*!
692 * \internal
693 *
694 * Searches for character \a c in the string \a str and returns a pointer to
695 * it. Unlike strchr() and wcschr() (but like glibc's strchrnul()), if the
696 * character is not found, this function returns a pointer to the end of the
697 * string -- that is, \c{str.end()}.
698 */
699const char16_t *QtPrivate::qustrchr(QStringView str, char16_t c) noexcept
700{
701 const char16_t *n = str.utf16();
702 const char16_t *e = n + str.size();
703
704#ifdef __SSE2__
705 bool loops = true;
706 // Using the PMOVMSKB instruction, we get two bits for each character
707 // we compare.
708 __m128i mch;
709 if constexpr (UseAvx2) {
710 // we're going to read n[0..15] (32 bytes)
711 __m256i mch256 = _mm256_set1_epi32(i: c | (c << 16));
712 for (const char16_t *next = n + 16; next <= e; n = next, next += 16) {
713 __m256i data = _mm256_loadu_si256(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m256i *>(n));
714 __m256i result = _mm256_cmpeq_epi16(a: data, b: mch256);
715 uint mask = uint(_mm256_movemask_epi8(a: result));
716 if (mask) {
717 uint idx = qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: mask);
718 return n + idx / 2;
719 }
720 }
721 loops = false;
722 mch = _mm256_castsi256_si128(a: mch256);
723 } else {
724 mch = _mm_set1_epi32(i: c | (c << 16));
725 }
726
727 auto hasMatch = [mch, &n](__m128i data, ushort validityMask) {
728 __m128i result = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: data, b: mch);
729 uint mask = uint(_mm_movemask_epi8(a: result));
730 if ((mask & validityMask) == 0)
731 return false;
732 uint idx = qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: mask);
733 n += idx / 2;
734 return true;
735 };
736
737 // we're going to read n[0..7] (16 bytes)
738 for (const char16_t *next = n + 8; next <= e; n = next, next += 8) {
739 __m128i data = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(n));
740 if (hasMatch(data, 0xffff))
741 return n;
742
743 if (!loops) {
744 n += 8;
745 break;
746 }
747 }
748
749# if !defined(__OPTIMIZE_SIZE__)
750 // we're going to read n[0..3] (8 bytes)
751 if (e - n > 3) {
752 __m128i data = _mm_loadl_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(n));
753 if (hasMatch(data, 0xff))
754 return n;
755
756 n += 4;
757 }
758
759 return UnrollTailLoop<3>::exec(count: e - n, returnIfExited: e,
760 loopCheck: [=](qsizetype i) { return n[i] == c; },
761 returnIfFailed: [=](qsizetype i) { return n + i; });
762# endif
763#elif defined(__ARM_NEON__)
764 const uint16x8_t vmask = { 1, 1 << 1, 1 << 2, 1 << 3, 1 << 4, 1 << 5, 1 << 6, 1 << 7 };
765 const uint16x8_t ch_vec = vdupq_n_u16(c);
766 for (const char16_t *next = n + 8; next <= e; n = next, next += 8) {
767 uint16x8_t data = vld1q_u16(reinterpret_cast<const uint16_t *>(n));
768 uint mask = vaddvq_u16(vandq_u16(vceqq_u16(data, ch_vec), vmask));
769 if (ushort(mask)) {
770 // found a match
771 return n + qCountTrailingZeroBits(mask);
772 }
773 }
774#endif // aarch64
775
776 return std::find(first: n, last: e, val: c);
777}
778
779// Note: ptr on output may be off by one and point to a preceding US-ASCII
780// character. Usually harmless.
781bool qt_is_ascii(const char *&ptr, const char *end) noexcept
782{
783#if defined(__SSE2__)
784 // Testing for the high bit can be done efficiently with just PMOVMSKB
785 bool loops = true;
786 if constexpr (UseAvx2) {
787 while (ptr + 32 <= end) {
788 __m256i data = _mm256_loadu_si256(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m256i *>(ptr));
789 quint32 mask = _mm256_movemask_epi8(a: data);
790 if (mask) {
791 uint idx = qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: mask);
792 ptr += idx;
793 return false;
794 }
795 ptr += 32;
796 }
797 loops = false;
798 }
799
800 while (ptr + 16 <= end) {
801 __m128i data = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
802 quint32 mask = _mm_movemask_epi8(a: data);
803 if (mask) {
804 uint idx = qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: mask);
805 ptr += idx;
806 return false;
807 }
808 ptr += 16;
809
810 if (!loops)
811 break;
812 }
813 if (ptr + 8 <= end) {
814 __m128i data = _mm_loadl_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(ptr));
815 quint8 mask = _mm_movemask_epi8(a: data);
816 if (mask) {
817 uint idx = qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: mask);
818 ptr += idx;
819 return false;
820 }
821 ptr += 8;
822 }
823#endif
824
825 while (ptr + 4 <= end) {
826 quint32 data = qFromUnaligned<quint32>(src: ptr);
827 if (data &= 0x80808080U) {
828 uint idx = QSysInfo::ByteOrder == QSysInfo::BigEndian
829 ? qCountLeadingZeroBits(v: data)
830 : qCountTrailingZeroBits(v: data);
831 ptr += idx / 8;
832 return false;
833 }
834 ptr += 4;
835 }
836
837 while (ptr != end) {
838 if (quint8(*ptr) & 0x80)
839 return false;
840 ++ptr;
841 }
842 return true;
843}
844
845bool QtPrivate::isAscii(QLatin1StringView s) noexcept
846{
847 const char *ptr = s.begin();
848 const char *end = s.end();
849
850 return qt_is_ascii(ptr, end);
851}
852
853static bool isAscii_helper(const char16_t *&ptr, const char16_t *end)
854{
855#ifdef __SSE2__
856 const char *ptr8 = reinterpret_cast<const char *>(ptr);
857 const char *end8 = reinterpret_cast<const char *>(end);
858 bool ok = simdTestMask(ptr&: ptr8, end: end8, maskval: 0xff80ff80);
859 ptr = reinterpret_cast<const char16_t *>(ptr8);
860 if (!ok)
861 return false;
862#endif
863
864 while (ptr != end) {
865 if (*ptr & 0xff80)
866 return false;
867 ++ptr;
868 }
869 return true;
870}
871
872bool QtPrivate::isAscii(QStringView s) noexcept
873{
874 const char16_t *ptr = s.utf16();
875 const char16_t *end = ptr + s.size();
876
877 return isAscii_helper(ptr, end);
878}
879
880bool QtPrivate::isLatin1(QStringView s) noexcept
881{
882 const char16_t *ptr = s.utf16();
883 const char16_t *end = ptr + s.size();
884
885#ifdef __SSE2__
886 const char *ptr8 = reinterpret_cast<const char *>(ptr);
887 const char *end8 = reinterpret_cast<const char *>(end);
888 if (!simdTestMask(ptr&: ptr8, end: end8, maskval: 0xff00ff00))
889 return false;
890 ptr = reinterpret_cast<const char16_t *>(ptr8);
891#endif
892
893 while (ptr != end) {
894 if (*ptr++ > 0xff)
895 return false;
896 }
897 return true;
898}
899
900bool QtPrivate::isValidUtf16(QStringView s) noexcept
901{
902 constexpr char32_t InvalidCodePoint = UINT_MAX;
903
904 QStringIterator i(s);
905 while (i.hasNext()) {
906 const char32_t c = i.next(invalidAs: InvalidCodePoint);
907 if (c == InvalidCodePoint)
908 return false;
909 }
910
911 return true;
912}
913
914// conversion between Latin 1 and UTF-16
915Q_CORE_EXPORT void qt_from_latin1(char16_t *dst, const char *str, size_t size) noexcept
916{
917 /* SIMD:
918 * Unpacking with SSE has been shown to improve performance on recent CPUs
919 * The same method gives no improvement with NEON. On Aarch64, clang will do the vectorization
920 * itself in exactly the same way as one would do it with intrinsics.
921 */
922#if defined(__SSE2__)
923 // we're going to read str[offset..offset+15] (16 bytes)
924 const __m128i nullMask = _mm_setzero_si128();
925 auto processOneChunk = [=](qptrdiff offset) {
926 const __m128i chunk = _mm_loadu_si128(p: (const __m128i*)(str + offset)); // load
927 if constexpr (UseAvx2) {
928 // zero extend to an YMM register
929 const __m256i extended = _mm256_cvtepu8_epi16(V: chunk);
930
931 // store
932 _mm256_storeu_si256(p: (__m256i*)(dst + offset), a: extended);
933 } else {
934 // unpack the first 8 bytes, padding with zeros
935 const __m128i firstHalf = _mm_unpacklo_epi8(a: chunk, b: nullMask);
936 _mm_storeu_si128(p: (__m128i*)(dst + offset), b: firstHalf); // store
937
938 // unpack the last 8 bytes, padding with zeros
939 const __m128i secondHalf = _mm_unpackhi_epi8 (a: chunk, b: nullMask);
940 _mm_storeu_si128(p: (__m128i*)(dst + offset + 8), b: secondHalf); // store
941 }
942 };
943
944 const char *e = str + size;
945 if (size >= sizeof(__m128i)) {
946 qptrdiff offset = 0;
947 for ( ; str + offset + sizeof(__m128i) <= e; offset += sizeof(__m128i))
948 processOneChunk(offset);
949 if (str + offset < e)
950 processOneChunk(size - sizeof(__m128i));
951 return;
952 }
953
954# if !defined(__OPTIMIZE_SIZE__)
955 if (size >= 4) {
956 // two overlapped loads & stores, of either 64-bit or of 32-bit
957 if (size >= 8) {
958 const __m128i unpacked1 = mm_load8_zero_extend(ptr: str);
959 const __m128i unpacked2 = mm_load8_zero_extend(ptr: str + size - 8);
960 _mm_storeu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<__m128i *>(dst), b: unpacked1);
961 _mm_storeu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<__m128i *>(dst + size - 8), b: unpacked2);
962 } else {
963 const __m128i chunk1 = _mm_cvtsi32_si128(a: qFromUnaligned<quint32>(src: str));
964 const __m128i chunk2 = _mm_cvtsi32_si128(a: qFromUnaligned<quint32>(src: str + size - 4));
965 const __m128i unpacked1 = _mm_unpacklo_epi8(a: chunk1, b: nullMask);
966 const __m128i unpacked2 = _mm_unpacklo_epi8(a: chunk2, b: nullMask);
967 _mm_storel_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<__m128i *>(dst), a: unpacked1);
968 _mm_storel_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<__m128i *>(dst + size - 4), a: unpacked2);
969 }
970 return;
971 } else {
972 size = size % 4;
973 return UnrollTailLoop<3>::exec(count: qsizetype(size), code: [=](int i) { dst[i] = (uchar)str[i]; });
974 }
975# endif
976#endif
977#if defined(__mips_dsp)
978 static_assert(sizeof(qsizetype) == sizeof(int),
979 "oops, the assembler implementation needs to be called in a loop");
980 if (size > 20)
981 qt_fromlatin1_mips_asm_unroll8(dst, str, size);
982 else
983 qt_fromlatin1_mips_asm_unroll4(dst, str, size);
984#else
985 while (size--)
986 *dst++ = (uchar)*str++;
987#endif
988}
989
990static QVarLengthArray<char16_t> qt_from_latin1_to_qvla(QLatin1StringView str) noexcept
991{
992 const qsizetype len = str.size();
993 QVarLengthArray<char16_t> arr(len);
994 qt_from_latin1(dst: arr.data(), str: str.data(), size: len);
995 return arr;
996}
997
998template <bool Checked>
999static void qt_to_latin1_internal(uchar *dst, const char16_t *src, qsizetype length)
1000{
1001#if defined(__SSE2__)
1002 auto questionMark256 = []() {
1003 if constexpr (UseAvx2)
1004 return _mm256_broadcastw_epi16(X: _mm_cvtsi32_si128(a: '?'));
1005 else
1006 return 0;
1007 }();
1008 auto outOfRange256 = []() {
1009 if constexpr (UseAvx2)
1010 return _mm256_broadcastw_epi16(X: _mm_cvtsi32_si128(a: 0x100));
1011 else
1012 return 0;
1013 }();
1014 __m128i questionMark, outOfRange;
1015 if constexpr (UseAvx2) {
1016 questionMark = _mm256_castsi256_si128(questionMark256);
1017 outOfRange = _mm256_castsi256_si128(outOfRange256);
1018 } else {
1019 questionMark = _mm_set1_epi16(w: '?');
1020 outOfRange = _mm_set1_epi16(w: 0x100);
1021 }
1022
1023 auto mergeQuestionMarks = [=](__m128i chunk) {
1024 if (!Checked)
1025 return chunk;
1026
1027 // SSE has no compare instruction for unsigned comparison.
1028 if constexpr (UseSse4_1) {
1029 // We use an unsigned uc = qMin(uc, 0x100) and then compare for equality.
1030 chunk = _mm_min_epu16(V1: chunk, V2: outOfRange);
1031 const __m128i offLimitMask = _mm_cmpeq_epi16(a: chunk, b: outOfRange);
1032 chunk = _mm_blendv_epi8(V1: chunk, V2: questionMark, M: offLimitMask);
1033 return chunk;
1034 }
1035 // The variables must be shiffted + 0x8000 to be compared
1036 const __m128i signedBitOffset = _mm_set1_epi16(w: short(0x8000));
1037 const __m128i thresholdMask = _mm_set1_epi16(w: short(0xff + 0x8000));
1038
1039 const __m128i signedChunk = _mm_add_epi16(a: chunk, b: signedBitOffset);
1040 const __m128i offLimitMask = _mm_cmpgt_epi16(a: signedChunk, b: thresholdMask);
1041
1042 // offLimitQuestionMark contains '?' for each 16 bits that was off-limit
1043 // the 16 bits that were correct contains zeros
1044 const __m128i offLimitQuestionMark = _mm_and_si128(a: offLimitMask, b: questionMark);
1045
1046 // correctBytes contains the bytes that were in limit
1047 // the 16 bits that were off limits contains zeros
1048 const __m128i correctBytes = _mm_andnot_si128(a: offLimitMask, b: chunk);
1049
1050 // merge offLimitQuestionMark and correctBytes to have the result
1051 chunk = _mm_or_si128(a: correctBytes, b: offLimitQuestionMark);
1052
1053 Q_UNUSED(outOfRange);
1054 return chunk;
1055 };
1056
1057 // we're going to read to src[offset..offset+15] (16 bytes)
1058 auto loadChunkAt = [=](qptrdiff offset) {
1059 __m128i chunk1, chunk2;
1060 if constexpr (UseAvx2) {
1061 __m256i chunk = _mm256_loadu_si256(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m256i *>(src + offset));
1062 if (Checked) {
1063 // See mergeQuestionMarks lambda above for details
1064 chunk = _mm256_min_epu16(chunk, outOfRange256);
1065 const __m256i offLimitMask = _mm256_cmpeq_epi16(chunk, outOfRange256);
1066 chunk = _mm256_blendv_epi8(chunk, questionMark256, offLimitMask);
1067 }
1068
1069 chunk2 = _mm256_extracti128_si256(chunk, 1);
1070 chunk1 = _mm256_castsi256_si128(a: chunk);
1071 } else {
1072 chunk1 = _mm_loadu_si128(p: (const __m128i*)(src + offset)); // load
1073 chunk1 = mergeQuestionMarks(chunk1);
1074
1075 chunk2 = _mm_loadu_si128(p: (const __m128i*)(src + offset + 8)); // load
1076 chunk2 = mergeQuestionMarks(chunk2);
1077 }
1078
1079 // pack the two vector to 16 x 8bits elements
1080 return _mm_packus_epi16(a: chunk1, b: chunk2);
1081 };
1082
1083 if (size_t(length) >= sizeof(__m128i)) {
1084 // because of possible overlapping, we won't process the last chunk in the loop
1085 qptrdiff offset = 0;
1086 for ( ; offset + 2 * sizeof(__m128i) < size_t(length); offset += sizeof(__m128i))
1087 _mm_storeu_si128(reinterpret_cast<__m128i *>(dst + offset), loadChunkAt(offset));
1088
1089 // overlapped conversion of the last full chunk and the tail
1090 __m128i last1 = loadChunkAt(offset);
1091 __m128i last2 = loadChunkAt(length - sizeof(__m128i));
1092 _mm_storeu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<__m128i *>(dst + offset), b: last1);
1093 _mm_storeu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<__m128i *>(dst + length - sizeof(__m128i)), b: last2);
1094 return;
1095 }
1096
1097# if !defined(__OPTIMIZE_SIZE__)
1098 if (length >= 4) {
1099 // this code is fine even for in-place conversion because we load both
1100 // before any store
1101 if (length >= 8) {
1102 __m128i chunk1 = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(src));
1103 __m128i chunk2 = _mm_loadu_si128(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(src + length - 8));
1104 chunk1 = mergeQuestionMarks(chunk1);
1105 chunk2 = mergeQuestionMarks(chunk2);
1106
1107 // pack, where the upper half is ignored
1108 const __m128i result1 = _mm_packus_epi16(a: chunk1, b: chunk1);
1109 const __m128i result2 = _mm_packus_epi16(a: chunk2, b: chunk2);
1110 _mm_storel_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<__m128i *>(dst), a: result1);
1111 _mm_storel_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<__m128i *>(dst + length - 8), a: result2);
1112 } else {
1113 __m128i chunk1 = _mm_loadl_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(src));
1114 __m128i chunk2 = _mm_loadl_epi64(p: reinterpret_cast<const __m128i *>(src + length - 4));
1115 chunk1 = mergeQuestionMarks(chunk1);
1116 chunk2 = mergeQuestionMarks(chunk2);
1117
1118 // pack, we'll zero the upper three quarters
1119 const __m128i result1 = _mm_packus_epi16(a: chunk1, b: chunk1);
1120 const __m128i result2 = _mm_packus_epi16(a: chunk2, b: chunk2);
1121 qToUnaligned(src: _mm_cvtsi128_si32(a: result1), dest: dst);
1122 qToUnaligned(src: _mm_cvtsi128_si32(a: result2), dest: dst + length - 4);
1123 }
1124 return;
1125 }
1126
1127 length = length % 4;
1128 return UnrollTailLoop<3>::exec(length, [=](qsizetype i) {
1129 if (Checked)
1130 dst[i] = (src[i]>0xff) ? '?' : (uchar) src[i];
1131 else
1132 dst[i] = src[i];
1133 });
1134# else
1135 length = length % 16;
1136# endif // optimize size
1137#elif defined(__ARM_NEON__)
1138 // Refer to the documentation of the SSE2 implementation.
1139 // This uses exactly the same method as for SSE except:
1140 // 1) neon has unsigned comparison
1141 // 2) packing is done to 64 bits (8 x 8bits component).
1142 if (length >= 16) {
1143 const qsizetype chunkCount = length >> 3; // divided by 8
1144 const uint16x8_t questionMark = vdupq_n_u16('?'); // set
1145 const uint16x8_t thresholdMask = vdupq_n_u16(0xff); // set
1146 for (qsizetype i = 0; i < chunkCount; ++i) {
1147 uint16x8_t chunk = vld1q_u16((uint16_t *)src); // load
1148 src += 8;
1149
1150 if (Checked) {
1151 const uint16x8_t offLimitMask = vcgtq_u16(chunk, thresholdMask); // chunk > thresholdMask
1152 const uint16x8_t offLimitQuestionMark = vandq_u16(offLimitMask, questionMark); // offLimitMask & questionMark
1153 const uint16x8_t correctBytes = vbicq_u16(chunk, offLimitMask); // !offLimitMask & chunk
1154 chunk = vorrq_u16(correctBytes, offLimitQuestionMark); // correctBytes | offLimitQuestionMark
1155 }
1156 const uint8x8_t result = vmovn_u16(chunk); // narrowing move->packing
1157 vst1_u8(dst, result); // store
1158 dst += 8;
1159 }
1160 length = length % 8;
1161 }
1162#endif
1163#if defined(__mips_dsp)
1164 static_assert(sizeof(qsizetype) == sizeof(int),
1165 "oops, the assembler implementation needs to be called in a loop");
1166 qt_toLatin1_mips_dsp_asm(dst, src, length);
1167#else
1168 while (length--) {
1169 if (Checked)
1170 *dst++ = (*src>0xff) ? '?' : (uchar) *src;
1171 else
1172 *dst++ = *src;
1173 ++src;
1174 }
1175#endif
1176}
1177
1178void qt_to_latin1(uchar *dst, const char16_t *src, qsizetype length)
1179{
1180 qt_to_latin1_internal<true>(dst, src, length);
1181}

1183void qt_to_latin1_unchecked(uchar *dst, const char16_t *src, qsizetype length)
1184{
1185 qt_to_latin1_internal<false>(dst, src, length);

1187
1188// Unicode case-insensitive comparison (argument order matches QStringView)
1189Q_NEVER_INLINE static int ucstricmp(qsizetype alen, const char16_t *a, qsizetype blen, const char16_t *b)
1190{
1191 if (a == b)
1192 return (alen - blen);
1193
1194 char32_t alast = 0;
1195 char32_t blast = 0;
1196 qsizetype l = qMin(a: alen, b: blen);
1197 qsizetype i;
1198 for (i = 0; i < l; ++i) {
1199// qDebug() << Qt::hex << alast << blast;
1200// qDebug() << Qt::hex << "*a=" << *a << "alast=" << alast << "folded=" << foldCase (*a, alast);
1201// qDebug() << Qt::hex << "*b=" << *b << "blast=" << blast << "folded=" << foldCase (*b, blast);
1202 int diff = foldCase(ch: a[i], last&: alast) - foldCase(ch: b[i], last&: blast);
1203 if ((diff))
1204 return diff;
1205 }
1206 if (i == alen) {
1207 if (i == blen)
1208 return 0;
1209 return -1;
1210 }
1211 return 1;
1212}
1213
1214// Case-insensitive comparison between a QStringView and a QLatin1StringView
1215// (argument order matches those types)
1216Q_NEVER_INLINE static int ucstricmp(qsizetype alen, const char16_t *a, qsizetype blen, const char *b)
1217{
1218 qsizetype l = qMin(a: alen, b: blen);
1219 qsizetype i;
1220 for (i = 0; i < l; ++i) {
1221 int diff = foldCase(ch: a[i]) - foldCase(ch: char16_t{uchar(b[i])});
1222 if ((diff))
1223 return diff;
1224 }
1225 if (i == alen) {
1226 if (i == blen)
1227 return 0;
1228 return -1;
1229 }
1230 return 1;
1231}
1232
1233// Case-insensitive comparison between a Unicode string and a UTF-8 string
1234Q_NEVER_INLINE static int ucstricmp8(const char *utf8, const char *utf8end, const QChar *utf16, const QChar *utf16end)
1235{
1236 auto src1 = reinterpret_cast<const uchar *>(utf8);
1237 auto end1 = reinterpret_cast<const uchar *>(utf8end);
1238 QStringIterator src2(utf16, utf16end);
1239
1240 while (src1 < end1 && src2.hasNext()) {
1241 char32_t uc1 = 0;
1242 char32_t *output = &uc1;
1243 uchar b = *src1++;
1244 int res = QUtf8Functions::fromUtf8<QUtf8BaseTraits>(b, dst&: output, src&: src1, end: end1);
1245 if (res < 0) {
1246 // decoding error
1247 uc1 = QChar::ReplacementCharacter;
1248 } else {
1249 uc1 = QChar::toCaseFolded(ucs4: uc1);
1250 }
1251
1252 char32_t uc2 = QChar::toCaseFolded(ucs4: src2.next());
1253 int diff = uc1 - uc2; // can't underflow
1254 if (diff)
1255 return diff;
1256 }
1257
1258 // the shorter string sorts first
1259 return (end1 > src1) - int(src2.hasNext());
1260}
1261
1262#if defined(__mips_dsp)
1263// From qstring_mips_dsp_asm.S
1264extern "C" int qt_ucstrncmp_mips_dsp_asm(const char16_t *a,
1265 const char16_t *b,
1266 unsigned len);
1267#endif
1268
1269// Unicode case-sensitive compare two same-sized strings
1270template <StringComparisonMode Mode>
1271static int ucstrncmp(const char16_t *a, const char16_t *b, size_t l)
1272{
1273 // This function isn't memcmp() because that can return the wrong sorting
1274 // result in little-endian architectures: 0x00ff must sort before 0x0100,
1275 // but the bytes in memory are FF 00 and 00 01.
1276
1277#ifndef __OPTIMIZE_SIZE__
1278# if defined(__mips_dsp)
1279 static_assert(sizeof(uint) == sizeof(size_t));
1280 if (l >= 8) {
1281 return qt_ucstrncmp_mips_dsp_asm(a, b, l);
1282 }
1283# elif defined(__SSE2__)
1284 return ucstrncmp_sse2<Mode>(a, b, l);
1285# elif defined(__ARM_NEON__)
1286 if (l >= 8) {
1287 const char16_t *end = a + l;
1288 const uint16x8_t mask = { 1, 1 << 1, 1 << 2, 1 << 3, 1 << 4, 1 << 5, 1 << 6, 1 << 7 };
1289 while (end - a > 7) {
1290 uint16x8_t da = vld1q_u16(reinterpret_cast<const uint16_t *>(a));
1291 uint16x8_t db = vld1q_u16(reinterpret_cast<const uint16_t *>(b));
1292
1293 uint8_t r = ~(uint8_t)vaddvq_u16(vandq_u16(vceqq_u16(da, db), mask));
1294 if (r) {
1295 // found a different QChar
1296 if (Mode == CompareStringsForEquality)
1297 return 1;
1298 uint idx = qCountTrailingZeroBits(r);
1299 return a[idx] - b[idx];
1300 }
1301 a += 8;
1302 b += 8;
1303 }
1304 l &= 7;
1305 }
1306 const auto lambda = [=](size_t i) -> int {
1307 return a[i] - b[i];
1308 };
1309 return UnrollTailLoop<7>::exec(l, 0, lambda, lambda);
1310# endif // MIPS DSP or __SSE2__ or __ARM_NEON__
1311#endif // __OPTIMIZE_SIZE__
1312
1313 if (Mode == CompareStringsForEquality || QSysInfo::ByteOrder == QSysInfo::BigEndian)
1314 return memcmp(s1: a, s2: b, n: l * sizeof(char16_t));
1315
1316 for (size_t i = 0; i < l; ++i) {
1317 if (int diff = a[i] - b[i])
1318 return diff;
1319 }
1320 return 0;
1321}
1322
1323template <StringComparisonMode Mode>
1324static int ucstrncmp(const char16_t *a, const char *b, size_t l)
1325{
1326 const uchar *c = reinterpret_cast<const uchar *>(b);
1327 const char16_t *uc = a;
1328 const char16_t *e = uc + l;
1329
1330#if defined(__SSE2__) && !defined(__OPTIMIZE_SIZE__)
1331 return ucstrncmp_sse2<Mode>(uc, c, l);
1332#endif
1333
1334 while (uc < e) {
1335 int diff = *uc - *c;
1336 if (diff)
1337 return diff;
1338 uc++, c++;
1339 }
1340
1341 return 0;
1342}
1343
1344// Unicode case-sensitive equality
1345template <typename Char2>
1346static bool ucstreq(const char16_t *a, size_t alen, const Char2 *b, size_t blen)
1347{
1348 if (alen != blen)
1349 return false;
1350 if constexpr (std::is_same_v<decltype(a), decltype(b)>) {
1351 if (a == b)
1352 return true;
1353 }
1354 return ucstrncmp<CompareStringsForEquality>(a, b, alen) == 0;
1355}
1356
1357// Unicode case-sensitive comparison
1358template <typename Char2>
1359static int ucstrcmp(const char16_t *a, size_t alen, const Char2 *b, size_t blen)
1360{
1361 if constexpr (std::is_same_v<decltype(a), decltype(b)>) {
1362 if (a == b && alen == blen)
1363 return 0;
1364 }
1365 const size_t l = qMin(a: alen, b: blen);
1366 int cmp = ucstrncmp<CompareStringsForOrdering>(a, b, l);
1367 return cmp ? cmp : qt_lencmp(lhs: alen, rhs: blen);
1368}

1388};
1389static int latin1nicmp(const char *lhsChar, qsizetype lSize, const char *rhsChar, qsizetype rSize)
1390{
1391 // We're called with QLatin1StringView's .data() and .size():
1392 Q_ASSERT(lSize >= 0 && rSize >= 0);
1393 if (!lSize)
1394 return rSize ? -1 : 0;
1395 if (!rSize)
1396 return 1;
1397 const qsizetype size = std::min(a: lSize, b: rSize);
1398
1399 const uchar *lhs = reinterpret_cast<const uchar *>(lhsChar);
1400 const uchar *rhs = reinterpret_cast<const uchar *>(rhsChar);
1401 Q_ASSERT(lhs && rhs); // since both lSize and rSize are positive
1402 for (qsizetype i = 0; i < size; i++) {
1403 if (int res = latin1Lower[lhs[i]] - latin1Lower[rhs[i]])
1404 return res;
1405 }
1406 return qt_lencmp(lhs: lSize, rhs: rSize);
1407}

1454bool QAnyStringView::equal(QAnyStringView lhs, QAnyStringView rhs) noexcept
1455{
1456 if (lhs.size() != rhs.size() && lhs.isUtf8() == rhs.isUtf8())
1457 return false;

1459 return rhs.visit([lhs](auto rhs) {
1460 return QtPrivate::equalStrings(lhs, rhs);
1461 });
1462 });
1463}

1465/*!
1466 \relates QStringView
1467 \internal
1468 \since 5.10
1469
1470 Returns an integer that compares to 0 as \a lhs compares to \a rhs.
1471
1472 \include qstring.qdocinc {search-comparison-case-sensitivity} {comparison}
1473
1474 Case-sensitive comparison is based exclusively on the numeric Unicode values
1475 of the characters and is very fast, but is not what a human would expect.
1476 Consider sorting user-visible strings with QString::localeAwareCompare().
1477
1478 \sa {Comparing Strings}
1479*/
1480int QtPrivate::compareStrings(QStringView lhs, QStringView rhs, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
1481{
1482 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive)
1483 return ucstrcmp(a: lhs.utf16(), alen: lhs.size(), b: rhs.utf16(), blen: rhs.size());
1484 return ucstricmp(alen: lhs.size(), a: lhs.utf16(), blen: rhs.size(), b: rhs.utf16());
1485}

1500
1501 \sa {Comparing Strings}

1532/*!
1533 \relates QStringView
1534 \internal
1535 \since 5.10
1536 \overload
1537
1538 Returns an integer that compares to 0 as \a lhs compares to \a rhs.
1539
1540 \include qstring.qdocinc {search-comparison-case-sensitivity} {comparison}
1541
1542 Case-sensitive comparison is based exclusively on the numeric Latin-1 values
1543 of the characters and is very fast, but is not what a human would expect.
1544 Consider sorting user-visible strings with QString::localeAwareCompare().
1545
1546 \sa {Comparing Strings}
1547*/
1548int QtPrivate::compareStrings(QLatin1StringView lhs, QLatin1StringView rhs, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
1549{
1550 if (lhs.isEmpty())
1551 return qt_lencmp(lhs: qsizetype(0), rhs: rhs.size());
1552 if (cs == Qt::CaseInsensitive)
1553 return latin1nicmp(lhsChar: lhs.data(), lSize: lhs.size(), rhsChar: rhs.data(), rSize: rhs.size());
1554 const auto l = std::min(a: lhs.size(), b: rhs.size());
1555 int r = memcmp(s1: lhs.data(), s2: rhs.data(), n: l);
1556 return r ? r : qt_lencmp(lhs: lhs.size(), rhs: rhs.size());
1557}

1614// ### Qt 7: do not allow anything but ASCII digits
1615// in arg()'s replacements.
1616#if QT_VERSION < QT_VERSION_CHECK(7, 0, 0)
1617static bool supportUnicodeDigitValuesInArg()
1618{
1619 static const bool result = []() {
1620 static const char supportUnicodeDigitValuesEnvVar[]
1621 = "QT_USE_UNICODE_DIGIT_VALUES_IN_STRING_ARG";
1622
1623 if (qEnvironmentVariableIsSet(varName: supportUnicodeDigitValuesEnvVar))
1624 return qEnvironmentVariableIntValue(varName: supportUnicodeDigitValuesEnvVar) != 0;
1625
1626#if QT_VERSION < QT_VERSION_CHECK(6, 6, 0) // keep it in sync with the test
1627 return true;
1628#else
1629 return false;
1630#endif
1631 }();
1632
1633 return result;
1634}
1635#endif
1636
1637static int qArgDigitValue(QChar ch) noexcept
1638{
1639#if QT_VERSION < QT_VERSION_CHECK(7, 0, 0)
1640 if (supportUnicodeDigitValuesInArg())
1641 return ch.digitValue();
1642#endif
1643 if (ch >= u'0' && ch <= u'9')
1644 return int(ch.unicode() - u'0');
1645 return -1;
1646}

1653/*!
1654 \macro QT_RESTRICTED_CAST_FROM_ASCII
1655 \relates QString
1656
1657 Disables most automatic conversions from source literals and 8-bit data
1658 to unicode QStrings, but allows the use of
1659 the \c{QChar(char)} and \c{QString(const char (&ch)[N]} constructors,
1660 and the \c{QString::operator=(const char (&ch)[N])} assignment operator.
1661 This gives most of the type-safety benefits of \l QT_NO_CAST_FROM_ASCII
1662 but does not require user code to wrap character and string literals
1663 with QLatin1Char, QLatin1StringView or similar.
1664
1665 Using this macro together with source strings outside the 7-bit range,
1666 non-literals, or literals with embedded NUL characters is undefined.
1667
1668 \sa QT_NO_CAST_FROM_ASCII, QT_NO_CAST_TO_ASCII
1669*/
1670
1671/*!
1672 \macro QT_NO_CAST_FROM_ASCII
1673 \relates QString
1674 \relates QChar
1675
1676 Disables automatic conversions from 8-bit strings (\c{char *}) to Unicode
1677 QStrings, as well as from 8-bit \c{char} types (\c{char} and
1678 \c{unsigned char}) to QChar.
1679
1680 \sa QT_NO_CAST_TO_ASCII, QT_RESTRICTED_CAST_FROM_ASCII,
1681 QT_NO_CAST_FROM_BYTEARRAY
1682*/
1683
1684/*!
1685 \macro QT_NO_CAST_TO_ASCII
1686 \relates QString
1687
1688 Disables automatic conversion from QString to 8-bit strings (\c{char *}).
1689
1690 \sa QT_NO_CAST_FROM_ASCII, QT_RESTRICTED_CAST_FROM_ASCII,
1691 QT_NO_CAST_FROM_BYTEARRAY
1692*/
1693
1694/*!
1695 \macro QT_ASCII_CAST_WARNINGS
1696 \internal
1697 \relates QString
1698
1699 This macro can be defined to force a warning whenever a function is
1700 called that automatically converts between unicode and 8-bit encodings.
1701
1702 Note: This only works for compilers that support warnings for
1703 deprecated API.
1704
1705 \sa QT_NO_CAST_TO_ASCII, QT_NO_CAST_FROM_ASCII, QT_RESTRICTED_CAST_FROM_ASCII
1706*/
1707
1708/*!
1709 \class QString
1710 \inmodule QtCore
1711 \reentrant
1712
1713 \brief The QString class provides a Unicode character string.
1714
1715 \ingroup tools
1716 \ingroup shared
1717 \ingroup string-processing
1718
1719 QString stores a string of 16-bit \l{QChar}s, where each QChar
1720 corresponds to one UTF-16 code unit. (Unicode characters
1721 with code values above 65535 are stored using surrogate pairs,
1722 i.e., two consecutive \l{QChar}s.)
1723
1724 \l{Unicode} is an international standard that supports most of the
1725 writing systems in use today. It is a superset of US-ASCII (ANSI
1726 X3.4-1986) and Latin-1 (ISO 8859-1), and all the US-ASCII/Latin-1
1727 characters are available at the same code positions.
1728
1729 Behind the scenes, QString uses \l{implicit sharing}
1730 (copy-on-write) to reduce memory usage and to avoid the needless
1731 copying of data. This also helps reduce the inherent overhead of
1732 storing 16-bit characters instead of 8-bit characters.
1733
1734 In addition to QString, Qt also provides the QByteArray class to
1735 store raw bytes and traditional 8-bit '\\0'-terminated strings.
1736 For most purposes, QString is the class you want to use. It is
1737 used throughout the Qt API, and the Unicode support ensures that
1738 your applications will be easy to translate if you want to expand
1739 your application's market at some point. The two main cases where
1740 QByteArray is appropriate are when you need to store raw binary
1741 data, and when memory conservation is critical (like in embedded
1742 systems).
1743
1744 \tableofcontents
1745
1746 \section1 Initializing a String
1747
1748 One way to initialize a QString is simply to pass a \c{const char
1749 *} to its constructor. For example, the following code creates a
1750 QString of size 5 containing the data "Hello":
1751
1752 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 0
1753
1754 QString converts the \c{const char *} data into Unicode using the
1755 fromUtf8() function.
1756
1757 In all of the QString functions that take \c{const char *}
1758 parameters, the \c{const char *} is interpreted as a classic
1759 C-style '\\0'-terminated string encoded in UTF-8. It is legal for
1760 the \c{const char *} parameter to be \nullptr.
1761
1762 You can also provide string data as an array of \l{QChar}s:
1763
1764 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 1
1765
1766 QString makes a deep copy of the QChar data, so you can modify it
1767 later without experiencing side effects. (If for performance
1768 reasons you don't want to take a deep copy of the character data,
1769 use QString::fromRawData() instead.)
1770
1771 Another approach is to set the size of the string using resize()
1772 and to initialize the data character per character. QString uses
1773 0-based indexes, just like C++ arrays. To access the character at
1774 a particular index position, you can use \l operator[](). On
1775 non-\c{const} strings, \l operator[]() returns a reference to a
1776 character that can be used on the left side of an assignment. For
1777 example:
1778
1779 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 2
1780
1781 For read-only access, an alternative syntax is to use the at()
1782 function:
1783
1784 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 3
1785
1786 The at() function can be faster than \l operator[](), because it
1787 never causes a \l{deep copy} to occur. Alternatively, use the
1788 first(), last(), or sliced() functions to extract several characters
1789 at a time.
1790
1791 A QString can embed '\\0' characters (QChar::Null). The size()
1792 function always returns the size of the whole string, including
1793 embedded '\\0' characters.
1794
1795 After a call to the resize() function, newly allocated characters
1796 have undefined values. To set all the characters in the string to
1797 a particular value, use the fill() function.
1798
1799 QString provides dozens of overloads designed to simplify string
1800 usage. For example, if you want to compare a QString with a string
1801 literal, you can write code like this and it will work as expected:
1802
1803 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 4
1804
1805 You can also pass string literals to functions that take QStrings
1806 as arguments, invoking the QString(const char *)
1807 constructor. Similarly, you can pass a QString to a function that
1808 takes a \c{const char *} argument using the \l qPrintable() macro
1809 which returns the given QString as a \c{const char *}. This is
1810 equivalent to calling <QString>.toLocal8Bit().constData().
1811
1812 \section1 Manipulating String Data
1813
1814 QString provides the following basic functions for modifying the
1815 character data: append(), prepend(), insert(), replace(), and
1816 remove(). For example:
1817
1818 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 5
1819
1820 In the above example the replace() function's first two arguments are the
1821 position from which to start replacing and the number of characters that
1822 should be replaced.
1823
1824 When data-modifying functions increase the size of the string,
1825 they may lead to reallocation of memory for the QString object. When
1826 this happens, QString expands by more than it immediately needs so as
1827 to have space for further expansion without reallocation until the size
1828 of the string has greatly increased.
1829
1830 The insert(), remove() and, when replacing a sub-string with one of
1831 different size, replace() functions can be slow (\l{linear time}) for
1832 large strings, because they require moving many characters in the string
1833 by at least one position in memory.
1834
1835 If you are building a QString gradually and know in advance
1836 approximately how many characters the QString will contain, you
1837 can call reserve(), asking QString to preallocate a certain amount
1838 of memory. You can also call capacity() to find out how much
1839 memory the QString actually has allocated.
1840
1841 QString provides \l{STL-style iterators} (QString::const_iterator and
1842 QString::iterator). In practice, iterators are handy when working with
1843 generic algorithms provided by the C++ standard library.
1844
1845 \note Iterators over a QString, and references to individual characters
1846 within one, cannot be relied on to remain valid when any non-\c{const}
1847 method of the QString is called. Accessing such an iterator or reference
1848 after the call to a non-\c{const} method leads to undefined behavior. When
1849 stability for iterator-like functionality is required, you should use
1850 indexes instead of iterators as they are not tied to QString's internal
1851 state and thus do not get invalidated.
1852
1853 \note Due to \l{implicit sharing}, the first non-\c{const} operator or
1854 function used on a given QString may cause it to, internally, perform a deep
1855 copy of its data. This invalidates all iterators over the string and
1856 references to individual characters within it. After the first non-\c{const}
1857 operator, operations that modify QString may completely (in case of
1858 reallocation) or partially invalidate iterators and references, but other
1859 methods (such as begin() or end()) will not. Accessing an iterator or
1860 reference after it has been invalidated leads to undefined behavior.
1861
1862 A frequent requirement is to remove whitespace characters from a
1863 string ('\\n', '\\t', ' ', etc.). If you want to remove whitespace
1864 from both ends of a QString, use the trimmed() function. If you
1865 want to remove whitespace from both ends and replace multiple
1866 consecutive whitespaces with a single space character within the
1867 string, use simplified().
1868
1869 If you want to find all occurrences of a particular character or
1870 substring in a QString, use the indexOf() or lastIndexOf()
1871 functions. The former searches forward starting from a given index
1872 position, the latter searches backward. Both return the index
1873 position of the character or substring if they find it; otherwise,
1874 they return -1. For example, here is a typical loop that finds all
1875 occurrences of a particular substring:
1876
1877 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 6
1878
1879 QString provides many functions for converting numbers into
1880 strings and strings into numbers. See the arg() functions, the
1881 setNum() functions, the number() static functions, and the
1882 toInt(), toDouble(), and similar functions.
1883
1884 To get an upper- or lowercase version of a string use toUpper() or
1885 toLower().
1886
1887 Lists of strings are handled by the QStringList class. You can
1888 split a string into a list of strings using the split() function,
1889 and join a list of strings into a single string with an optional
1890 separator using QStringList::join(). You can obtain a list of
1891 strings from a string list that contain a particular substring or
1892 that match a particular QRegularExpression using the QStringList::filter()
1893 function.
1894
1895 \section1 Querying String Data
1896
1897 If you want to see if a QString starts or ends with a particular
1898 substring use startsWith() or endsWith(). If you simply want to
1899 check whether a QString contains a particular character or
1900 substring, use the contains() function. If you want to find out
1901 how many times a particular character or substring occurs in the
1902 string, use count().
1903
1904 To obtain a pointer to the actual character data, call data() or
1905 constData(). These functions return a pointer to the beginning of
1906 the QChar data. The pointer is guaranteed to remain valid until a
1907 non-\c{const} function is called on the QString.
1908
1909 \section2 Comparing Strings
1910
1911 QStrings can be compared using overloaded operators such as \l
1912 operator<(), \l operator<=(), \l operator==(), \l operator>=(),
1913 and so on. Note that the comparison is based exclusively on the
1914 numeric Unicode values of the characters. It is very fast, but is
1915 not what a human would expect; the QString::localeAwareCompare()
1916 function is usually a better choice for sorting user-interface
1917 strings, when such a comparison is available.
1918
1919 On Unix-like platforms (including Linux, \macos and iOS), when Qt
1920 is linked with the ICU library (which it usually is), its
1921 locale-aware sorting is used. Otherwise, on \macos and iOS, \l
1922 localeAwareCompare() compares according the "Order for sorted
1923 lists" setting in the International preferences panel. On other
1924 Unix-like systems without ICU, the comparison falls back to the
1925 system library's \c strcoll(),
1926
1927 \section1 Converting Between Encoded Strings Data and QString
1928
1929 QString provides the following three functions that return a
1930 \c{const char *} version of the string as QByteArray: toUtf8(),
1931 toLatin1(), and toLocal8Bit().
1932
1933 \list
1934 \li toLatin1() returns a Latin-1 (ISO 8859-1) encoded 8-bit string.
1935 \li toUtf8() returns a UTF-8 encoded 8-bit string. UTF-8 is a
1936 superset of US-ASCII (ANSI X3.4-1986) that supports the entire
1937 Unicode character set through multibyte sequences.
1938 \li toLocal8Bit() returns an 8-bit string using the system's local
1939 encoding. This is the same as toUtf8() on Unix systems.
1940 \endlist
1941
1942 To convert from one of these encodings, QString provides
1943 fromLatin1(), fromUtf8(), and fromLocal8Bit(). Other
1944 encodings are supported through the QStringEncoder and QStringDecoder
1945 classes.
1946
1947 As mentioned above, QString provides a lot of functions and
1948 operators that make it easy to interoperate with \c{const char *}
1949 strings. But this functionality is a double-edged sword: It makes
1950 QString more convenient to use if all strings are US-ASCII or
1951 Latin-1, but there is always the risk that an implicit conversion
1952 from or to \c{const char *} is done using the wrong 8-bit
1953 encoding. To minimize these risks, you can turn off these implicit
1954 conversions by defining some of the following preprocessor symbols:
1955
1956 \list
1957 \li \l QT_NO_CAST_FROM_ASCII disables automatic conversions from
1958 C string literals and pointers to Unicode.
1959 \li \l QT_RESTRICTED_CAST_FROM_ASCII allows automatic conversions
1960 from C characters and character arrays, but disables automatic
1961 conversions from character pointers to Unicode.
1962 \li \l QT_NO_CAST_TO_ASCII disables automatic conversion from QString
1963 to C strings.
1964 \endlist
1965
1966 You then need to explicitly call fromUtf8(), fromLatin1(),
1967 or fromLocal8Bit() to construct a QString from an
1968 8-bit string, or use the lightweight QLatin1StringView class, for
1969 example:
1970
1971 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 1
1972
1973 Similarly, you must call toLatin1(), toUtf8(), or
1974 toLocal8Bit() explicitly to convert the QString to an 8-bit
1975 string.
1976
1977 \table 100 %
1978 \header
1979 \li Note for C Programmers
1980
1981 \row
1982 \li
1983 Due to C++'s type system and the fact that QString is
1984 \l{implicitly shared}, QStrings may be treated like \c{int}s or
1985 other basic types. For example:
1986
1987 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 7
1988
1989 The \c result variable, is a normal variable allocated on the
1990 stack. When \c return is called, and because we're returning by
1991 value, the copy constructor is called and a copy of the string is
1992 returned. No actual copying takes place thanks to the implicit
1993 sharing.
1994
1995 \endtable
1996
1997 \section1 Distinction Between Null and Empty Strings
1998
1999 For historical reasons, QString distinguishes between a null
2000 string and an empty string. A \e null string is a string that is
2001 initialized using QString's default constructor or by passing
2002 (\c{const char *})0 to the constructor. An \e empty string is any
2003 string with size 0. A null string is always empty, but an empty
2004 string isn't necessarily null:
2005
2006 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 8
2007
2008 All functions except isNull() treat null strings the same as empty
2009 strings. For example, toUtf8().constData() returns a valid pointer
2010 (\e not nullptr) to a '\\0' character for a null string. We
2011 recommend that you always use the isEmpty() function and avoid isNull().
2012
2013 \section1 Number Formats
2014
2015 When a QString::arg() \c{'%'} format specifier includes the \c{'L'} locale
2016 qualifier, and the base is ten (its default), the default locale is
2017 used. This can be set using \l{QLocale::setDefault()}. For more refined
2018 control of localized string representations of numbers, see
2019 QLocale::toString(). All other number formatting done by QString follows the
2020 C locale's representation of numbers.
2021
2022 When QString::arg() applies left-padding to numbers, the fill character
2023 \c{'0'} is treated specially. If the number is negative, its minus sign will
2024 appear before the zero-padding. If the field is localized, the
2025 locale-appropriate zero character is used in place of \c{'0'}. For
2026 floating-point numbers, this special treatment only applies if the number is
2027 finite.
2028
2029 \section2 Floating-point Formats
2030
2031 In member functions (e.g., arg(), number()) that represent floating-point
2032 numbers (\c float or \c double) as strings, the form of display can be
2033 controlled by a choice of \e format and \e precision, whose meanings are as
2034 for \l {QLocale::toString(double, char, int)}.
2035
2036 If the selected \e format includes an exponent, localized forms follow the
2037 locale's convention on digits in the exponent. For non-localized formatting,
2038 the exponent shows its sign and includes at least two digits, left-padding
2039 with zero if needed.
2040
2041 \section1 More Efficient String Construction
2042
2043 Many strings are known at compile time. But the trivial
2044 constructor QString("Hello"), will copy the contents of the string,
2045 treating the contents as Latin-1. To avoid this one can use the
2046 QStringLiteral macro to directly create the required data at compile
2047 time. Constructing a QString out of the literal does then not cause
2048 any overhead at runtime.
2049
2050 A slightly less efficient way is to use QLatin1StringView. This class wraps
2051 a C string literal, precalculates it length at compile time and can
2052 then be used for faster comparison with QStrings and conversion to
2053 QStrings than a regular C string literal.
2054
2055 Using the QString \c{'+'} operator, it is easy to construct a
2056 complex string from multiple substrings. You will often write code
2057 like this:
2058
2059 \snippet qstring/stringbuilder.cpp 0
2060
2061 There is nothing wrong with either of these string constructions,
2062 but there are a few hidden inefficiencies. Beginning with Qt 4.6,
2063 you can eliminate them.
2064
2065 First, multiple uses of the \c{'+'} operator usually means
2066 multiple memory allocations. When concatenating \e{n} substrings,
2067 where \e{n > 2}, there can be as many as \e{n - 1} calls to the
2068 memory allocator.
2069
2070 In 4.6, an internal template class \c{QStringBuilder} has been
2071 added along with a few helper functions. This class is marked
2072 internal and does not appear in the documentation, because you
2073 aren't meant to instantiate it in your code. Its use will be
2074 automatic, as described below. The class is found in
2075 \c {src/corelib/tools/qstringbuilder.cpp} if you want to have a
2076 look at it.
2077
2078 \c{QStringBuilder} uses expression templates and reimplements the
2079 \c{'%'} operator so that when you use \c{'%'} for string
2080 concatenation instead of \c{'+'}, multiple substring
2081 concatenations will be postponed until the final result is about
2082 to be assigned to a QString. At this point, the amount of memory
2083 required for the final result is known. The memory allocator is
2084 then called \e{once} to get the required space, and the substrings
2085 are copied into it one by one.
2086
2087 Additional efficiency is gained by inlining and reduced reference
2088 counting (the QString created from a \c{QStringBuilder} typically
2089 has a ref count of 1, whereas QString::append() needs an extra
2090 test).
2091
2092 There are two ways you can access this improved method of string
2093 construction. The straightforward way is to include
2094 \c{QStringBuilder} wherever you want to use it, and use the
2095 \c{'%'} operator instead of \c{'+'} when concatenating strings:
2096
2097 \snippet qstring/stringbuilder.cpp 5
2098
2099 A more global approach which is the most convenient but
2100 not entirely source compatible, is to this define in your
2101 .pro file:
2102
2103 \snippet qstring/stringbuilder.cpp 3
2104
2105 and the \c{'+'} will automatically be performed as the
2106 \c{QStringBuilder} \c{'%'} everywhere.
2107
2108 \section1 Maximum Size and Out-of-memory Conditions
2109
2110 The maximum size of QString depends on the architecture. Most 64-bit
2111 systems can allocate more than 2 GB of memory, with a typical limit
2112 of 2^63 bytes. The actual value also depends on the overhead required for
2113 managing the data block. As a result, you can expect the maximum size
2114 of 2 GB minus overhead on 32-bit platforms, and 2^63 bytes minus overhead
2115 on 64-bit platforms. The number of elements that can be stored in a
2116 QString is this maximum size divided by the size of QChar.
2117
2118 When memory allocation fails, QString throws a \c std::bad_alloc
2119 exception if the application was compiled with exception support.
2120 Out of memory conditions in Qt containers are the only case where Qt
2121 will throw exceptions. If exceptions are disabled, then running out of
2122 memory is undefined behavior.
2123
2124 Note that the operating system may impose further limits on applications
2125 holding a lot of allocated memory, especially large, contiguous blocks.
2126 Such considerations, the configuration of such behavior or any mitigation
2127 are outside the scope of the Qt API.
2128
2129 \sa fromRawData(), QChar, QStringView, QLatin1StringView, QByteArray
2130*/
2131

2372/*! \fn QString QString::fromStdString(const std::string &str)
2373
2374 Returns a copy of the \a str string. The given string is converted
2375 to Unicode using the fromUtf8() function.
2376
2377 \sa fromLatin1(), fromLocal8Bit(), fromUtf8(), QByteArray::fromStdString()
2378*/
2379

2381

2383 to be encoded in utf16 if the size of wchar_t is 2 bytes (e.g. on
2384 windows) and ucs4 if the size of wchar_t is 4 bytes (most Unix

2391/*! \fn QString QString::fromWCharArray(const wchar_t *string, qsizetype size)
2392 \since 4.2
2393
2394 Returns a copy of the \a string, where the encoding of \a string depends on
2395 the size of wchar. If wchar is 4 bytes, the \a string is interpreted as
2396 UCS-4, if wchar is 2 bytes it is interpreted as UTF-16.
2397
2398 If \a size is -1 (default), the \a string must be '\\0'-terminated.
2399
2400 \sa fromUtf16(), fromLatin1(), fromLocal8Bit(), fromUtf8(), fromUcs4(),
2401 fromStdWString()

2404/*! \fn std::wstring QString::toStdWString() const
2405
2406 Returns a std::wstring object with the data contained in this
2407 QString. The std::wstring is encoded in utf16 on platforms where
2408 wchar_t is 2 bytes wide (e.g. windows) and in ucs4 on platforms
2409 where wchar_t is 4 bytes wide (most Unix systems).
2410
2411 This method is mostly useful to pass a QString to a function
2412 that accepts a std::wstring object.
2413
2414 \sa utf16(), toLatin1(), toUtf8(), toLocal8Bit(), toStdU16String(),
2415 toStdU32String()
2416*/
2417
2418qsizetype QString::toUcs4_helper(const ushort *uc, qsizetype length, uint *out)
2419{
2420 qsizetype count = 0;
2421
2422 QStringIterator i(QStringView(uc, length));
2423 while (i.hasNext())
2424 out[count++] = i.next();
2425
2426 return count;
2427}

2434 wchar_t is 2 bytes wide (e.g. windows) and in UCS-4 on platforms

2449/*! \fn QString::QString(const QString &other)
2450
2451 Constructs a copy of \a other.
2452
2453 This operation takes \l{constant time}, because QString is
2454 \l{implicitly shared}. This makes returning a QString from a
2455 function very fast. If a shared instance is modified, it will be
2456 copied (copy-on-write), and that takes \l{linear time}.
2457
2458 \sa operator=()
2459*/
2460
2461/*!
2462 Constructs a string initialized with the first \a size characters
2463 of the QChar array \a unicode.
2464
2465 If \a unicode is 0, a null string is constructed.
2466
2467 If \a size is negative, \a unicode is assumed to point to a \\0'-terminated
2468 array and its length is determined dynamically. The terminating
2469 null character is not considered part of the string.
2470
2471 QString makes a deep copy of the string data. The unicode data is copied as
2472 is and the Byte Order Mark is preserved if present.
2473
2474 \sa fromRawData()
2475*/
2476QString::QString(const QChar *unicode, qsizetype size)
2477{
2478 if (!unicode) {
2479 d.clear();
2480 } else {
2481 if (size < 0) {
2482 size = 0;
2483 while (!unicode[size].isNull())
2484 ++size;
2485 }
2486 if (!size) {
2487 d = DataPointer::fromRawData(rawData: &_empty, length: 0);
2488 } else {
2489 d = DataPointer(Data::allocate(capacity: size), size);
2490 Q_CHECK_PTR(d.data());
2491 memcpy(dest: d.data(), src: unicode, n: size * sizeof(QChar));
2492 d.data()[size] = '\0';
2493 }
2494 }
2495}

2497/*!
2498 Constructs a string of the given \a size with every character set
2499 to \a ch.
2500
2501 \sa fill()
2502*/
2503QString::QString(qsizetype size, QChar ch)
2504{
2505 if (size <= 0) {
2506 d = DataPointer::fromRawData(rawData: &_empty, length: 0);
2507 } else {
2508 d = DataPointer(Data::allocate(capacity: size), size);
2509 Q_CHECK_PTR(d.data());
2510 d.data()[size] = '\0';
2511 char16_t *b = d.data();
2512 char16_t *e = d.data() + size;
2513 const char16_t value = ch.unicode();
2514 std::fill(b, e, value);
2515 }
2516}

2611/*!
2612 Sets the size of the string to \a size characters.
2613
2614 If \a size is greater than the current size, the string is
2615 extended to make it \a size characters long with the extra
2616 characters added to the end. The new characters are uninitialized.
2617
2618 If \a size is less than the current size, characters beyond position
2619 \a size are excluded from the string.
2620
2621 \note While resize() will grow the capacity if needed, it never shrinks
2622 capacity. To shed excess capacity, use squeeze().
2623
2624 Example:
2625
2626 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 45
2627
2628 If you want to append a certain number of identical characters to
2629 the string, use the \l {QString::}{resize(qsizetype, QChar)} overload.
2630
2631 If you want to expand the string so that it reaches a certain
2632 width and fill the new positions with a particular character, use
2633 the leftJustified() function:
2634
2635 If \a size is negative, it is equivalent to passing zero.
2636
2637 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 47
2638
2639 \sa truncate(), reserve(), squeeze()
2640*/
2641
2642void QString::resize(qsizetype size)
2643{
2644 if (size < 0)
2645 size = 0;
2646
2647 const auto capacityAtEnd = capacity() - d.freeSpaceAtBegin();
2648 if (d->needsDetach() || size > capacityAtEnd)
2649 reallocData(alloc: size, option: QArrayData::Grow);
2650 d.size = size;
2651 if (d->allocatedCapacity())
2652 d.data()[size] = u'\0';
2653}
2654
2655/*!
2656 \overload
2657 \since 5.7
2658
2659 Unlike \l {QString::}{resize(qsizetype)}, this overload
2660 initializes the new characters to \a fillChar:
2661
2662 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 46
2663*/
2664
2665void QString::resize(qsizetype newSize, QChar fillChar)
2666{
2667 const qsizetype oldSize = size();
2668 resize(size: newSize);
2669 const qsizetype difference = size() - oldSize;
2670 if (difference > 0)
2671 std::fill_n(d.data() + oldSize, difference, fillChar.unicode());
2672}
