2674/*! \fn qsizetype QString::capacity() const
2675
2676 Returns the maximum number of characters that can be stored in
2677 the string without forcing a reallocation.
2678
2679 The sole purpose of this function is to provide a means of fine
2680 tuning QString's memory usage. In general, you will rarely ever
2681 need to call this function. If you want to know how many
2682 characters are in the string, call size().
2683
2684 \note a statically allocated string will report a capacity of 0,
2685 even if it's not empty.
2686
2687 \note The free space position in the allocated memory block is undefined. In
2688 other words, one should not assume that the free memory is always located
2689 after the initialized elements.
2690
2691 \sa reserve(), squeeze()
2692*/
2693
2694/*!
2695 \fn void QString::reserve(qsizetype size)
2696
2697 Ensures the string has space for at least \a size characters.
2698
2699 If you know in advance how large the string will be, you can call this
2700 function to save repeated reallocation in the course of building it.
2701 This can improve performance when building a string incrementally.
2702 A long sequence of operations that add to a string may trigger several
2703 reallocations, the last of which may leave you with significantly more
2704 space than you really need, which is less efficient than doing a single
2705 allocation of the right size at the start.
2706
2707 If in doubt about how much space shall be needed, it is usually better to
2708 use an upper bound as \a size, or a high estimate of the most likely size,
2709 if a strict upper bound would be much bigger than this. If \a size is an
2710 underestimate, the string will grow as needed once the reserved size is
2711 exceeded, which may lead to a larger allocation than your best overestimate
2712 would have and will slow the operation that triggers it.
2713
2714 \warning reserve() reserves memory but does not change the size of the
2715 string. Accessing data beyond the end of the string is undefined behavior.
2716 If you need to access memory beyond the current end of the string,
2717 use resize().
2718
2719 This function is useful for code that needs to build up a long
2720 string and wants to avoid repeated reallocation. In this example,
2721 we want to add to the string until some condition is \c true, and
2722 we're fairly sure that size is large enough to make a call to
2723 reserve() worthwhile:
2724
2725 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 44
2726
2727 \sa squeeze(), capacity(), resize()
2728*/
2729
2730/*!
2731 \fn void QString::squeeze()
2732
2733 Releases any memory not required to store the character data.
2734
2735 The sole purpose of this function is to provide a means of fine
2736 tuning QString's memory usage. In general, you will rarely ever
2737 need to call this function.
2738
2739 \sa reserve(), capacity()
2740*/
2741
2742void QString::reallocData(qsizetype alloc, QArrayData::AllocationOption option)
2743{
2744 if (!alloc) {
2745 d = DataPointer::fromRawData(rawData: &_empty, length: 0);
2746 return;
2747 }
2748
2749 // don't use reallocate path when reducing capacity and there's free space
2750 // at the beginning: might shift data pointer outside of allocated space
2751 const bool cannotUseReallocate = d.freeSpaceAtBegin() > 0;
2752
2753 if (d->needsDetach() || cannotUseReallocate) {
2754 DataPointer dd(Data::allocate(capacity: alloc, option), qMin(a: alloc, b: d.size));
2755 Q_CHECK_PTR(dd.data());
2756 if (dd.size > 0)
2757 ::memcpy(dest: dd.data(), src: d.data(), n: dd.size * sizeof(QChar));
2758 dd.data()[dd.size] = 0;
2759 d = dd;
2760 } else {
2761 d->reallocate(alloc, option);
2762 }
2763}
2764
2765void QString::reallocGrowData(qsizetype n)
2766{
2767 if (!n) // expected to always allocate
2768 n = 1;
2769
2770 if (d->needsDetach()) {
2771 DataPointer dd(DataPointer::allocateGrow(from: d, n, position: QArrayData::GrowsAtEnd));
2772 Q_CHECK_PTR(dd.data());
2773 dd->copyAppend(b: d.data(), e: d.data() + d.size);
2774 dd.data()[dd.size] = 0;
2775 d = dd;
2776 } else {
2777 d->reallocate(alloc: d.constAllocatedCapacity() + n, option: QArrayData::Grow);
2778 }
2779}

2933/*!
2934 \fn QString &QString::insert(qsizetype position, QLatin1StringView str)
2935 \overload insert()
2936
2937 Inserts the Latin-1 string viewed by \a str at the given index \a position.
2938
2939 \include qstring.cpp string-grow-at-insertion
2940*/
2941QString &QString::insert(qsizetype i, QLatin1StringView str)
2942{
2943 const char *s = str.latin1();
2944 if (i < 0 || !s || !(*s))
2945 return *this;
2946
2947 qsizetype len = str.size();
2948 qsizetype difference = 0;
2949 if (Q_UNLIKELY(i > size()))
2950 difference = i - size();
2951 d.detachAndGrow(where: Data::GrowsAtEnd, n: difference + len, data: nullptr, old: nullptr);
2952 Q_CHECK_PTR(d.data());
2953 d->copyAppend(n: difference, t: u' ');
2954 d.size += len;
2955
2956 ::memmove(dest: d.data() + i + len, src: d.data() + i, n: (d.size - i - len) * sizeof(QChar));
2957 qt_from_latin1(dst: d.data() + i, str: s, size: size_t(len));
2958 d.data()[d.size] = u'\0';
2959 return *this;
2960}

2980/*!
2981 \fn QString& QString::insert(qsizetype position, const QChar *unicode, qsizetype size)
2982 \overload insert()
2983
2984 Inserts the first \a size characters of the QChar array \a unicode
2985 at the given index \a position in the string.
2986
2987 This string grows to accommodate the insertion. If \a position is beyond
2988 the end of the string, space characters are appended to the string to reach
2989 this \a position, followed by \a size characters of the QChar array
2990 \a unicode.
2991*/
2992QString& QString::insert(qsizetype i, const QChar *unicode, qsizetype size)
2993{
2994 if (i < 0 || size <= 0)
2995 return *this;
2996
2997 const char16_t *s = reinterpret_cast<const char16_t *>(unicode);
2998
2999 // handle this specially, as QArrayDataOps::insert() doesn't handle out of
3000 // bounds positions
3001 if (i >= d->size) {
3002 // In case when data points into the range or is == *this, we need to
3003 // defer a call to free() so that it comes after we copied the data from
3004 // the old memory:
3005 DataPointer detached{}; // construction is free
3006 d.detachAndGrow(where: Data::GrowsAtEnd, n: (i - d.size) + size, data: &s, old: &detached);
3007 Q_CHECK_PTR(d.data());
3008 d->copyAppend(n: i - d->size, t: u' ');
3009 d->copyAppend(b: s, e: s + size);
3010 d.data()[d.size] = u'\0';
3011 return *this;
3012 }
3013
3014 if (!d->needsDetach() && QtPrivate::q_points_into_range(p: s, b: d.data(), e: d.data() + d.size))
3015 return insert(i, v: QStringView{QVarLengthArray(s, s + size)});
3016
3017 d->insert(i, data: s, n: size);
3018 d.data()[d.size] = u'\0';
3019 return *this;
3020}

3040/*!
3041 Appends the string \a str onto the end of this string.

3045 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 9
3046
3047 This is the same as using the insert() function:

3063 } else if (str.size()) {

3065 }

3070/*!

3073 \since 6.0
3074
3075 Appends the given string view \a v to this string and returns the result.

3078/*!
3079 \overload append()
3080 \since 5.0
3081
3082 Appends \a len characters from the QChar array \a str to this string.
3083*/
3084QString &QString::append(const QChar *str, qsizetype len)
3085{
3086 if (str && len > 0) {
3087 static_assert(sizeof(QChar) == sizeof(char16_t), "Unexpected difference in sizes");
3088 // the following should be safe as QChar uses char16_t as underlying data
3089 const char16_t *char16String = reinterpret_cast<const char16_t *>(str);
3090 d->growAppend(b: char16String, e: char16String + len);
3091 d.data()[d.size] = u'\0';
3092 }
3093 return *this;
3094}

3100*/

3102{

3104 const qsizetype len = str.size();
3105 const char *s = str.latin1();

3107 qt_from_latin1(dst: i, str: s, size: size_t(len));
3108 return dst + len;
3109 };
3110
3111 append_helper(self&: *this, view: str, appendToUtf16: appendUtf16);
3112 return *this;
3113}

3249/*!
3250 \fn QString &QString::remove(qsizetype position, qsizetype n)
3251
3252 Removes \a n characters from the string, starting at the given \a
3253 position index, and returns a reference to the string.
3254
3255 If the specified \a position index is within the string, but \a
3256 position + \a n is beyond the end of the string, the string is
3257 truncated at the specified \a position.
3258
3259 If \a n is <= 0 nothing is changed.
3260
3261 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 37
3262
3263//! [shrinking-erase]
3264 Element removal will preserve the string's capacity and not reduce the
3265 amount of allocated memory. To shed extra capacity and free as much memory
3266 as possible, call squeeze() after the last change to the string's size.
3267//! [shrinking-erase]
3268
3269 \sa insert(), replace()
3270*/
3271QString &QString::remove(qsizetype pos, qsizetype len)
3272{
3273 if (pos < 0) // count from end of string
3274 pos += size();
3275
3276 if (size_t(pos) >= size_t(size()) || len <= 0)
3277 return *this;
3278
3279 len = std::min(a: len, b: size() - pos);
3280
3281 if (!d->isShared()) {
3282 d->erase(b: d.begin() + pos, n: len);
3283 d.data()[d.size] = u'\0';
3284 } else {
3285 // TODO: either reserve "size()", which is bigger than needed, or
3286 // modify the shrinking-erase docs of this method (since the size
3287 // of "copy" won't have any extra capacity any more)
3288 const qsizetype sz = size() - len;
3289 QString copy{sz, Qt::Uninitialized};
3290 auto begin = d.begin();
3291 auto toRemove_start = d.begin() + pos;
3292 copy.d->copyRanges(ranges: {{.begin: begin, .end: toRemove_start},
3293 {.begin: toRemove_start + len, .end: d.end()}});
3294 swap(other&: copy);
3295 }
3296 return *this;
3297}
3298
3299template<typename T>
3300static void removeStringImpl(QString &s, const T &needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
3301{
3302 const auto needleSize = needle.size();
3303 if (!needleSize)
3304 return;
3305
3306 // avoid detach if nothing to do:
3307 qsizetype i = s.indexOf(needle, 0, cs);
3308 if (i < 0)
3309 return;
3310
3311 QString::DataPointer &dptr = s.data_ptr();
3312 auto begin = dptr.begin();
3313 auto end = dptr.end();
3314
3315 auto copyFunc = [&](auto &dst) {
3316 auto src = begin + i + needleSize;
3317 while (src < end) {
3318 i = s.indexOf(needle, std::distance(begin, src), cs);
3319 auto hit = i == -1 ? end : begin + i;
3320 dst = std::copy(src, hit, dst);
3321 src = hit + needleSize;
3322 }
3323 return dst;
3324 };
3325
3326 if (!dptr->needsDetach()) {
3327 auto dst = begin + i;
3328 dst = copyFunc(dst);
3329 s.truncate(pos: std::distance(first: begin, last: dst));
3330 } else {
3331 QString copy{s.size(), Qt::Uninitialized};
3332 auto copy_begin = copy.begin();
3333 auto dst = std::copy(begin, begin + i, copy_begin); // Chunk before the first hit
3334 dst = copyFunc(dst);
3335 copy.resize(size: std::distance(first: copy_begin, last: dst));
3336 s.swap(other&: copy);
3337 }
3338}
3339
3340/*!
3341 Removes every occurrence of the given \a str string in this
3342 string, and returns a reference to this string.
3343
3344 \include qstring.qdocinc {search-comparison-case-sensitivity} {search}
3345
3346 This is the same as \c replace(str, "", cs).
3347
3348 \include qstring.cpp shrinking-erase
3349
3350 \sa replace()
3351*/
3352QString &QString::remove(const QString &str, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
3353{
3354 const auto s = str.d.data();
3355 if (QtPrivate::q_points_into_range(p: s, b: d.data(), e: d.data() + d.size))
3356 removeStringImpl(s&: *this, needle: QStringView{QVarLengthArray(s, s + str.size())}, cs);
3357 else
3358 removeStringImpl(s&: *this, needle: qToStringViewIgnoringNull(s: str), cs);
3359 return *this;
3360}

3362/*!
3363 \since 5.11

3371 This is the same as \c replace(str, "", cs).

3373 \include qstring.cpp shrinking-erase
3374
3375 \sa replace()
3376*/
3377QString &QString::remove(QLatin1StringView str, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
3378{
3379 removeStringImpl(s&: *this, needle: str, cs);
3380 return *this;
3381}

3416/*!
3417 Removes every occurrence of the character \a ch in this string, and
3418 returns a reference to this string.
3419
3420 \include qstring.qdocinc {search-comparison-case-sensitivity} {search}
3421
3422 Example:
3423
3424 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 38
3425
3426 This is the same as \c replace(ch, "", cs).
3427
3428 \include qstring.cpp shrinking-erase
3429
3430 \sa replace()
3431*/
3432QString &QString::remove(QChar ch, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
3433{
3434 const qsizetype idx = indexOf(c: ch, from: 0, cs);
3435 if (idx == -1)
3436 return *this;
3437
3438 const bool isCase = cs == Qt::CaseSensitive;
3439 ch = isCase ? ch : ch.toCaseFolded();
3440 auto match = [ch, isCase](QChar x) {
3441 return ch == (isCase ? x : x.toCaseFolded());
3442 };
3443
3444
3445 auto begin = d.begin();
3446 auto first_match = begin + idx;
3447 auto end = d.end();
3448 if (!d->isShared()) {
3449 auto it = std::remove_if(first: first_match, last: end, pred: match);
3450 d->erase(b: it, n: std::distance(first: it, last: end));
3451 d.data()[d.size] = u'\0';
3452 } else {
3453 // Instead of detaching, create a new string and copy all characters except for
3454 // the ones we're removing
3455 // TODO: size() is more than the needed since "copy" would be shorter
3456 QString copy{size(), Qt::Uninitialized};
3457 auto dst = copy.d.begin();
3458 auto it = std::copy(begin, first_match, dst); // Chunk before idx
3459 it = std::remove_copy_if(first: first_match + 1, last: end, result: it, pred: match);
3460 copy.d.size = std::distance(first: dst, last: it);
3461 copy.d.data()[copy.d.size] = u'\0';
3462 *this = copy;
3463 }
3464 return *this;
3465}

3512/*!
3513 \fn QString &QString::replace(qsizetype position, qsizetype n, const QChar *unicode, qsizetype size)
3514 \overload replace()

3516 first \a size characters of the QChar array \a unicode and returns a

3519QString &QString::replace(qsizetype pos, qsizetype len, const QChar *unicode, qsizetype size)
3520{

3522 return *this;
3523 if (len > this->size() - pos)
3524 len = this->size() - pos;
3525

3527 replace_helper(indices: &index, nIndices: 1, blen: len, after: unicode, alen: size);
3528 return *this;
3529}

3564
3565namespace { // helpers for replace and its helper:
3566QChar *textCopy(const QChar *start, qsizetype len)
3567{
3568 const size_t size = len * sizeof(QChar);
3569 QChar *const copy = static_cast<QChar *>(::malloc(size: size));
3570 Q_CHECK_PTR(copy);
3571 ::memcpy(dest: copy, src: start, n: size);
3572 return copy;
3573}
3574
3575static bool pointsIntoRange(const QChar *ptr, const char16_t *base, qsizetype len)
3576{
3577 const QChar *const start = reinterpret_cast<const QChar *>(base);
3578 const std::less<const QChar *> less;
3579 return !less(ptr, start) && less(ptr, start + len);
3580}
3581} // end namespace
3582
3583/*!
3584 \internal
3585 */
3586void QString::replace_helper(size_t *indices, qsizetype nIndices, qsizetype blen, const QChar *after, qsizetype alen)
3587{
3588 // Copy after if it lies inside our own d.b area (which we could
3589 // possibly invalidate via a realloc or modify by replacement).
3590 QChar *afterBuffer = nullptr;
3591 if (pointsIntoRange(ptr: after, base: d.data(), len: d.size)) // Use copy in place of vulnerable original:
3592 after = afterBuffer = textCopy(start: after, len: alen);
3593
3594 QT_TRY {
3595 if (blen == alen) {
3596 // replace in place
3597 detach();
3598 for (qsizetype i = 0; i < nIndices; ++i)
3599 memcpy(dest: d.data() + indices[i], src: after, n: alen * sizeof(QChar));
3600 } else if (alen < blen) {
3601 // replace from front
3602 detach();
3603 size_t to = indices[0];
3604 if (alen)
3605 memcpy(dest: d.data()+to, src: after, n: alen*sizeof(QChar));
3606 to += alen;
3607 size_t movestart = indices[0] + blen;
3608 for (qsizetype i = 1; i < nIndices; ++i) {
3609 qsizetype msize = indices[i] - movestart;
3610 if (msize > 0) {
3611 memmove(dest: d.data() + to, src: d.data() + movestart, n: msize * sizeof(QChar));
3612 to += msize;
3613 }
3614 if (alen) {
3615 memcpy(dest: d.data() + to, src: after, n: alen * sizeof(QChar));
3616 to += alen;
3617 }
3618 movestart = indices[i] + blen;
3619 }
3620 qsizetype msize = d.size - movestart;
3621 if (msize > 0)
3622 memmove(dest: d.data() + to, src: d.data() + movestart, n: msize * sizeof(QChar));
3623 resize(size: d.size - nIndices*(blen-alen));
3624 } else {
3625 // replace from back
3626 qsizetype adjust = nIndices*(alen-blen);
3627 qsizetype newLen = d.size + adjust;
3628 qsizetype moveend = d.size;
3629 resize(size: newLen);
3630
3631 while (nIndices) {
3632 --nIndices;
3633 qsizetype movestart = indices[nIndices] + blen;
3634 qsizetype insertstart = indices[nIndices] + nIndices*(alen-blen);
3635 qsizetype moveto = insertstart + alen;
3636 memmove(dest: d.data() + moveto, src: d.data() + movestart,
3637 n: (moveend - movestart)*sizeof(QChar));
3638 memcpy(dest: d.data() + insertstart, src: after, n: alen * sizeof(QChar));
3639 moveend = movestart-blen;
3640 }
3641 }
3642 } QT_CATCH(const std::bad_alloc &) {
3643 ::free(ptr: afterBuffer);
3644 QT_RETHROW;
3645 }
3646 ::free(ptr: afterBuffer);
3647}
3648
3649/*!
3650 \since 4.5
3651 \overload replace()
3652
3653 Replaces each occurrence in this string of the first \a blen
3654 characters of \a before with the first \a alen characters of \a
3655 after and returns a reference to this string.
3656
3657 \include qstring.qdocinc {search-comparison-case-sensitivity} {search}
3658*/
3659QString &QString::replace(const QChar *before, qsizetype blen,
3660 const QChar *after, qsizetype alen,
3661 Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
3662{
3663 if (d.size == 0) {
3664 if (blen)
3665 return *this;
3666 } else {
3667 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive && before == after && blen == alen)
3668 return *this;
3669 }
3670 if (alen == 0 && blen == 0)
3671 return *this;
3672 if (alen == 1 && blen == 1)
3673 return replace(before: *before, after: *after, cs);
3674
3675 QStringMatcher matcher(before, blen, cs);
3676 QChar *beforeBuffer = nullptr, *afterBuffer = nullptr;
3677
3678 qsizetype index = 0;
3679 while (1) {
3680 size_t indices[1024];
3681 size_t pos = 0;
3682 while (pos < 1024) {
3683 index = matcher.indexIn(str: *this, from: index);
3684 if (index == -1)
3685 break;
3686 indices[pos++] = index;
3687 if (blen) // Step over before:
3688 index += blen;
3689 else // Only count one instance of empty between any two characters:
3690 index++;
3691 }
3692 if (!pos) // Nothing to replace
3693 break;
3694
3695 if (Q_UNLIKELY(index != -1)) {
3696 /*
3697 We're about to change data, that before and after might point
3698 into, and we'll need that data for our next batch of indices.
3699 */
3700 if (!afterBuffer && pointsIntoRange(ptr: after, base: d.data(), len: d.size))
3701 after = afterBuffer = textCopy(start: after, len: alen);
3702
3703 if (!beforeBuffer && pointsIntoRange(ptr: before, base: d.data(), len: d.size)) {
3704 beforeBuffer = textCopy(start: before, len: blen);
3705 matcher = QStringMatcher(beforeBuffer, blen, cs);
3706 }
3707 }
3708
3709 replace_helper(indices, nIndices: pos, blen, after, alen);
3710
3711 if (Q_LIKELY(index == -1)) // Nothing left to replace
3712 break;
3713 // The call to replace_helper just moved what index points at:
3714 index += pos*(alen-blen);
3715 }
3716 ::free(ptr: afterBuffer);
3717 ::free(ptr: beforeBuffer);
3718
3719 return *this;
3720}
3721
3722/*!
3723 \overload replace()
3724 Replaces every occurrence of the character \a ch in the string with
3725 \a after and returns a reference to this string.
3726
3727 \include qstring.qdocinc {search-comparison-case-sensitivity} {search}
3728*/
3729QString& QString::replace(QChar ch, const QString &after, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
3730{
3731 if (after.size() == 0)
3732 return remove(ch, cs);
3733
3734 if (after.size() == 1)
3735 return replace(before: ch, after: after.front(), cs);
3736
3737 if (size() == 0)
3738 return *this;
3739
3740 char16_t cc = (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive ? ch.unicode() : ch.toCaseFolded().unicode());
3741
3742 qsizetype index = 0;
3743 while (1) {
3744 size_t indices[1024];
3745 size_t pos = 0;
3746 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive) {
3747 while (pos < 1024 && index < size()) {
3748 if (d.data()[index] == cc)
3749 indices[pos++] = index;
3750 index++;
3751 }
3752 } else {
3753 while (pos < 1024 && index < size()) {
3754 if (QChar::toCaseFolded(ucs4: d.data()[index]) == cc)
3755 indices[pos++] = index;
3756 index++;
3757 }
3758 }
3759 if (!pos) // Nothing to replace
3760 break;
3761
3762 replace_helper(indices, nIndices: pos, blen: 1, after: after.constData(), alen: after.size());
3763
3764 if (Q_LIKELY(index == size())) // Nothing left to replace
3765 break;
3766 // The call to replace_helper just moved what index points at:
3767 index += pos*(after.size() - 1);
3768 }
3769 return *this;
3770}
3771
3772/*!
3773 \overload replace()
3774 Replaces every occurrence of the character \a before with the
3775 character \a after and returns a reference to this string.
3776
3777 \include qstring.qdocinc {search-comparison-case-sensitivity} {search}
3778*/
3779QString& QString::replace(QChar before, QChar after, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
3780{
3781 if (d.size) {
3782 const qsizetype idx = indexOf(c: before, from: 0, cs);
3783 if (idx != -1) {
3784 detach();
3785 const char16_t a = after.unicode();
3786 char16_t *i = d.data();
3787 char16_t *const e = i + d.size;
3788 i += idx;
3789 *i = a;
3790 ++i;
3791 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive) {
3792 const char16_t toReplace = before.unicode();
3793 std::replace(first: i, last: e, old_value: toReplace, new_value: a);
3794 } else {
3795 const char16_t toReplace = foldCase(ch: before.unicode());
3796 auto match = [toReplace](const char16_t c) {
3797 return foldAndCompare(a: c, b: toReplace);
3798 };
3799 std::replace_if(first: i, last: e, pred: match, new_value: a);
3800 }
3801 }
3802 }
3803 return *this;
3804}
3805
3806/*!
3807 \since 4.5
3808 \overload replace()
3809
3810 Replaces every occurrence in this string of the Latin-1 string viewed
3811 by \a before with the Latin-1 string viewed by \a after, and returns a
3812 reference to this string.
3813
3814 \include qstring.qdocinc {search-comparison-case-sensitivity} {search}
3815
3816 \note The text is not rescanned after a replacement.
3817*/
3818QString &QString::replace(QLatin1StringView before, QLatin1StringView after, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
3819{
3820 const qsizetype alen = after.size();
3821 const qsizetype blen = before.size();
3822 if (blen == 1 && alen == 1)
3823 return replace(before: before.front(), after: after.front(), cs);
3824
3825 QVarLengthArray<char16_t> a = qt_from_latin1_to_qvla(str: after);
3826 QVarLengthArray<char16_t> b = qt_from_latin1_to_qvla(str: before);
3827 return replace(before: (const QChar *)b.data(), blen, after: (const QChar *)a.data(), alen, cs);
3828}

4432 \since 5.0
4433
4434 Replaces every occurrence of the regular expression \a re in the
4435 string with \a after. Returns a reference to the string. For
4436 example:
4437
4438 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 87
4439
4440 For regular expressions containing capturing groups,
4441 occurrences of \b{\\1}, \b{\\2}, ..., in \a after are replaced
4442 with the string captured by the corresponding capturing group.
4443
4444 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 88
4445
4446 \sa indexOf(), lastIndexOf(), remove(), QRegularExpression, QRegularExpressionMatch
4447*/
4448QString &QString::replace(const QRegularExpression &re, const QString &after)
4449{
4450 if (!re.isValid()) {
4451 qtWarnAboutInvalidRegularExpression(pattern: re.pattern(), where: "QString::replace");
4452 return *this;
4453 }
4454
4455 const QString copy(*this);
4456 QRegularExpressionMatchIterator iterator = re.globalMatch(subject: copy);
4457 if (!iterator.hasNext()) // no matches at all
4458 return *this;
4459
4460 reallocData(alloc: d.size, option: QArrayData::KeepSize);
4461
4462 qsizetype numCaptures = re.captureCount();
4463
4464 // 1. build the backreferences list, holding where the backreferences
4465 // are in the replacement string
4466 QList<QStringCapture> backReferences;
4467 const qsizetype al = after.size();
4468 const QChar *ac = after.unicode();
4469
4470 for (qsizetype i = 0; i < al - 1; i++) {
4471 if (ac[i] == u'\\') {
4472 int no = ac[i + 1].digitValue();
4473 if (no > 0 && no <= numCaptures) {
4474 QStringCapture backReference;
4475 backReference.pos = i;
4476 backReference.len = 2;
4477
4478 if (i < al - 2) {
4479 int secondDigit = ac[i + 2].digitValue();
4480 if (secondDigit != -1 && ((no * 10) + secondDigit) <= numCaptures) {
4481 no = (no * 10) + secondDigit;
4482 ++backReference.len;
4483 }
4484 }
4485
4486 backReference.no = no;
4487 backReferences.append(t: backReference);
4488 }
4489 }
4490 }
4491
4492 // 2. iterate on the matches. For every match, copy in chunks
4493 // - the part before the match
4494 // - the after string, with the proper replacements for the backreferences
4495
4496 qsizetype newLength = 0; // length of the new string, with all the replacements
4497 qsizetype lastEnd = 0;
4498 QList<QStringView> chunks;
4499 const QStringView copyView{ copy }, afterView{ after };
4500 while (iterator.hasNext()) {
4501 QRegularExpressionMatch match = iterator.next();
4502 qsizetype len;
4503 // add the part before the match
4504 len = match.capturedStart() - lastEnd;
4505 if (len > 0) {
4506 chunks << copyView.mid(pos: lastEnd, n: len);
4507 newLength += len;
4508 }
4509
4510 lastEnd = 0;
4511 // add the after string, with replacements for the backreferences
4512 for (const QStringCapture &backReference : std::as_const(t&: backReferences)) {
4513 // part of "after" before the backreference
4514 len = backReference.pos - lastEnd;
4515 if (len > 0) {
4516 chunks << afterView.mid(pos: lastEnd, n: len);
4517 newLength += len;
4518 }
4519
4520 // backreference itself
4521 len = match.capturedLength(nth: backReference.no);
4522 if (len > 0) {
4523 chunks << copyView.mid(pos: match.capturedStart(nth: backReference.no), n: len);
4524 newLength += len;
4525 }
4526
4527 lastEnd = backReference.pos + backReference.len;
4528 }
4529
4530 // add the last part of the after string
4531 len = afterView.size() - lastEnd;
4532 if (len > 0) {
4533 chunks << afterView.mid(pos: lastEnd, n: len);
4534 newLength += len;
4535 }
4536
4537 lastEnd = match.capturedEnd();
4538 }
4539
4540 // 3. trailing string after the last match
4541 if (copyView.size() > lastEnd) {
4542 chunks << copyView.mid(pos: lastEnd);
4543 newLength += copyView.size() - lastEnd;
4544 }
4545
4546 // 4. assemble the chunks together
4547 resize(size: newLength);
4548 qsizetype i = 0;
4549 QChar *uc = data();
4550 for (const QStringView &chunk : std::as_const(t&: chunks)) {
4551 qsizetype len = chunk.size();
4552 memcpy(dest: uc + i, src: chunk.constData(), n: len * sizeof(QChar));
4553 i += len;
4554 }
4555
4556 return *this;
4557}
4558#endif // QT_CONFIG(regularexpression)

4774
4775/*!
4776 \enum QString::SectionFlag
4777
4778 This enum specifies flags that can be used to affect various
4779 aspects of the section() function's behavior with respect to
4780 separators and empty fields.
4781
4782 \value SectionDefault Empty fields are counted, leading and
4783 trailing separators are not included, and the separator is
4784 compared case sensitively.
4785
4786 \value SectionSkipEmpty Treat empty fields as if they don't exist,
4787 i.e. they are not considered as far as \e start and \e end are
4788 concerned.
4789
4790 \value SectionIncludeLeadingSep Include the leading separator (if
4791 any) in the result string.
4792
4793 \value SectionIncludeTrailingSep Include the trailing separator
4794 (if any) in the result string.
4795
4796 \value SectionCaseInsensitiveSeps Compare the separator
4797 case-insensitively.
4798
4799 \sa section()
4800*/
4801
4802/*!
4803 \fn QString QString::section(QChar sep, qsizetype start, qsizetype end = -1, SectionFlags flags) const
4804
4805 This function returns a section of the string.
4806
4807 This string is treated as a sequence of fields separated by the
4808 character, \a sep. The returned string consists of the fields from
4809 position \a start to position \a end inclusive. If \a end is not
4810 specified, all fields from position \a start to the end of the
4811 string are included. Fields are numbered 0, 1, 2, etc., counting
4812 from the left, and -1, -2, etc., counting from right to left.
4813
4814 The \a flags argument can be used to affect some aspects of the
4815 function's behavior, e.g. whether to be case sensitive, whether
4816 to skip empty fields and how to deal with leading and trailing
4817 separators; see \l{SectionFlags}.
4818
4819 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 52
4820
4821 If \a start or \a end is negative, we count fields from the right
4822 of the string, the right-most field being -1, the one from
4823 right-most field being -2, and so on.
4824
4825 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 53
4826
4827 \sa split()
4828*/
4829
4830/*!
4831 \overload section()
4832
4833 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 51
4834 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 54
4835
4836 \sa split()
4837*/
4838
4839QString QString::section(const QString &sep, qsizetype start, qsizetype end, SectionFlags flags) const
4840{
4841 const QList<QStringView> sections = QStringView{ *this }.split(
4842 sep, behavior: Qt::KeepEmptyParts, cs: (flags & SectionCaseInsensitiveSeps) ? Qt::CaseInsensitive : Qt::CaseSensitive);
4843 const qsizetype sectionsSize = sections.size();
4844 if (!(flags & SectionSkipEmpty)) {
4845 if (start < 0)
4846 start += sectionsSize;
4847 if (end < 0)
4848 end += sectionsSize;
4849 } else {
4850 qsizetype skip = 0;
4851 for (qsizetype k = 0; k < sectionsSize; ++k) {
4852 if (sections.at(i: k).isEmpty())
4853 skip++;
4854 }
4855 if (start < 0)
4856 start += sectionsSize - skip;
4857 if (end < 0)
4858 end += sectionsSize - skip;
4859 }
4860 if (start >= sectionsSize || end < 0 || start > end)
4861 return QString();
4862
4863 QString ret;
4864 qsizetype first_i = start, last_i = end;
4865 for (qsizetype x = 0, i = 0; x <= end && i < sectionsSize; ++i) {
4866 const QStringView &section = sections.at(i);
4867 const bool empty = section.isEmpty();
4868 if (x >= start) {
4869 if (x == start)
4870 first_i = i;
4871 if (x == end)
4872 last_i = i;
4873 if (x > start && i > 0)
4874 ret += sep;
4875 ret += section;
4876 }
4877 if (!empty || !(flags & SectionSkipEmpty))
4878 x++;
4879 }
4880 if ((flags & SectionIncludeLeadingSep) && first_i > 0)
4881 ret.prepend(s: sep);
4882 if ((flags & SectionIncludeTrailingSep) && last_i < sectionsSize - 1)
4883 ret += sep;
4884 return ret;
4885}
4886
4887#if QT_CONFIG(regularexpression)
4888class qt_section_chunk {
4889public:
4890 qt_section_chunk() {}
4891 qt_section_chunk(qsizetype l, QStringView s) : length(l), string(std::move(s)) {}
4892 qsizetype length;
4893 QStringView string;
4894};
4895Q_DECLARE_TYPEINFO(qt_section_chunk, Q_RELOCATABLE_TYPE);
4896
4897static QString extractSections(const QList<qt_section_chunk> &sections, qsizetype start, qsizetype end,
4898 QString::SectionFlags flags)
4899{
4900 const qsizetype sectionsSize = sections.size();
4901
4902 if (!(flags & QString::SectionSkipEmpty)) {
4903 if (start < 0)
4904 start += sectionsSize;
4905 if (end < 0)
4906 end += sectionsSize;
4907 } else {
4908 qsizetype skip = 0;
4909 for (qsizetype k = 0; k < sectionsSize; ++k) {
4910 const qt_section_chunk &section = sections.at(i: k);
4911 if (section.length == section.string.size())
4912 skip++;
4913 }
4914 if (start < 0)
4915 start += sectionsSize - skip;
4916 if (end < 0)
4917 end += sectionsSize - skip;
4918 }
4919 if (start >= sectionsSize || end < 0 || start > end)
4920 return QString();
4921
4922 QString ret;
4923 qsizetype x = 0;
4924 qsizetype first_i = start, last_i = end;
4925 for (qsizetype i = 0; x <= end && i < sectionsSize; ++i) {
4926 const qt_section_chunk &section = sections.at(i);
4927 const bool empty = (section.length == section.string.size());
4928 if (x >= start) {
4929 if (x == start)
4930 first_i = i;
4931 if (x == end)
4932 last_i = i;
4933 if (x != start)
4934 ret += section.string;
4935 else
4936 ret += section.string.mid(pos: section.length);
4937 }
4938 if (!empty || !(flags & QString::SectionSkipEmpty))
4939 x++;
4940 }
4941
4942 if ((flags & QString::SectionIncludeLeadingSep) && first_i >= 0) {
4943 const qt_section_chunk &section = sections.at(i: first_i);
4944 ret.prepend(v: section.string.left(n: section.length));
4945 }
4946
4947 if ((flags & QString::SectionIncludeTrailingSep)
4948 && last_i < sectionsSize - 1) {
4949 const qt_section_chunk &section = sections.at(i: last_i+1);
4950 ret += section.string.left(n: section.length);
4951 }
4952
4953 return ret;
4954}
4955
4956/*!
4957 \overload section()
4958 \since 5.0
4959
4960 This string is treated as a sequence of fields separated by the
4961 regular expression, \a re.
4962
4963 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 89
4964
4965 \warning Using this QRegularExpression version is much more expensive than
4966 the overloaded string and character versions.
4967
4968 \sa split(), simplified()
4969*/
4970QString QString::section(const QRegularExpression &re, qsizetype start, qsizetype end, SectionFlags flags) const
4971{
4972 if (!re.isValid()) {
4973 qtWarnAboutInvalidRegularExpression(pattern: re.pattern(), where: "QString::section");
4974 return QString();
4975 }
4976
4977 const QChar *uc = unicode();
4978 if (!uc)
4979 return QString();
4980
4981 QRegularExpression sep(re);
4982 if (flags & SectionCaseInsensitiveSeps)
4983 sep.setPatternOptions(sep.patternOptions() | QRegularExpression::CaseInsensitiveOption);
4984
4985 QList<qt_section_chunk> sections;
4986 qsizetype n = size(), m = 0, last_m = 0, last_len = 0;
4987 QRegularExpressionMatchIterator iterator = sep.globalMatch(subject: *this);
4988 while (iterator.hasNext()) {
4989 QRegularExpressionMatch match = iterator.next();
4990 m = match.capturedStart();
4991 sections.append(t: qt_section_chunk(last_len, QStringView{ *this }.sliced(pos: last_m, n: m - last_m)));
4992 last_m = m;
4993 last_len = match.capturedLength();
4994 }
4995 sections.append(t: qt_section_chunk(last_len, QStringView{ *this }.sliced(pos: last_m, n: n - last_m)));
4996
4997 return extractSections(sections, start, end, flags);
4998}

5009 to size(), or less than zero.

5039/*!
5040 Returns a string that contains \a n characters of this string,
5041 starting at the specified \a position index.
5042
5043 If you know that \a position and \a n cannot be out of bounds, use sliced()
5044 instead in new code, because it is faster.
5045
5046 Returns a null string if the \a position index exceeds the
5047 length of the string. If there are less than \a n characters
5048 available in the string starting at the given \a position, or if
5049 \a n is -1 (default), the function returns all characters that
5050 are available from the specified \a position.
5051
5052
5053 \sa first(), last(), sliced(), chopped(), chop(), truncate()
5054*/
5055
5056QString QString::mid(qsizetype position, qsizetype n) const
5057{
5058 qsizetype p = position;
5059 qsizetype l = n;
5060 using namespace QtPrivate;
5061 switch (QContainerImplHelper::mid(originalLength: size(), position: &p, length: &l)) {
5062 case QContainerImplHelper::Null:
5063 return QString();
5064 case QContainerImplHelper::Empty:
5065 return QString(DataPointer::fromRawData(rawData: &_empty, length: 0));
5066 case QContainerImplHelper::Full:
5067 return *this;
5068 case QContainerImplHelper::Subset:
5069 return QString(constData() + p, l);
5070 }
5071 Q_UNREACHABLE_RETURN(QString());
5072}

5242/*!
5243 Returns \c true if the string is uppercase, that is, it's identical
5244 to its toUpper() folding.
5245
5246 Note that this does \e not mean that the string does not contain
5247 lowercase letters (some lowercase letters do not have a uppercase
5248 folding; they are left unchanged by toUpper()).
5249 For more information, refer to the Unicode standard, section 3.13.
5250
5251 \since 5.12
5252
5253 \sa QChar::toUpper(), isLower()
5254*/
5255bool QString::isUpper() const
5256{
5257 QStringIterator it(*this);
5258
5259 while (it.hasNext()) {
5260 const char32_t uc = it.next();
5261 if (qGetProp(ucs4: uc)->cases[QUnicodeTables::UpperCase].diff)
5262 return false;
5263 }
5264
5265 return true;
5266}
5267
5268/*!
5269 Returns \c true if the string is lowercase, that is, it's identical
5270 to its toLower() folding.
5271
5272 Note that this does \e not mean that the string does not contain
5273 uppercase letters (some uppercase letters do not have a lowercase
5274 folding; they are left unchanged by toLower()).
5275 For more information, refer to the Unicode standard, section 3.13.
5276
5277 \since 5.12
5278
5279 \sa QChar::toLower(), isUpper()
5280 */
5281bool QString::isLower() const
5282{
5283 QStringIterator it(*this);
5284
5285 while (it.hasNext()) {
5286 const char32_t uc = it.next();
5287 if (qGetProp(ucs4: uc)->cases[QUnicodeTables::LowerCase].diff)
5288 return false;
5289 }
5290
5291 return true;
5292}

5316/*!
5317 \since 5.10
5318 \internal
5319 \relates QStringView
5320
5321 Returns a Latin-1 representation of \a string as a QByteArray.
5322
5323 The behavior is undefined if \a string contains non-Latin1 characters.
5324
5325 \sa QString::toLatin1(), QStringView::toLatin1(), QtPrivate::convertToUtf8(),
5326 QtPrivate::convertToLocal8Bit(), QtPrivate::convertToUcs4()
5327*/
5328QByteArray QtPrivate::convertToLatin1(QStringView string)
5329{
5330 return qt_convert_to_latin1(string);
5331}
5332
5333Q_NEVER_INLINE
5334static QByteArray qt_convert_to_latin1(QStringView string)
5335{
5336 if (Q_UNLIKELY(string.isNull()))
5337 return QByteArray();
5338
5339 QByteArray ba(string.size(), Qt::Uninitialized);
5340
5341 // since we own the only copy, we're going to const_cast the constData;
5342 // that avoids an unnecessary call to detach() and expansion code that will never get used
5343 qt_to_latin1(dst: reinterpret_cast<uchar *>(const_cast<char *>(ba.constData())),
5344 src: string.utf16(), length: string.size());
5345 return ba;
5346}
5347
5348QByteArray QString::toLatin1_helper_inplace(QString &s)
5349{
5350 if (!s.isDetached())
5351 return qt_convert_to_latin1(string: s);
5352
5353 // We can return our own buffer to the caller.
5354 // Conversion to Latin-1 always shrinks the buffer by half.
5355 // This relies on the fact that we use QArrayData for everything behind the scenes
5356
5357 // First, do the in-place conversion. Since isDetached() == true, the data
5358 // was allocated by QArrayData, so the null terminator must be there.
5359 qsizetype length = s.size();
5360 char16_t *sdata = s.d->data();
5361 Q_ASSERT(sdata[length] == u'\0');
5362 qt_to_latin1(dst: reinterpret_cast<uchar *>(sdata), src: sdata, length: length + 1);
5363
5364 // Move the internals over to the byte array.
5365 // Kids, avert your eyes. Don't try this at home.
5366 auto ba_d = std::move(s.d).reinterpreted<char>();
5367
5368 // Some sanity checks
5369 Q_ASSERT(ba_d.d->allocatedCapacity() >= ba_d.size);
5370 Q_ASSERT(s.isNull());
5371 Q_ASSERT(s.isEmpty());
5372 Q_ASSERT(s.constData() == QString().constData());
5373
5374 return QByteArray(std::move(ba_d));
5375}

5484static QList<uint> qt_convert_to_ucs4(QStringView string);
5485
5486/*!
5487 \since 4.2
5488
5489 Returns a UCS-4/UTF-32 representation of the string as a QList<uint>.
5490
5491 UCS-4 is a Unicode codec and therefore it is lossless. All characters from
5492 this string will be encoded in UCS-4. Any invalid sequence of code units in
5493 this string is replaced by the Unicode's replacement character
5494 (QChar::ReplacementCharacter, which corresponds to \c{U+FFFD}).
5495
5496 The returned list is not \\0'-terminated.
5497
5498 \sa fromUtf8(), toUtf8(), toLatin1(), toLocal8Bit(), QStringEncoder,
5499 fromUcs4(), toWCharArray()
5500*/
5501QList<uint> QString::toUcs4() const
5502{
5503 return qt_convert_to_ucs4(string: *this);
5504}
5505
5506static QList<uint> qt_convert_to_ucs4(QStringView string)
5507{
5508 QList<uint> v(string.size());
5509 uint *a = const_cast<uint*>(v.constData());
5510 QStringIterator it(string);
5511 while (it.hasNext())
5512 *a++ = it.next();
5513 v.resize(size: a - v.constData());
5514 return v;
5515}

5518 \since 5.10
5519 \internal
5520 \relates QStringView

5525 this string will be encoded in UCS-4. Any invalid sequence of code units in
5526 this string is replaced by the Unicode's replacement character
5527 (QChar::ReplacementCharacter, which corresponds to \c{U+FFFD}).
5528
5529 The returned list is not \\0'-terminated.
5530
5531 \sa QString::toUcs4(), QStringView::toUcs4(), QtPrivate::convertToLatin1(),
5532 QtPrivate::convertToLocal8Bit(), QtPrivate::convertToUtf8()

5539/*!
5540 \fn QString QString::fromLatin1(QByteArrayView str)
5541 \overload
5542 \since 6.0
5543
5544 Returns a QString initialized with the Latin-1 string \a str.
5545
5546 \note: any null ('\\0') bytes in the byte array will be included in this
5547 string, converted to Unicode null characters (U+0000).
5548*/
5549QString QString::fromLatin1(QByteArrayView ba)
5550{
5551 DataPointer d;
5552 if (!ba.data()) {
5553 // nothing to do
5554 } else if (ba.size() == 0) {
5555 d = DataPointer::fromRawData(rawData: &_empty, length: 0);
5556 } else {
5557 d = DataPointer(Data::allocate(capacity: ba.size()), ba.size());
5558 Q_CHECK_PTR(d.data());
5559 d.data()[ba.size()] = '\0';
5560 char16_t *dst = d.data();
5561
5562 qt_from_latin1(dst, str: ba.data(), size: size_t(ba.size()));
5563 }
5564 return QString(std::move(d));
5565}

5634/*! \fn QString QString::fromUtf8(const char *str, qsizetype size)
5635 Returns a QString initialized with the first \a size bytes
5636 of the UTF-8 string \a str.
5637
5638 If \a size is \c{-1}, \c{strlen(str)} is used instead.
5639
5640 UTF-8 is a Unicode codec and can represent all characters in a Unicode
5641 string like QString. However, invalid sequences are possible with UTF-8
5642 and, if any such are found, they will be replaced with one or more
5643 "replacement characters", or suppressed. These include non-Unicode
5644 sequences, non-characters, overlong sequences or surrogate codepoints
5645 encoded into UTF-8.
5646
5647 This function can be used to process incoming data incrementally as long as
5648 all UTF-8 characters are terminated within the incoming data. Any
5649 unterminated characters at the end of the string will be replaced or
5650 suppressed. In order to do stateful decoding, please use \l QStringDecoder.
5651
5652 \sa toUtf8(), fromLatin1(), fromLocal8Bit()
5653*/

5702/*!
5703 \since 5.3
5704 Returns a QString initialized with the first \a size characters
5705 of the Unicode string \a unicode (ISO-10646-UTF-16 encoded).
5706
5707 If \a size is -1 (default), \a unicode must be \\0'-terminated.
5708
5709 This function checks for a Byte Order Mark (BOM). If it is missing,
5710 host byte order is assumed.
5711
5712 This function is slow compared to the other Unicode conversions.
5713 Use QString(const QChar *, qsizetype) or QString(const QChar *) if possible.
5714
5715 QString makes a deep copy of the Unicode data.
5716
5717 \sa utf16(), setUtf16(), fromStdU16String()
5718*/
5719QString QString::fromUtf16(const char16_t *unicode, qsizetype size)
5720{
5721 if (!unicode)
5722 return QString();
5723 if (size < 0)
5724 size = QtPrivate::qustrlen(str: unicode);
5725 QStringDecoder toUtf16(QStringDecoder::Utf16, QStringDecoder::Flag::Stateless);
5726 return toUtf16(QByteArrayView(reinterpret_cast<const char *>(unicode), size * 2));
5727}
5728
5729/*!
5730 \fn QString QString::fromUtf16(const ushort *str, qsizetype size)
5731 \deprecated [6.0] Use the \c char16_t overload instead.
5732*/
5733
5734/*!
5735 \fn QString QString::fromUcs4(const uint *str, qsizetype size)
5736 \since 4.2
5737 \deprecated [6.0] Use the \c char32_t overload instead.
5738*/
5739
5740/*!
5741 \since 5.3
5742
5743 Returns a QString initialized with the first \a size characters
5744 of the Unicode string \a unicode (ISO-10646-UCS-4 encoded).
5745
5746 If \a size is -1 (default), \a unicode must be \\0'-terminated.
5747
5748 \sa toUcs4(), fromUtf16(), utf16(), setUtf16(), fromWCharArray(),
5749 fromStdU32String()
5750*/
5751QString QString::fromUcs4(const char32_t *unicode, qsizetype size)
5752{
5753 if (!unicode)
5754 return QString();
5755 if (size < 0) {
5756 size = 0;
5757 while (unicode[size] != 0)
5758 ++size;
5759 }
5760 QStringDecoder toUtf16(QStringDecoder::Utf32, QStringDecoder::Flag::Stateless);
5761 return toUtf16(QByteArrayView(reinterpret_cast<const char *>(unicode), size * 4));
5762}

5765/*!
5766 Resizes the string to \a size characters and copies \a unicode
5767 into the string.
5768
5769 If \a unicode is \nullptr, nothing is copied, but the string is still
5770 resized to \a size.
5771
5772 \sa unicode(), setUtf16()
5773*/
5774QString& QString::setUnicode(const QChar *unicode, qsizetype size)
5775{
5776 resize(size);
5777 if (unicode && size)
5778 memcpy(dest: d.data(), src: unicode, n: size * sizeof(QChar));
5779 return *this;
5780}

5803

5824namespace {
5825 template <typename StringView>
5826 StringView qt_trimmed(StringView s) noexcept
5827 {
5828 auto begin = s.begin();
5829 auto end = s.end();
5830 QStringAlgorithms<const StringView>::trimmed_helper_positions(begin, end);
5831 return StringView{begin, end};
5832 }
5833}

5835/*!
5836 \fn QStringView QtPrivate::trimmed(QStringView s)
5837 \fn QLatin1StringView QtPrivate::trimmed(QLatin1StringView s)
5838 \internal
5839 \relates QStringView
5840 \since 5.10
5841
5842 Returns \a s with whitespace removed from the start and the end.
5843
5844 Whitespace means any character for which QChar::isSpace() returns

6378 rhs: QUtf8StringView(data2, length2), cs);

6403/*!
6404 \fn int QString::localeAwareCompare(const QString & s1, const QString & s2)
6405
6406 Compares \a s1 with \a s2 and returns an integer less than, equal
6407 to, or greater than zero if \a s1 is less than, equal to, or
6408 greater than \a s2.
6409
6410 The comparison is performed in a locale- and also
6411 platform-dependent manner. Use this function to present sorted
6412 lists of strings to the user.
6413
6414 \sa compare(), QLocale, {Comparing Strings}
6415*/
6416
6417/*!
6418 \fn int QString::localeAwareCompare(QStringView other) const
6419 \since 6.0
6420 \overload localeAwareCompare()
6421
6422 Compares this string with the \a other string and returns an
6423 integer less than, equal to, or greater than zero if this string
6424 is less than, equal to, or greater than the \a other string.
6425
6426 The comparison is performed in a locale- and also
6427 platform-dependent manner. Use this function to present sorted
6428 lists of strings to the user.
6429
6430 Same as \c {localeAwareCompare(*this, other)}.
6431
6432 \sa {Comparing Strings}
6433*/
6434
6435/*!
6436 \fn int QString::localeAwareCompare(QStringView s1, QStringView s2)
6437 \since 6.0
6438 \overload localeAwareCompare()
6439
6440 Compares \a s1 with \a s2 and returns an integer less than, equal
6441 to, or greater than zero if \a s1 is less than, equal to, or
6442 greater than \a s2.
6443
6444 The comparison is performed in a locale- and also
6445 platform-dependent manner. Use this function to present sorted
6446 lists of strings to the user.
6447
6448 \sa {Comparing Strings}
6449*/
6450
6451
6452#if !defined(CSTR_LESS_THAN)
6453#define CSTR_LESS_THAN 1
6454#define CSTR_EQUAL 2
6455#define CSTR_GREATER_THAN 3
6456#endif
6457
6458/*!
6459 \overload localeAwareCompare()
6460
6461 Compares this string with the \a other string and returns an
6462 integer less than, equal to, or greater than zero if this string
6463 is less than, equal to, or greater than the \a other string.
6464
6465 The comparison is performed in a locale- and also
6466 platform-dependent manner. Use this function to present sorted
6467 lists of strings to the user.
6468
6469 Same as \c {localeAwareCompare(*this, other)}.
6470
6471 \sa {Comparing Strings}
6472*/
6473int QString::localeAwareCompare(const QString &other) const
6474{
6475 return localeAwareCompare_helper(data1: constData(), length1: size(), data2: other.constData(), length2: other.size());
6476}
6477
6478/*!
6479 \internal
6480 \since 4.5
6481*/
6482int QString::localeAwareCompare_helper(const QChar *data1, qsizetype length1,
6483 const QChar *data2, qsizetype length2)
6484{
6485 Q_ASSERT(length1 >= 0);
6486 Q_ASSERT(data1 || length1 == 0);
6487 Q_ASSERT(length2 >= 0);
6488 Q_ASSERT(data2 || length2 == 0);
6489
6490 // do the right thing for null and empty
6491 if (length1 == 0 || length2 == 0)
6492 return QtPrivate::compareStrings(lhs: QStringView(data1, length1), rhs: QStringView(data2, length2),
6493 cs: Qt::CaseSensitive);
6494
6495#if QT_CONFIG(icu)
6496 return QCollator::defaultCompare(QStringView(data1, length1), QStringView(data2, length2));
6497#else
6498 const QString lhs = QString::fromRawData(data1, size: length1).normalized(mode: QString::NormalizationForm_C);
6499 const QString rhs = QString::fromRawData(data2, size: length2).normalized(mode: QString::NormalizationForm_C);
6500# if defined(Q_OS_WIN)
6501 int res = CompareStringEx(LOCALE_NAME_USER_DEFAULT, 0, (LPWSTR)lhs.constData(), lhs.length(), (LPWSTR)rhs.constData(), rhs.length(), NULL, NULL, 0);
6502
6503 switch (res) {
6504 case CSTR_LESS_THAN:
6505 return -1;
6506 case CSTR_GREATER_THAN:
6507 return 1;
6508 default:
6509 return 0;
6510 }
6511# elif defined (Q_OS_DARWIN)
6512 // Use CFStringCompare for comparing strings on Mac. This makes Qt order
6513 // strings the same way as native applications do, and also respects
6514 // the "Order for sorted lists" setting in the International preferences
6515 // panel.
6516 const CFStringRef thisString =
6517 CFStringCreateWithCharactersNoCopy(kCFAllocatorDefault,
6518 reinterpret_cast<const UniChar *>(lhs.constData()), lhs.length(), kCFAllocatorNull);
6519 const CFStringRef otherString =
6520 CFStringCreateWithCharactersNoCopy(kCFAllocatorDefault,
6521 reinterpret_cast<const UniChar *>(rhs.constData()), rhs.length(), kCFAllocatorNull);
6522
6523 const int result = CFStringCompare(thisString, otherString, kCFCompareLocalized);
6524 CFRelease(thisString);
6525 CFRelease(otherString);
6526 return result;
6527# elif defined(Q_OS_UNIX)
6528 // declared in <string.h> (no better than QtPrivate::compareStrings() on Android, sadly)
6529 return strcoll(s1: lhs.toLocal8Bit().constData(), s2: rhs.toLocal8Bit().constData());
6530# else
6531# error "This case shouldn't happen"
6532 return QtPrivate::compareStrings(lhs, rhs, Qt::CaseSensitive);
6533# endif
6534#endif // !QT_CONFIG(icu)
6535}
6536
6537
6538/*!
6539 \fn const QChar *QString::unicode() const
6540
6541 Returns a Unicode representation of the string.
6542 The result remains valid until the string is modified.
6543
6544 \note The returned string may not be '\\0'-terminated.
6545 Use size() to determine the length of the array.
6546
6547 \sa utf16(), fromRawData()
6548*/
6549
6550/*!
6551 \fn const ushort *QString::utf16() const
6552
6553 Returns the QString as a '\\0\'-terminated array of unsigned
6554 shorts. The result remains valid until the string is modified.
6555
6556 The returned string is in host byte order.
6557
6558 \sa unicode()
6559*/
6560
6561const ushort *QString::utf16() const
6562{
6563 if (!d->isMutable()) {
6564 // ensure '\0'-termination for ::fromRawData strings
6565 const_cast<QString*>(this)->reallocData(alloc: d.size, option: QArrayData::KeepSize);
6566 }
6567 return reinterpret_cast<const ushort *>(d.data());
6568}
6569
6570/*!
6571 Returns a string of size \a width that contains this string
6572 padded by the \a fill character.
6573
6574 If \a truncate is \c false and the size() of the string is more than
6575 \a width, then the returned string is a copy of the string.
6576
6577 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 32
6578
6579 If \a truncate is \c true and the size() of the string is more than
6580 \a width, then any characters in a copy of the string after
6581 position \a width are removed, and the copy is returned.
6582
6583 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 33
6584
6585 \sa rightJustified()
6586*/
6587
6588QString QString::leftJustified(qsizetype width, QChar fill, bool truncate) const
6589{
6590 QString result;
6591 qsizetype len = size();
6592 qsizetype padlen = width - len;
6593 if (padlen > 0) {
6594 result.resize(size: len+padlen);
6595 if (len)
6596 memcpy(dest: result.d.data(), src: d.data(), n: sizeof(QChar)*len);
6597 QChar *uc = (QChar*)result.d.data() + len;
6598 while (padlen--)
6599 * uc++ = fill;
6600 } else {
6601 if (truncate)
6602 result = left(n: width);
6603 else
6604 result = *this;
6605 }
6606 return result;
6607}
6608
6609/*!
6610 Returns a string of size() \a width that contains the \a fill
6611 character followed by the string. For example:
6612
6613 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 49
6614
6615 If \a truncate is \c false and the size() of the string is more than
6616 \a width, then the returned string is a copy of the string.
6617
6618 If \a truncate is true and the size() of the string is more than
6619 \a width, then the resulting string is truncated at position \a
6620 width.
6621
6622 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 50
6623
6624 \sa leftJustified()
6625*/
6626
6627QString QString::rightJustified(qsizetype width, QChar fill, bool truncate) const
6628{
6629 QString result;
6630 qsizetype len = size();
6631 qsizetype padlen = width - len;
6632 if (padlen > 0) {
6633 result.resize(size: len+padlen);
6634 QChar *uc = (QChar*)result.d.data();
6635 while (padlen--)
6636 * uc++ = fill;
6637 if (len)
6638 memcpy(dest: static_cast<void *>(uc), src: static_cast<const void *>(d.data()), n: sizeof(QChar)*len);
6639 } else {
6640 if (truncate)
6641 result = left(n: width);
6642 else
6643 result = *this;
6644 }
6645 return result;
6646}
6647
6648/*!
6649 \fn QString QString::toLower() const
6650
6651 Returns a lowercase copy of the string.
6652
6653 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 75
6654
6655 The case conversion will always happen in the 'C' locale. For
6656 locale-dependent case folding use QLocale::toLower()
6657
6658 \sa toUpper(), QLocale::toLower()
6659*/
6660
6661namespace QUnicodeTables {
6662/*
6663 \internal
6664 Converts the \a str string starting from the position pointed to by the \a
6665 it iterator, using the Unicode case traits \c Traits, and returns the
6666 result. The input string must not be empty (the convertCase function below
6667 guarantees that).
6668
6669 The string type \c{T} is also a template and is either \c{const QString} or
6670 \c{QString}. This function can do both copy-conversion and in-place
6671 conversion depending on the state of the \a str parameter:
6672 \list
6673 \li \c{T} is \c{const QString}: copy-convert
6674 \li \c{T} is \c{QString} and its refcount != 1: copy-convert
6675 \li \c{T} is \c{QString} and its refcount == 1: in-place convert
6676 \endlist
6677
6678 In copy-convert mode, the local variable \c{s} is detached from the input
6679 \a str. In the in-place convert mode, \a str is in moved-from state and
6680 \c{s} contains the only copy of the string, without reallocation (thus,
6681 \a it is still valid).
6682
6683 There is one pathological case left: when the in-place conversion needs to
6684 reallocate memory to grow the buffer. In that case, we need to adjust the \a
6685 it pointer.
6686 */
6687template <typename T>
6688Q_NEVER_INLINE
6689static QString detachAndConvertCase(T &str, QStringIterator it, QUnicodeTables::Case which)
6690{
6691 Q_ASSERT(!str.isEmpty());
6692 QString s = std::move(str); // will copy if T is const QString
6693 QChar *pp = s.begin() + it.index(); // will detach if necessary
6694
6695 do {
6696 const auto folded = fullConvertCase(uc: it.next(), which);
6697 if (Q_UNLIKELY(folded.size() > 1)) {
6698 if (folded.chars[0] == *pp && folded.size() == 2) {
6699 // special case: only second actually changed (e.g. surrogate pairs),
6700 // avoid slow case
6701 ++pp;
6702 *pp++ = folded.chars[1];
6703 } else {
6704 // slow path: the string is growing
6705 qsizetype inpos = it.index() - 1;
6706 qsizetype outpos = pp - s.constBegin();
6707
6708 s.replace(pos: outpos, len: 1, unicode: reinterpret_cast<const QChar *>(folded.data()), size: folded.size());
6709 pp = const_cast<QChar *>(s.constBegin()) + outpos + folded.size();
6710
6711 // Adjust the input iterator if we are performing an in-place conversion
6712 if constexpr (!std::is_const<T>::value)
6713 it = QStringIterator(s.constBegin(), inpos + folded.size(), s.constEnd());
6714 }
6715 } else {
6716 *pp++ = folded.chars[0];
6717 }
6718 } while (it.hasNext());
6719
6720 return s;
6721}
6722
6723template <typename T>
6724static QString convertCase(T &str, QUnicodeTables::Case which)
6725{
6726 const QChar *p = str.constBegin();
6727 const QChar *e = p + str.size();
6728
6729 // this avoids out of bounds check in the loop
6730 while (e != p && e[-1].isHighSurrogate())
6731 --e;
6732
6733 QStringIterator it(p, e);
6734 while (it.hasNext()) {
6735 const char32_t uc = it.next();
6736 if (qGetProp(ucs4: uc)->cases[which].diff) {
6737 it.recede();
6738 return detachAndConvertCase(str, it, which);
6739 }
6740 }
6741 return std::move(str);
6742}
6743} // namespace QUnicodeTables
6744
6745QString QString::toLower_helper(const QString &str)
6746{
6747 return QUnicodeTables::convertCase(str, which: QUnicodeTables::LowerCase);
6748}
6749
6750QString QString::toLower_helper(QString &str)
6751{
6752 return QUnicodeTables::convertCase(str, which: QUnicodeTables::LowerCase);
6753}

6794
6795/*!
6796 \since 5.5
6797
6798 Safely builds a formatted string from the format string \a cformat
6799 and an arbitrary list of arguments.
6800
6801 The format string supports the conversion specifiers, length modifiers,
6802 and flags provided by printf() in the standard C++ library. The \a cformat
6803 string and \c{%s} arguments must be UTF-8 encoded.
6804
6805 \note The \c{%lc} escape sequence expects a unicode character of type
6806 \c char16_t, or \c ushort (as returned by QChar::unicode()).
6807 The \c{%ls} escape sequence expects a pointer to a zero-terminated array
6808 of unicode characters of type \c char16_t, or ushort (as returned by
6809 QString::utf16()). This is at odds with the printf() in the standard C++
6810 library, which defines \c {%lc} to print a wchar_t and \c{%ls} to print
6811 a \c{wchar_t*}, and might also produce compiler warnings on platforms
6812 where the size of \c {wchar_t} is not 16 bits.
6813
6814 \warning We do not recommend using QString::asprintf() in new Qt
6815 code. Instead, consider using QTextStream or arg(), both of
6816 which support Unicode strings seamlessly and are type-safe.
6817 Here is an example that uses QTextStream:
6818
6819 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 64
6820
6821 For \l {QObject::tr()}{translations}, especially if the strings
6822 contains more than one escape sequence, you should consider using
6823 the arg() function instead. This allows the order of the
6824 replacements to be controlled by the translator.
6825
6826 \sa arg()
6827*/
6828
6829QString QString::asprintf(const char *cformat, ...)
6830{
6831 va_list ap;
6832 va_start(ap, cformat);
6833 const QString s = vasprintf(format: cformat, ap);
6834 va_end(ap);
6835 return s;
6836}
6837
6838static void append_utf8(QString &qs, const char *cs, qsizetype len)
6839{
6840 const qsizetype oldSize = qs.size();
6841 qs.resize(size: oldSize + len);
6842 const QChar *newEnd = QUtf8::convertToUnicode(buffer: qs.data() + oldSize, in: QByteArrayView(cs, len));
6843 qs.resize(size: newEnd - qs.constData());
6844}
6845
6846static uint parse_flag_characters(const char * &c) noexcept
6847{
6848 uint flags = QLocaleData::ZeroPadExponent;
6849 while (true) {
6850 switch (*c) {
6851 case '#':
6852 flags |= QLocaleData::ShowBase | QLocaleData::AddTrailingZeroes
6853 | QLocaleData::ForcePoint;
6854 break;
6855 case '0': flags |= QLocaleData::ZeroPadded; break;
6856 case '-': flags |= QLocaleData::LeftAdjusted; break;
6857 case ' ': flags |= QLocaleData::BlankBeforePositive; break;
6858 case '+': flags |= QLocaleData::AlwaysShowSign; break;
6859 case '\'': flags |= QLocaleData::GroupDigits; break;
6860 default: return flags;
6861 }
6862 ++c;
6863 }
6864}
6865
6866static int parse_field_width(const char *&c, qsizetype size)
6867{
6868 Q_ASSERT(isAsciiDigit(*c));
6869 const char *const stop = c + size;
6870
6871 // can't be negative - started with a digit
6872 // contains at least one digit
6873 auto [result, used] = qstrntoull(nptr: c, size, base: 10);
6874 c += used;
6875 if (used <= 0)
6876 return false;
6877 // preserve Qt 5.5 behavior of consuming all digits, no matter how many
6878 while (c < stop && isAsciiDigit(c: *c))
6879 ++c;
6880 return result < qulonglong(std::numeric_limits<int>::max()) ? int(result) : 0;
6881}
6882
6883enum LengthMod { lm_none, lm_hh, lm_h, lm_l, lm_ll, lm_L, lm_j, lm_z, lm_t };
6884
6885static inline bool can_consume(const char * &c, char ch) noexcept
6886{
6887 if (*c == ch) {
6888 ++c;
6889 return true;
6890 }
6891 return false;
6892}
6893
6894static LengthMod parse_length_modifier(const char * &c) noexcept
6895{
6896 switch (*c++) {
6897 case 'h': return can_consume(c, ch: 'h') ? lm_hh : lm_h;
6898 case 'l': return can_consume(c, ch: 'l') ? lm_ll : lm_l;
6899 case 'L': return lm_L;
6900 case 'j': return lm_j;
6901 case 'z':
6902 case 'Z': return lm_z;
6903 case 't': return lm_t;
6904 }
6905 --c; // don't consume *c - it wasn't a flag
6906 return lm_none;
6907}
6908
6909/*!
6910 \fn QString QString::vasprintf(const char *cformat, va_list ap)
6911 \since 5.5
6912
6913 Equivalent method to asprintf(), but takes a va_list \a ap
6914 instead a list of variable arguments. See the asprintf()
6915 documentation for an explanation of \a cformat.
6916
6917 This method does not call the va_end macro, the caller
6918 is responsible to call va_end on \a ap.
6919
6920 \sa asprintf()
6921*/
6922
6923QString QString::vasprintf(const char *cformat, va_list ap)
6924{
6925 if (!cformat || !*cformat) {
6926 // Qt 1.x compat
6927 return fromLatin1(ba: "");
6928 }
6929
6930 // Parse cformat
6931
6932 QString result;
6933 const char *c = cformat;
6934 const char *formatEnd = cformat + qstrlen(str: cformat);
6935 for (;;) {
6936 // Copy non-escape chars to result
6937 const char *cb = c;
6938 while (*c != '\0' && *c != '%')
6939 c++;
6940 append_utf8(qs&: result, cs: cb, len: qsizetype(c - cb));
6941
6942 if (*c == '\0')
6943 break;
6944
6945 // Found '%'
6946 const char *escape_start = c;
6947 ++c;
6948
6949 if (*c == '\0') {
6950 result.append(ch: u'%'); // a % at the end of the string - treat as non-escape text
6951 break;
6952 }
6953 if (*c == '%') {
6954 result.append(ch: u'%'); // %%
6955 ++c;
6956 continue;
6957 }
6958
6959 uint flags = parse_flag_characters(c);
6960
6961 if (*c == '\0') {
6962 result.append(str: QLatin1StringView(escape_start)); // incomplete escape, treat as non-escape text
6963 break;
6964 }
6965
6966 // Parse field width
6967 int width = -1; // -1 means unspecified
6968 if (isAsciiDigit(c: *c)) {
6969 width = parse_field_width(c, size: formatEnd - c);
6970 } else if (*c == '*') { // can't parse this in another function, not portably, at least
6971 width = va_arg(ap, int);
6972 if (width < 0)
6973 width = -1; // treat all negative numbers as unspecified
6974 ++c;
6975 }
6976
6977 if (*c == '\0') {
6978 result.append(str: QLatin1StringView(escape_start)); // incomplete escape, treat as non-escape text
6979 break;
6980 }
6981
6982 // Parse precision
6983 int precision = -1; // -1 means unspecified
6984 if (*c == '.') {
6985 ++c;
6986 precision = 0;
6987 if (isAsciiDigit(c: *c)) {
6988 precision = parse_field_width(c, size: formatEnd - c);
6989 } else if (*c == '*') { // can't parse this in another function, not portably, at least
6990 precision = va_arg(ap, int);
6991 if (precision < 0)
6992 precision = -1; // treat all negative numbers as unspecified
6993 ++c;
6994 }
6995 }
6996
6997 if (*c == '\0') {
6998 result.append(str: QLatin1StringView(escape_start)); // incomplete escape, treat as non-escape text
6999 break;
7000 }
7001
7002 const LengthMod length_mod = parse_length_modifier(c);
7003
7004 if (*c == '\0') {
7005 result.append(str: QLatin1StringView(escape_start)); // incomplete escape, treat as non-escape text
7006 break;
7007 }
7008
7009 // Parse the conversion specifier and do the conversion
7010 QString subst;
7011 switch (*c) {
7012 case 'd':
7013 case 'i': {
7014 qint64 i;
7015 switch (length_mod) {
7016 case lm_none: i = va_arg(ap, int); break;
7017 case lm_hh: i = va_arg(ap, int); break;
7018 case lm_h: i = va_arg(ap, int); break;
7019 case lm_l: i = va_arg(ap, long int); break;
7020 case lm_ll: i = va_arg(ap, qint64); break;
7021 case lm_j: i = va_arg(ap, long int); break;
7022
7023 /* ptrdiff_t actually, but it should be the same for us */
7024 case lm_z: i = va_arg(ap, qsizetype); break;
7025 case lm_t: i = va_arg(ap, qsizetype); break;
7026 default: i = 0; break;
7027 }
7028 subst = QLocaleData::c()->longLongToString(l: i, precision, base: 10, width, flags);
7029 ++c;
7030 break;
7031 }
7032 case 'o':
7033 case 'u':
7034 case 'x':
7035 case 'X': {
7036 quint64 u;
7037 switch (length_mod) {
7038 case lm_none: u = va_arg(ap, uint); break;
7039 case lm_hh: u = va_arg(ap, uint); break;
7040 case lm_h: u = va_arg(ap, uint); break;
7041 case lm_l: u = va_arg(ap, ulong); break;
7042 case lm_ll: u = va_arg(ap, quint64); break;
7043 case lm_t: u = va_arg(ap, size_t); break;
7044 case lm_z: u = va_arg(ap, size_t); break;
7045 default: u = 0; break;
7046 }
7047
7048 if (isAsciiUpper(c: *c))
7049 flags |= QLocaleData::CapitalEorX;
7050
7051 int base = 10;
7052 switch (QtMiscUtils::toAsciiLower(ch: *c)) {
7053 case 'o':
7054 base = 8; break;
7055 case 'u':
7056 base = 10; break;
7057 case 'x':
7058 base = 16; break;
7059 default: break;
7060 }
7061 subst = QLocaleData::c()->unsLongLongToString(l: u, precision, base, width, flags);
7062 ++c;
7063 break;
7064 }
7065 case 'E':
7066 case 'e':
7067 case 'F':
7068 case 'f':
7069 case 'G':
7070 case 'g':
7071 case 'A':
7072 case 'a': {
7073 double d;
7074 if (length_mod == lm_L)
7075 d = va_arg(ap, long double); // not supported - converted to a double
7076 else
7077 d = va_arg(ap, double);
7078
7079 if (isAsciiUpper(c: *c))
7080 flags |= QLocaleData::CapitalEorX;
7081
7082 QLocaleData::DoubleForm form = QLocaleData::DFDecimal;
7083 switch (QtMiscUtils::toAsciiLower(ch: *c)) {
7084 case 'e': form = QLocaleData::DFExponent; break;
7085 case 'a': // not supported - decimal form used instead
7086 case 'f': form = QLocaleData::DFDecimal; break;
7087 case 'g': form = QLocaleData::DFSignificantDigits; break;
7088 default: break;
7089 }
7090 subst = QLocaleData::c()->doubleToString(d, precision, form, width, flags);
7091 ++c;
7092 break;
7093 }
7094 case 'c': {
7095 if (length_mod == lm_l)
7096 subst = QChar::fromUcs2(va_arg(ap, int));
7097 else
7098 subst = QLatin1Char((uchar) va_arg(ap, int));
7099 ++c;
7100 break;
7101 }
7102 case 's': {
7103 if (length_mod == lm_l) {
7104 const ushort *buff = va_arg(ap, const ushort*);
7105 const ushort *ch = buff;
7106 while (precision != 0 && *ch != 0) {
7107 ++ch;
7108 --precision;
7109 }
7110 subst.setUtf16(autf16: buff, asize: ch - buff);
7111 } else if (precision == -1) {
7112 subst = QString::fromUtf8(va_arg(ap, const char*));
7113 } else {
7114 const char *buff = va_arg(ap, const char*);
7115 subst = QString::fromUtf8(utf8: buff, size: qstrnlen(str: buff, maxlen: precision));
7116 }
7117 ++c;
7118 break;
7119 }
7120 case 'p': {
7121 void *arg = va_arg(ap, void*);
7122 const quint64 i = reinterpret_cast<quintptr>(arg);
7123 flags |= QLocaleData::ShowBase;
7124 subst = QLocaleData::c()->unsLongLongToString(l: i, precision, base: 16, width, flags);
7125 ++c;
7126 break;
7127 }
7128 case 'n':
7129 switch (length_mod) {
7130 case lm_hh: {
7131 signed char *n = va_arg(ap, signed char*);
7132 *n = result.size();
7133 break;
7134 }
7135 case lm_h: {
7136 short int *n = va_arg(ap, short int*);
7137 *n = result.size();
7138 break;
7139 }
7140 case lm_l: {
7141 long int *n = va_arg(ap, long int*);
7142 *n = result.size();
7143 break;
7144 }
7145 case lm_ll: {
7146 qint64 *n = va_arg(ap, qint64*);
7147 *n = result.size();
7148 break;
7149 }
7150 default: {
7151 int *n = va_arg(ap, int*);
7152 *n = result.size();
7153 break;
7154 }
7155 }
7156 ++c;
7157 break;
7158
7159 default: // bad escape, treat as non-escape text
7160 for (const char *cc = escape_start; cc != c; ++cc)
7161 result.append(ch: QLatin1Char(*cc));
7162 continue;
7163 }
7164
7165 if (flags & QLocaleData::LeftAdjusted)
7166 result.append(str: subst.leftJustified(width));
7167 else
7168 result.append(str: subst.rightJustified(width));
7169 }
7170
7171 return result;
7172}
7173
7174/*!
7175 \fn QString::toLongLong(bool *ok, int base) const
7176
7177 Returns the string converted to a \c{long long} using base \a
7178 base, which is 10 by default and must be between 2 and 36, or 0.
7179 Returns 0 if the conversion fails.
7180
7181 If \a ok is not \nullptr, failure is reported by setting *\a{ok}
7182 to \c false, and success by setting *\a{ok} to \c true.
7183
7184 If \a base is 0, the C language convention is used: if the string begins
7185 with "0x", base 16 is used; otherwise, if the string begins with "0b", base
7186 2 is used; otherwise, if the string begins with "0", base 8 is used;
7187 otherwise, base 10 is used.
7188
7189 The string conversion will always happen in the 'C' locale. For
7190 locale-dependent conversion use QLocale::toLongLong()
7191
7192 Example:
7193
7194 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 74
7195
7196 This function ignores leading and trailing whitespace.
7197
7198 \note Support for the "0b" prefix was added in Qt 6.4.
7199
7200 \sa number(), toULongLong(), toInt(), QLocale::toLongLong()
7201*/
7202
7203template <typename Int>
7204static Int toIntegral(QStringView string, bool *ok, int base)
7205{
7206#if defined(QT_CHECK_RANGE)
7207 if (base != 0 && (base < 2 || base > 36)) {
7208 qWarning("QString::toIntegral: Invalid base (%d)", base);
7209 base = 10;
7210 }
7211#endif
7212
7213 QVarLengthArray<uchar> latin1(string.size());
7214 qt_to_latin1(dst: latin1.data(), src: string.utf16(), length: string.size());
7215 if constexpr (std::is_signed_v<Int>)
7216 return QLocaleData::bytearrayToLongLong(num: latin1, base, ok);
7217 else
7218 return QLocaleData::bytearrayToUnsLongLong(num: latin1, base, ok);
7219}
7220
7221qlonglong QString::toIntegral_helper(QStringView string, bool *ok, int base)
7222{
7223 return toIntegral<qlonglong>(string, ok, base);
7224}
7225
7226/*!
7227 \fn QString::toULongLong(bool *ok, int base) const
7228
7229 Returns the string converted to an \c{unsigned long long} using base \a
7230 base, which is 10 by default and must be between 2 and 36, or 0.
7231 Returns 0 if the conversion fails.
7232
7233 If \a ok is not \nullptr, failure is reported by setting *\a{ok}
7234 to \c false, and success by setting *\a{ok} to \c true.
7235
7236 If \a base is 0, the C language convention is used: if the string begins
7237 with "0x", base 16 is used; otherwise, if the string begins with "0b", base
7238 2 is used; otherwise, if the string begins with "0", base 8 is used;
7239 otherwise, base 10 is used.
7240
7241 The string conversion will always happen in the 'C' locale. For
7242 locale-dependent conversion use QLocale::toULongLong()
7243
7244 Example:
7245
7246 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 79
7247
7248 This function ignores leading and trailing whitespace.
7249
7250 \note Support for the "0b" prefix was added in Qt 6.4.
7251
7252 \sa number(), toLongLong(), QLocale::toULongLong()
7253*/
7254
7255qulonglong QString::toIntegral_helper(QStringView string, bool *ok, uint base)
7256{

7260/*!
7261 \fn long QString::toLong(bool *ok, int base) const
7262
7263 Returns the string converted to a \c long using base \a
7264 base, which is 10 by default and must be between 2 and 36, or 0.
7265 Returns 0 if the conversion fails.
7266
7267 If \a ok is not \nullptr, failure is reported by setting *\a{ok}
7268 to \c false, and success by setting *\a{ok} to \c true.
7269
7270 If \a base is 0, the C language convention is used: if the string begins
7271 with "0x", base 16 is used; otherwise, if the string begins with "0b", base
7272 2 is used; otherwise, if the string begins with "0", base 8 is used;
7273 otherwise, base 10 is used.

7276 locale-dependent conversion use QLocale::toLongLong()

7432/*!

7439 to \c false, and success by setting *\a{ok} to \c true.

7441 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 66
7442
7443 \warning The QString content may only contain valid numerical characters
7444 which includes the plus/minus sign, the character e used in scientific
7445 notation, and the decimal point. Including the unit or additional characters
7446 leads to a conversion error.
7447
7448 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 67

7450 The string conversion will always happen in the 'C' locale. For
7451 locale-dependent conversion use QLocale::toDouble()

7456 thousands group separators. If you need to convert such numbers,
7457 use QLocale::toDouble().
7458
7459 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 69
7460
7461 This function ignores leading and trailing whitespace.
7462
7463 \sa number(), QLocale::setDefault(), QLocale::toDouble(), trimmed()
7464*/

7466double QString::toDouble(bool *ok) const
7467{
7468 return QStringView(*this).toDouble(ok);

7471double QStringView::toDouble(bool *ok) const
7472{
7473 QStringView string = qt_trimmed(s: *this);
7474 QVarLengthArray<uchar> latin1(string.size());
7475 qt_to_latin1(dst: latin1.data(), src: string.utf16(), length: string.size());
7476 auto r = qt_asciiToDouble(num: reinterpret_cast<const char *>(latin1.data()), numLen: string.size());
7477 if (ok != nullptr)
7478 *ok = r.ok();
7479 return r.result;
7480}

7659/*!
7660 \overload
7661*/
7662QString QString::number(qlonglong n, int base)
7663{
7664#if defined(QT_CHECK_RANGE)
7665 if (base < 2 || base > 36) {
7666 qWarning("QString::setNum: Invalid base (%d)", base);
7667 base = 10;
7668 }
7669#endif
7670 bool negative = n < 0;
7671 /*
7672 Negating std::numeric_limits<qlonglong>::min() hits undefined behavior, so
7673 taking an absolute value has to take a slight detour.
7674 */
7675 return qulltoBasicLatin(l: negative ? 1u + qulonglong(-(n + 1)) : qulonglong(n), base, negative);
7676}
7677
7678/*!
7679 \overload
7680*/
7681QString QString::number(qulonglong n, int base)
7682{
7683#if defined(QT_CHECK_RANGE)
7684 if (base < 2 || base > 36) {
7685 qWarning("QString::setNum: Invalid base (%d)", base);
7686 base = 10;
7687 }
7688#endif
7689 return qulltoBasicLatin(l: n, base, negative: false);
7690}

7692
7693/*!
7694 Returns a string representing the floating-point number \a n.
7695
7696 Returns a string that represents \a n, formatted according to the specified
7697 \a format and \a precision.
7698
7699 For formats with an exponent, the exponent will show its sign and have at
7700 least two digits, left-padding the exponent with zero if needed.
7701
7702 \sa setNum(), QLocale::toString(), QLocale::FloatingPointPrecisionOption, {Number Formats}
7703*/
7704QString QString::number(double n, char format, int precision)
7705{
7706 QLocaleData::DoubleForm form = QLocaleData::DFDecimal;
7707
7708 switch (QtMiscUtils::toAsciiLower(ch: format)) {
7709 case 'f':
7710 form = QLocaleData::DFDecimal;
7711 break;
7712 case 'e':
7713 form = QLocaleData::DFExponent;
7714 break;
7715 case 'g':
7716 form = QLocaleData::DFSignificantDigits;
7717 break;
7718 default:
7719#if defined(QT_CHECK_RANGE)
7720 qWarning("QString::setNum: Invalid format char '%c'", format);
7721#endif
7722 break;
7723 }
7724
7725 return qdtoBasicLatin(d: n, form, precision, uppercase: isAsciiUpper(c: format));
7726}
