7728namespace {
7729template<class ResultList, class StringSource>
7730static ResultList splitString(const StringSource &source, QStringView sep,
7731 Qt::SplitBehavior behavior, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
7732{
7733 ResultList list;
7734 typename StringSource::size_type start = 0;
7735 typename StringSource::size_type end;
7736 typename StringSource::size_type extra = 0;
7737 while ((end = QtPrivate::findString(QStringView(source.constData(), source.size()), start + extra, sep, cs)) != -1) {
7738 if (start != end || behavior == Qt::KeepEmptyParts)
7739 list.append(source.sliced(start, end - start));
7740 start = end + sep.size();
7741 extra = (sep.size() == 0 ? 1 : 0);
7742 }
7743 if (start != source.size() || behavior == Qt::KeepEmptyParts)
7744 list.append(source.sliced(start));
7745 return list;
7746}
7747
7748} // namespace
7749
7750/*!
7751 Splits the string into substrings wherever \a sep occurs, and
7752 returns the list of those strings. If \a sep does not match
7753 anywhere in the string, split() returns a single-element list
7754 containing this string.
7755
7756 \a cs specifies whether \a sep should be matched case
7757 sensitively or case insensitively.
7758
7759 If \a behavior is Qt::SkipEmptyParts, empty entries don't
7760 appear in the result. By default, empty entries are kept.
7761
7762 Example:
7763
7764 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 62
7765
7766 If \a sep is empty, split() returns an empty string, followed
7767 by each of the string's characters, followed by another empty string:
7768
7769 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 62-empty
7770
7771 To understand this behavior, recall that the empty string matches
7772 everywhere, so the above is qualitatively the same as:
7773
7774 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 62-slashes
7775
7776 \sa QStringList::join(), section()
7777
7778 \since 5.14
7779*/
7780QStringList QString::split(const QString &sep, Qt::SplitBehavior behavior, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) const
7781{
7782 return splitString<QStringList>(source: *this, sep, behavior, cs);
7783}
7784
7785/*!
7786 \overload
7787 \since 5.14
7788*/
7789QStringList QString::split(QChar sep, Qt::SplitBehavior behavior, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) const
7790{
7791 return splitString<QStringList>(source: *this, sep: QStringView(&sep, 1), behavior, cs);
7792}
7793
7794/*!
7795 \fn QList<QStringView> QStringView::split(QChar sep, Qt::SplitBehavior behavior, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) const
7796 \fn QList<QStringView> QStringView::split(QStringView sep, Qt::SplitBehavior behavior, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) const
7797
7798
7799 Splits the view into substring views wherever \a sep occurs, and
7800 returns the list of those string views.
7801
7802 See QString::split() for how \a sep, \a behavior and \a cs interact to form
7803 the result.
7804
7805 \note All the returned views are valid as long as the data referenced by
7806 this string view is valid. Destroying the data will cause all views to
7807 become dangling.
7808
7809 \since 6.0
7810*/
7811QList<QStringView> QStringView::split(QStringView sep, Qt::SplitBehavior behavior, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) const
7812{
7813 return splitString<QList<QStringView>>(source: QStringView(*this), sep, behavior, cs);
7814}
7815
7816QList<QStringView> QStringView::split(QChar sep, Qt::SplitBehavior behavior, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) const
7817{
7818 return split(sep: QStringView(&sep, 1), behavior, cs);
7819}
7820
7821#if QT_CONFIG(regularexpression)
7822namespace {
7823template<class ResultList, typename String, typename MatchingFunction>
7824static ResultList splitString(const String &source, const QRegularExpression &re,
7825 MatchingFunction matchingFunction,
7826 Qt::SplitBehavior behavior)
7827{
7828 ResultList list;
7829 if (!re.isValid()) {
7830 qtWarnAboutInvalidRegularExpression(pattern: re.pattern(), where: "QString::split");
7831 return list;
7832 }
7833
7834 qsizetype start = 0;
7835 qsizetype end = 0;
7836 QRegularExpressionMatchIterator iterator = (re.*matchingFunction)(source, 0, QRegularExpression::NormalMatch, QRegularExpression::NoMatchOption);
7837 while (iterator.hasNext()) {
7838 QRegularExpressionMatch match = iterator.next();
7839 end = match.capturedStart();
7840 if (start != end || behavior == Qt::KeepEmptyParts)
7841 list.append(source.sliced(start, end - start));
7842 start = match.capturedEnd();
7843 }
7844
7845 if (start != source.size() || behavior == Qt::KeepEmptyParts)
7846 list.append(source.sliced(start));
7847
7848 return list;
7849}
7850} // namespace

7852/*!
7853 \overload
7854 \since 5.14
7855
7856 Splits the string into substrings wherever the regular expression
7857 \a re matches, and returns the list of those strings. If \a re
7858 does not match anywhere in the string, split() returns a
7859 single-element list containing this string.
7860
7861 Here is an example where we extract the words in a sentence
7862 using one or more whitespace characters as the separator:
7863
7864 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 90
7865
7866 Here is a similar example, but this time we use any sequence of
7867 non-word characters as the separator:
7868
7869 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 91
7870
7871 Here is a third example where we use a zero-length assertion,
7872 \b{\\b} (word boundary), to split the string into an
7873 alternating sequence of non-word and word tokens:
7874
7875 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 92
7876
7877 \sa QStringList::join(), section()
7878*/
7879QStringList QString::split(const QRegularExpression &re, Qt::SplitBehavior behavior) const
7880{
7881#if QT_VERSION < QT_VERSION_CHECK(7, 0, 0)
7882 const auto matchingFunction = qOverload<const QString &, qsizetype, QRegularExpression::MatchType, QRegularExpression::MatchOptions>(&QRegularExpression::globalMatch);
7883#else
7884 const auto matchingFunction = &QRegularExpression::globalMatch;
7885#endif
7886 return splitString<QStringList>(source: *this,
7887 re,
7888 matchingFunction,
7889 behavior);
7890}

7892/*!
7893 \since 6.0
7894
7895 Splits the string into substring views wherever the regular expression \a re
7896 matches, and returns the list of those strings. If \a re does not match
7897 anywhere in the string, split() returns a single-element list containing
7898 this string as view.
7899
7900 \note The views in the returned list are sub-views of this view; as such,
7901 they reference the same data as it and only remain valid for as long as that
7902 data remains live.
7903*/
7904QList<QStringView> QStringView::split(const QRegularExpression &re, Qt::SplitBehavior behavior) const
7905{
7906 return splitString<QList<QStringView>>(source: *this, re, matchingFunction: &QRegularExpression::globalMatchView, behavior);
7907}

7911/*!
7912 \enum QString::NormalizationForm
7913
7914 This enum describes the various normalized forms of Unicode text.
7915
7916 \value NormalizationForm_D Canonical Decomposition
7917 \value NormalizationForm_C Canonical Decomposition followed by Canonical Composition
7918 \value NormalizationForm_KD Compatibility Decomposition
7919 \value NormalizationForm_KC Compatibility Decomposition followed by Canonical Composition
7920
7921 \sa normalized(),
7922 {https://www.unicode.org/reports/tr15/}{Unicode Standard Annex #15}
7923*/
7924
7925/*!
7926 \since 4.5
7927
7928 Returns a copy of this string repeated the specified number of \a times.
7929
7930 If \a times is less than 1, an empty string is returned.
7931
7932 Example:
7933
7934 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 8
7935*/
7936QString QString::repeated(qsizetype times) const
7937{
7938 if (d.size == 0)
7939 return *this;
7940
7941 if (times <= 1) {
7942 if (times == 1)
7943 return *this;
7944 return QString();
7945 }
7946
7947 const qsizetype resultSize = times * d.size;
7948
7949 QString result;
7950 result.reserve(asize: resultSize);
7951 if (result.capacity() != resultSize)
7952 return QString(); // not enough memory
7953
7954 memcpy(dest: result.d.data(), src: d.data(), n: d.size * sizeof(QChar));
7955
7956 qsizetype sizeSoFar = d.size;
7957 char16_t *end = result.d.data() + sizeSoFar;
7958
7959 const qsizetype halfResultSize = resultSize >> 1;
7960 while (sizeSoFar <= halfResultSize) {
7961 memcpy(dest: end, src: result.d.data(), n: sizeSoFar * sizeof(QChar));
7962 end += sizeSoFar;
7963 sizeSoFar <<= 1;
7964 }
7965 memcpy(dest: end, src: result.d.data(), n: (resultSize - sizeSoFar) * sizeof(QChar));
7966 result.d.data()[resultSize] = '\0';
7967 result.d.size = resultSize;
7968 return result;
7969}
7970
7971void qt_string_normalize(QString *data, QString::NormalizationForm mode, QChar::UnicodeVersion version, qsizetype from)
7972{
7973 {
7974 // check if it's fully ASCII first, because then we have no work
7975 auto start = reinterpret_cast<const char16_t *>(data->constData());
7976 const char16_t *p = start + from;
7977 if (isAscii_helper(ptr&: p, end: p + data->size() - from))
7978 return;
7979 if (p > start + from)
7980 from = p - start - 1; // need one before the non-ASCII to perform NFC
7981 }
7982
7983 if (version == QChar::Unicode_Unassigned) {
7984 version = QChar::currentUnicodeVersion();
7985 } else if (int(version) <= NormalizationCorrectionsVersionMax) {
7986 const QString &s = *data;
7987 QChar *d = nullptr;
7988 for (const NormalizationCorrection &n : uc_normalization_corrections) {
7989 if (n.version > version) {
7990 qsizetype pos = from;
7991 if (QChar::requiresSurrogates(ucs4: n.ucs4)) {
7992 char16_t ucs4High = QChar::highSurrogate(ucs4: n.ucs4);
7993 char16_t ucs4Low = QChar::lowSurrogate(ucs4: n.ucs4);
7994 char16_t oldHigh = QChar::highSurrogate(ucs4: n.old_mapping);
7995 char16_t oldLow = QChar::lowSurrogate(ucs4: n.old_mapping);
7996 while (pos < s.size() - 1) {
7997 if (s.at(i: pos).unicode() == ucs4High && s.at(i: pos + 1).unicode() == ucs4Low) {
7998 if (!d)
7999 d = data->data();
8000 d[pos] = QChar(oldHigh);
8001 d[++pos] = QChar(oldLow);
8002 }
8003 ++pos;
8004 }
8005 } else {
8006 while (pos < s.size()) {
8007 if (s.at(i: pos).unicode() == n.ucs4) {
8008 if (!d)
8009 d = data->data();
8010 d[pos] = QChar(n.old_mapping);
8011 }
8012 ++pos;
8013 }
8014 }
8015 }
8016 }
8017 }
8018
8019 if (normalizationQuickCheckHelper(str: data, mode, from, lastStable: &from))
8020 return;
8021
8022 decomposeHelper(str: data, canonical: mode < QString::NormalizationForm_KD, version, from);
8023
8024 canonicalOrderHelper(str: data, version, from);
8025
8026 if (mode == QString::NormalizationForm_D || mode == QString::NormalizationForm_KD)
8027 return;
8028
8029 composeHelper(str: data, version, from);
8030}
8031
8032/*!
8033 Returns the string in the given Unicode normalization \a mode,
8034 according to the given \a version of the Unicode standard.
8035*/
8036QString QString::normalized(QString::NormalizationForm mode, QChar::UnicodeVersion version) const
8037{
8038 QString copy = *this;
8039 qt_string_normalize(data: &copy, mode, version, from: 0);
8040 return copy;
8041}
8042
8043#if QT_VERSION < QT_VERSION_CHECK(7, 0, 0)
8044static void checkArgEscape(QStringView s)
8045{
8046 // If we're in here, it means that qArgDigitValue has accepted the
8047 // digit. We can skip the check in case we already know it will
8048 // succeed.
8049 if (!supportUnicodeDigitValuesInArg())
8050 return;
8051
8052 const auto isNonAsciiDigit = [](QChar c) {
8053 return c.unicode() < u'0' || c.unicode() > u'9';
8054 };
8055
8056 if (std::any_of(first: s.begin(), last: s.end(), pred: isNonAsciiDigit)) {
8057 const auto accumulateDigit = [](int partial, QChar digit) {
8058 return partial * 10 + digit.digitValue();
8059 };
8060 const int parsedNumber = std::accumulate(first: s.begin(), last: s.end(), init: 0, binary_op: accumulateDigit);
8061
8062 qWarning(msg: "QString::arg(): the replacement \"%%%ls\" contains non-ASCII digits;\n"
8063 " it is currently being interpreted as the %d-th substitution.\n"
8064 " This is deprecated; support for non-ASCII digits will be dropped\n"
8065 " in a future version of Qt.",
8066 qUtf16Printable(s.toString()),
8067 parsedNumber);
8068 }
8069}
8070#endif
8071
8072struct ArgEscapeData
8073{
8074 int min_escape; // lowest escape sequence number
8075 qsizetype occurrences; // number of occurrences of the lowest escape sequence number
8076 qsizetype locale_occurrences; // number of occurrences of the lowest escape sequence number that
8077 // contain 'L'
8078 qsizetype escape_len; // total length of escape sequences which will be replaced
8079};
8080
8081static ArgEscapeData findArgEscapes(QStringView s)
8082{
8083 const QChar *uc_begin = s.begin();
8084 const QChar *uc_end = s.end();
8085
8086 ArgEscapeData d;
8087
8088 d.min_escape = INT_MAX;
8089 d.occurrences = 0;
8090 d.escape_len = 0;
8091 d.locale_occurrences = 0;
8092
8093 const QChar *c = uc_begin;
8094 while (c != uc_end) {
8095 while (c != uc_end && c->unicode() != '%')
8096 ++c;
8097
8098 if (c == uc_end)
8099 break;
8100 const QChar *escape_start = c;
8101 if (++c == uc_end)
8102 break;
8103
8104 bool locale_arg = false;
8105 if (c->unicode() == 'L') {
8106 locale_arg = true;
8107 if (++c == uc_end)
8108 break;
8109 }
8110
8111 int escape = qArgDigitValue(ch: *c);
8112 if (escape == -1)
8113 continue;
8114
8115 // ### Qt 7: do not allow anything but ASCII digits
8116 // in arg()'s replacements.
8117#if QT_VERSION <= QT_VERSION_CHECK(7, 0, 0)
8118 const QChar *escapeBegin = c;
8119 const QChar *escapeEnd = escapeBegin + 1;
8120#endif
8121
8122 ++c;
8123
8124 if (c != uc_end) {
8125 const int next_escape = qArgDigitValue(ch: *c);
8126 if (next_escape != -1) {
8127 escape = (10 * escape) + next_escape;
8128 ++c;
8129#if QT_VERSION <= QT_VERSION_CHECK(7, 0, 0)
8130 ++escapeEnd;
8131#endif
8132 }
8133 }
8134
8135#if QT_VERSION <= QT_VERSION_CHECK(7, 0, 0)
8136 checkArgEscape(s: QStringView(escapeBegin, escapeEnd));
8137#endif
8138
8139 if (escape > d.min_escape)
8140 continue;
8141
8142 if (escape < d.min_escape) {
8143 d.min_escape = escape;
8144 d.occurrences = 0;
8145 d.escape_len = 0;
8146 d.locale_occurrences = 0;
8147 }
8148
8149 ++d.occurrences;
8150 if (locale_arg)
8151 ++d.locale_occurrences;
8152 d.escape_len += c - escape_start;
8153 }
8154 return d;
8155}
8156
8157static QString replaceArgEscapes(QStringView s, const ArgEscapeData &d, qsizetype field_width,
8158 QStringView arg, QStringView larg, QChar fillChar)
8159{
8160 // Negative field-width for right-padding, positive for left-padding:
8161 const qsizetype abs_field_width = qAbs(t: field_width);
8162 const qsizetype result_len =
8163 s.size() - d.escape_len
8164 + (d.occurrences - d.locale_occurrences) * qMax(a: abs_field_width, b: arg.size())
8165 + d.locale_occurrences * qMax(a: abs_field_width, b: larg.size());
8166
8167 QString result(result_len, Qt::Uninitialized);
8168 QChar *rc = const_cast<QChar *>(result.unicode());
8169 QChar *const result_end = rc + result_len;
8170 qsizetype repl_cnt = 0;
8171
8172 const QChar *c = s.begin();
8173 const QChar *const uc_end = s.end();
8174 while (c != uc_end) {
8175 Q_ASSERT(d.occurrences > repl_cnt);
8176 /* We don't have to check increments of c against uc_end because, as
8177 long as d.occurrences > repl_cnt, we KNOW there are valid escape
8178 sequences remaining. */
8179
8180 const QChar *text_start = c;
8181 while (c->unicode() != '%')
8182 ++c;
8183
8184 const QChar *escape_start = c++;
8185 const bool localize = c->unicode() == 'L';
8186 if (localize)
8187 ++c;
8188
8189 int escape = qArgDigitValue(ch: *c);
8190 if (escape != -1 && c + 1 != uc_end) {
8191 const int digit = qArgDigitValue(ch: c[1]);
8192 if (digit != -1) {
8193 ++c;
8194 escape = 10 * escape + digit;
8195 }
8196 }
8197
8198 if (escape != d.min_escape) {
8199 memcpy(dest: rc, src: text_start, n: (c - text_start) * sizeof(QChar));
8200 rc += c - text_start;
8201 } else {
8202 ++c;
8203
8204 memcpy(dest: rc, src: text_start, n: (escape_start - text_start) * sizeof(QChar));
8205 rc += escape_start - text_start;
8206
8207 const QStringView use = localize ? larg : arg;
8208 const qsizetype pad_chars = abs_field_width - use.size();
8209 // (If negative, relevant loops are no-ops: no need to check.)
8210
8211 if (field_width > 0) { // left padded
8212 rc = std::fill_n(rc, pad_chars, fillChar);
8213 }
8214
8215 memcpy(dest: rc, src: use.data(), n: use.size() * sizeof(QChar));
8216 rc += use.size();
8217
8218 if (field_width < 0) { // right padded
8219 rc = std::fill_n(rc, pad_chars, fillChar);
8220 }
8221
8222 if (++repl_cnt == d.occurrences) {
8223 memcpy(dest: rc, src: c, n: (uc_end - c) * sizeof(QChar));
8224 rc += uc_end - c;
8225 Q_ASSERT(rc == result_end);
8226 c = uc_end;
8227 }
8228 }
8229 }
8230 Q_ASSERT(rc == result_end);
8231
8232 return result;
8233}
8234
8235/*!
8236 Returns a copy of this string with the lowest numbered place marker
8237 replaced by string \a a, i.e., \c %1, \c %2, ..., \c %99.
8238
8239 \a fieldWidth specifies the minimum amount of space that argument \a
8240 a shall occupy. If \a a requires less space than \a fieldWidth, it
8241 is padded to \a fieldWidth with character \a fillChar. A positive
8242 \a fieldWidth produces right-aligned text. A negative \a fieldWidth
8243 produces left-aligned text.
8244
8245 This example shows how we might create a \c status string for
8246 reporting progress while processing a list of files:
8247
8248 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 11
8249
8250 First, \c arg(i) replaces \c %1. Then \c arg(total) replaces \c
8251 %2. Finally, \c arg(fileName) replaces \c %3.
8252
8253 One advantage of using arg() over asprintf() is that the order of the
8254 numbered place markers can change, if the application's strings are
8255 translated into other languages, but each arg() will still replace
8256 the lowest numbered unreplaced place marker, no matter where it
8257 appears. Also, if place marker \c %i appears more than once in the
8258 string, the arg() replaces all of them.
8259
8260 If there is no unreplaced place marker remaining, a warning message
8261 is output and the result is undefined. Place marker numbers must be
8262 in the range 1 to 99.
8263*/
8264QString QString::arg(const QString &a, int fieldWidth, QChar fillChar) const
8265{
8266 return arg(a: qToStringViewIgnoringNull(s: a), fieldWidth, fillChar);
8267}
8268
8269/*!
8270 \overload
8271 \since 5.10
8272
8273 Returns a copy of this string with the lowest-numbered place-marker
8274 replaced by string \a a, i.e., \c %1, \c %2, ..., \c %99.
8275
8276 \a fieldWidth specifies the minimum amount of space that \a a
8277 shall occupy. If \a a requires less space than \a fieldWidth, it
8278 is padded to \a fieldWidth with character \a fillChar. A positive
8279 \a fieldWidth produces right-aligned text. A negative \a fieldWidth
8280 produces left-aligned text.
8281
8282 This example shows how we might create a \c status string for
8283 reporting progress while processing a list of files:
8284
8285 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 11-qstringview
8286
8287 First, \c arg(i) replaces \c %1. Then \c arg(total) replaces \c
8288 %2. Finally, \c arg(fileName) replaces \c %3.
8289
8290 One advantage of using arg() over asprintf() is that the order of the
8291 numbered place markers can change, if the application's strings are
8292 translated into other languages, but each arg() will still replace
8293 the lowest-numbered unreplaced place-marker, no matter where it
8294 appears. Also, if place-marker \c %i appears more than once in the
8295 string, arg() replaces all of them.
8296
8297 If there is no unreplaced place-marker remaining, a warning message
8298 is printed and the result is undefined. Place-marker numbers must be
8299 in the range 1 to 99.
8300*/
8301QString QString::arg(QStringView a, int fieldWidth, QChar fillChar) const
8302{
8303 ArgEscapeData d = findArgEscapes(s: *this);
8304
8305 if (Q_UNLIKELY(d.occurrences == 0)) {
8306 qWarning(msg: "QString::arg: Argument missing: %ls, %ls", qUtf16Printable(*this),
8307 qUtf16Printable(a.toString()));
8308 return *this;
8309 }
8310 return replaceArgEscapes(s: *this, d, field_width: fieldWidth, arg: a, larg: a, fillChar);
8311}

8411 giving octal, 10 decimal, and 16 hexadecimal numbers.

8416/*!
8417 \overload arg()
8418
8419 \a fieldWidth specifies the minimum amount of space that \a a is
8420 padded to and filled with the character \a fillChar. A positive
8421 value produces right-aligned text; a negative value produces
8422 left-aligned text.
8423
8424 The \a base argument specifies the base to use when converting the
8425 integer \a a into a string. The base must be between 2 and 36, with
8426 8 giving octal, 10 decimal, and 16 hexadecimal numbers.
8427
8428 \sa {Number Formats}
8429*/
8430QString QString::arg(qlonglong a, int fieldWidth, int base, QChar fillChar) const
8431{
8432 ArgEscapeData d = findArgEscapes(s: *this);
8433
8434 if (d.occurrences == 0) {
8435 qWarning() << "QString::arg: Argument missing:" << *this << ',' << a;
8436 return *this;
8437 }
8438
8439 unsigned flags = QLocaleData::NoFlags;
8440 // ZeroPadded sorts out left-padding when the fill is zero, to the right of sign:
8441 if (fillChar == u'0')
8442 flags = QLocaleData::ZeroPadded;
8443
8444 QString arg;
8445 if (d.occurrences > d.locale_occurrences) {
8446 arg = QLocaleData::c()->longLongToString(l: a, precision: -1, base, width: fieldWidth, flags);
8447 Q_ASSERT(fillChar != u'0' || !qIsFinite(a)
8448 || fieldWidth <= arg.size());
8449 }
8450
8451 QString localeArg;
8452 if (d.locale_occurrences > 0) {
8453 QLocale locale;
8454 if (!(locale.numberOptions() & QLocale::OmitGroupSeparator))
8455 flags |= QLocaleData::GroupDigits;
8456 localeArg = locale.d->m_data->longLongToString(l: a, precision: -1, base, width: fieldWidth, flags);
8457 Q_ASSERT(fillChar != u'0' || !qIsFinite(a)
8458 || fieldWidth <= localeArg.size());
8459 }
8460
8461 return replaceArgEscapes(s: *this, d, field_width: fieldWidth, arg, larg: localeArg, fillChar);
8462}

8470 left-aligned text.
8471

8474 giving octal, 10 decimal, and 16 hexadecimal numbers.

8563/*!
8564 \overload arg()
8565
8566 Argument \a a is formatted according to the specified \a format and
8567 \a precision. See \l{Floating-point Formats} for details.
8568
8569 \a fieldWidth specifies the minimum amount of space that \a a is
8570 padded to and filled with the character \a fillChar. A positive
8571 value produces right-aligned text; a negative value produces
8572 left-aligned text.
8573
8574 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 2
8575
8576 \sa QLocale::toString(), QLocale::FloatingPointPrecisionOption, {Number Formats}
8577*/
8578QString QString::arg(double a, int fieldWidth, char format, int precision, QChar fillChar) const
8579{
8580 ArgEscapeData d = findArgEscapes(s: *this);
8581
8582 if (d.occurrences == 0) {
8583 qWarning(msg: "QString::arg: Argument missing: %s, %g", toLocal8Bit().data(), a);
8584 return *this;
8585 }
8586
8587 unsigned flags = QLocaleData::NoFlags;
8588 // ZeroPadded sorts out left-padding when the fill is zero, to the right of sign:
8589 if (fillChar == u'0')
8590 flags |= QLocaleData::ZeroPadded;
8591
8592 if (isAsciiUpper(c: format))
8593 flags |= QLocaleData::CapitalEorX;
8594
8595 QLocaleData::DoubleForm form = QLocaleData::DFDecimal;
8596 switch (QtMiscUtils::toAsciiLower(ch: format)) {
8597 case 'f':
8598 form = QLocaleData::DFDecimal;
8599 break;
8600 case 'e':
8601 form = QLocaleData::DFExponent;
8602 break;
8603 case 'g':
8604 form = QLocaleData::DFSignificantDigits;
8605 break;
8606 default:
8607#if defined(QT_CHECK_RANGE)
8608 qWarning("QString::arg: Invalid format char '%c'", format);
8609#endif
8610 break;
8611 }
8612
8613 QString arg;
8614 if (d.occurrences > d.locale_occurrences) {
8615 arg = QLocaleData::c()->doubleToString(d: a, precision, form, width: fieldWidth,
8616 flags: flags | QLocaleData::ZeroPadExponent);
8617 Q_ASSERT(fillChar != u'0' || !qIsFinite(a)
8618 || fieldWidth <= arg.size());
8619 }
8620
8621 QString localeArg;
8622 if (d.locale_occurrences > 0) {
8623 QLocale locale;
8624
8625 const QLocale::NumberOptions numberOptions = locale.numberOptions();
8626 if (!(numberOptions & QLocale::OmitGroupSeparator))
8627 flags |= QLocaleData::GroupDigits;
8628 if (!(numberOptions & QLocale::OmitLeadingZeroInExponent))
8629 flags |= QLocaleData::ZeroPadExponent;
8630 if (numberOptions & QLocale::IncludeTrailingZeroesAfterDot)
8631 flags |= QLocaleData::AddTrailingZeroes;
8632 localeArg = locale.d->m_data->doubleToString(d: a, precision, form, width: fieldWidth, flags);
8633 Q_ASSERT(fillChar != u'0' || !qIsFinite(a)
8634 || fieldWidth <= localeArg.size());
8635 }
8636
8637 return replaceArgEscapes(s: *this, d, field_width: fieldWidth, arg, larg: localeArg, fillChar);
8638}
8639
8640static inline char16_t to_unicode(const QChar c) { return c.unicode(); }
8641static inline char16_t to_unicode(const char c) { return QLatin1Char{c}.unicode(); }
8642
8643template <typename Char>
8644static int getEscape(const Char *uc, qsizetype *pos, qsizetype len, int maxNumber = 999)
8645{
8646 qsizetype i = *pos;
8647 ++i;
8648 if (i < len && uc[i] == u'L')
8649 ++i;
8650 if (i < len) {
8651 int escape = to_unicode(uc[i]) - '0';
8652 if (uint(escape) >= 10U)
8653 return -1;
8654 ++i;
8655 while (i < len) {
8656 int digit = to_unicode(uc[i]) - '0';
8657 if (uint(digit) >= 10U)
8658 break;
8659 escape = (escape * 10) + digit;
8660 ++i;
8661 }
8662 if (escape <= maxNumber) {
8663 *pos = i;
8664 return escape;
8665 }
8666 }
8667 return -1;
8668}
8669
8670/*
8671 Algorithm for multiArg:
8672
8673 1. Parse the string as a sequence of verbatim text and placeholders (%L?\d{,3}).
8674 The L is parsed and accepted for compatibility with non-multi-arg, but since
8675 multiArg only accepts strings as replacements, the localization request can
8676 be safely ignored.
8677 2. The result of step (1) is a list of (string-ref,int)-tuples. The string-ref
8678 either points at text to be copied verbatim (in which case the int is -1),
8679 or, initially, at the textual representation of the placeholder. In that case,
8680 the int contains the numerical number as parsed from the placeholder.
8681 3. Next, collect all the non-negative ints found, sort them in ascending order and
8682 remove duplicates.
8683 3a. If the result has more entries than multiArg() was given replacement strings,
8684 we have found placeholders we can't satisfy with replacement strings. That is
8685 fine (there could be another .arg() call coming after this one), so just
8686 truncate the result to the number of actual multiArg() replacement strings.
8687 3b. If the result has less entries than multiArg() was given replacement strings,
8688 the string is missing placeholders. This is an error that the user should be
8689 warned about.
8690 4. The result of step (3) is a mapping from the index of any replacement string to
8691 placeholder number. This is the wrong way around, but since placeholder
8692 numbers could get as large as 999, while we typically don't have more than 9
8693 replacement strings, we trade 4K of sparsely-used memory for doing a reverse lookup
8694 each time we need to map a placeholder number to a replacement string index
8695 (that's a linear search; but still *much* faster than using an associative container).
8696 5. Next, for each of the tuples found in step (1), do the following:
8697 5a. If the int is negative, do nothing.
8698 5b. Otherwise, if the int is found in the result of step (3) at index I, replace
8699 the string-ref with a string-ref for the (complete) I'th replacement string.
8700 5c. Otherwise, do nothing.
8701 6. Concatenate all string refs into a single result string.
8702*/
8703
8704namespace {
8705struct Part
8706{
8707 Part() = default; // for QVarLengthArray; do not use
8708 constexpr Part(QStringView s, int num = -1)
8709 : tag{QtPrivate::ArgBase::U16}, number{num}, data{s.utf16()}, size{s.size()} {}
8710 constexpr Part(QLatin1StringView s, int num = -1)
8711 : tag{QtPrivate::ArgBase::L1}, number{num}, data{s.data()}, size{s.size()} {}
8712
8713 void reset(QStringView s) noexcept { *this = {s, number}; }
8714 void reset(QLatin1StringView s) noexcept { *this = {s, number}; }
8715
8716 QtPrivate::ArgBase::Tag tag;
8717 int number;
8718 const void *data;
8719 qsizetype size;
8720};
8721} // unnamed namespace
8722
8723Q_DECLARE_TYPEINFO(Part, Q_PRIMITIVE_TYPE);
8724
8725namespace {
8726
8727enum { ExpectedParts = 32 };
8728
8729typedef QVarLengthArray<Part, ExpectedParts> ParseResult;
8730typedef QVarLengthArray<int, ExpectedParts/2> ArgIndexToPlaceholderMap;
8731
8732template <typename StringView>
8733static ParseResult parseMultiArgFormatString(StringView s)
8734{
8735 ParseResult result;
8736
8737 const auto uc = s.data();
8738 const auto len = s.size();
8739 const auto end = len - 1;
8740 qsizetype i = 0;
8741 qsizetype last = 0;
8742
8743 while (i < end) {
8744 if (uc[i] == u'%') {
8745 qsizetype percent = i;
8746 int number = getEscape(uc, &i, len);
8747 if (number != -1) {
8748 if (last != percent)
8749 result.push_back(t: Part{s.sliced(last, percent - last)}); // literal text (incl. failed placeholders)
8750 result.push_back(t: Part{s.sliced(percent, i - percent), number}); // parsed placeholder
8751 last = i;
8752 continue;
8753 }
8754 }
8755 ++i;
8756 }
8757
8758 if (last < len)
8759 result.push_back(t: Part{s.sliced(last, len - last)}); // trailing literal text
8760
8761 return result;
8762}
8763
8764static ArgIndexToPlaceholderMap makeArgIndexToPlaceholderMap(const ParseResult &parts)
8765{
8766 ArgIndexToPlaceholderMap result;
8767
8768 for (const Part &part : parts) {
8769 if (part.number >= 0)
8770 result.push_back(t: part.number);
8771 }
8772
8773 std::sort(first: result.begin(), last: result.end());
8774 result.erase(begin: std::unique(first: result.begin(), last: result.end()),
8775 end: result.end());
8776
8777 return result;
8778}
8779
8780static qsizetype resolveStringRefsAndReturnTotalSize(ParseResult &parts, const ArgIndexToPlaceholderMap &argIndexToPlaceholderMap, const QtPrivate::ArgBase *args[])
8781{
8782 using namespace QtPrivate;
8783 qsizetype totalSize = 0;
8784 for (Part &part : parts) {
8785 if (part.number != -1) {
8786 const auto it = std::find(first: argIndexToPlaceholderMap.begin(), last: argIndexToPlaceholderMap.end(), val: part.number);
8787 if (it != argIndexToPlaceholderMap.end()) {
8788 const auto &arg = *args[it - argIndexToPlaceholderMap.begin()];
8789 switch (arg.tag) {
8790 case ArgBase::L1:
8791 part.reset(s: static_cast<const QLatin1StringArg&>(arg).string);
8792 break;
8793 case ArgBase::U8:
8794 Q_UNREACHABLE(); // waiting for QUtf8String...
8795 break;
8796 case ArgBase::U16:
8797 part.reset(s: static_cast<const QStringViewArg&>(arg).string);
8798 break;
8799 }
8800 }
8801 }
8802 totalSize += part.size;
8803 }
8804 return totalSize;
8805}
8806
8807} // unnamed namespace
8808
8809Q_ALWAYS_INLINE QString to_string(QLatin1StringView s) noexcept { return s; }
8810Q_ALWAYS_INLINE QString to_string(QStringView s) noexcept { return s.toString(); }
8811
8812template <typename StringView>
8813static QString argToQStringImpl(StringView pattern, size_t numArgs, const QtPrivate::ArgBase **args)
8814{
8815 // Step 1-2 above
8816 ParseResult parts = parseMultiArgFormatString(pattern);
8817
8818 // 3-4
8819 ArgIndexToPlaceholderMap argIndexToPlaceholderMap = makeArgIndexToPlaceholderMap(parts);
8820
8821 if (static_cast<size_t>(argIndexToPlaceholderMap.size()) > numArgs) // 3a
8822 argIndexToPlaceholderMap.resize(sz: qsizetype(numArgs));
8823 else if (Q_UNLIKELY(static_cast<size_t>(argIndexToPlaceholderMap.size()) < numArgs)) // 3b
8824 qWarning(msg: "QString::arg: %d argument(s) missing in %ls",
8825 int(numArgs - argIndexToPlaceholderMap.size()), qUtf16Printable(to_string(pattern)));
8826
8827 // 5
8828 const qsizetype totalSize = resolveStringRefsAndReturnTotalSize(parts, argIndexToPlaceholderMap, args);
8829
8830 // 6:
8831 QString result(totalSize, Qt::Uninitialized);
8832 auto out = const_cast<QChar*>(result.constData());
8833
8834 for (const Part &part : parts) {
8835 switch (part.tag) {
8836 case QtPrivate::ArgBase::L1:
8837 if (part.size) {
8838 qt_from_latin1(dst: reinterpret_cast<char16_t*>(out),
8839 str: reinterpret_cast<const char*>(part.data), size: part.size);
8840 }
8841 break;
8842 case QtPrivate::ArgBase::U8:
8843 Q_UNREACHABLE(); // waiting for QUtf8String
8844 break;
8845 case QtPrivate::ArgBase::U16:
8846 if (part.size)
8847 memcpy(dest: out, src: part.data, n: part.size * sizeof(QChar));
8848 break;
8849 }
8850 out += part.size;
8851 }
8852
8853 return result;
8854}
8855
8856QString QtPrivate::argToQString(QStringView pattern, size_t n, const ArgBase **args)
8857{
8858 return argToQStringImpl(pattern, numArgs: n, args);
8859}
8860
8861QString QtPrivate::argToQString(QLatin1StringView pattern, size_t n, const ArgBase **args)
8862{
8863 return argToQStringImpl(pattern, numArgs: n, args);
8864}

8866/*! \fn bool QString::isSimpleText() const
8867
8868 \internal
8869*/
8870bool QString::isSimpleText() const
8871{
8872 const char16_t *p = d.data();
8873 const char16_t * const end = p + d.size;
8874 while (p < end) {
8875 char16_t uc = *p;
8876 // sort out regions of complex text formatting
8877 if (uc > 0x058f && (uc < 0x1100 || uc > 0xfb0f)) {
8878 return false;
8879 }
8880 p++;
8881 }
8882
8883 return true;
8884}

8988/*!
8989 \since 6.1
8990
8991 Removes from the string the characters in the half-open range
8992 [ \a first , \a last ). Returns an iterator to the character
8993 immediately after the last erased character (i.e. the character
8994 referred to by \a last before the erase).
8995*/
8996QString::iterator QString::erase(QString::const_iterator first, QString::const_iterator last)
8997{
8998 const auto start = std::distance(first: cbegin(), last: first);
8999 const auto len = std::distance(first: first, last: last);
9000 remove(pos: start, len);
9001 return begin() + start;
9002}

9041/*!
9042 Constructs a QString that uses the first \a size Unicode characters
9043 in the array \a unicode. The data in \a unicode is \e not
9044 copied. The caller must be able to guarantee that \a unicode will
9045 not be deleted or modified as long as the QString (or an
9046 unmodified copy of it) exists.
9047
9048 Any attempts to modify the QString or copies of it will cause it
9049 to create a deep copy of the data, ensuring that the raw data
9050 isn't modified.
9051
9052 Here is an example of how we can use a QRegularExpression on raw data in
9053 memory without requiring to copy the data into a QString:
9054
9055 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 22
9056 \snippet qstring/main.cpp 23
9057
9058 \warning A string created with fromRawData() is \e not
9059 '\\0'-terminated, unless the raw data contains a '\\0' character
9060 at position \a size. This means unicode() will \e not return a
9061 '\\0'-terminated string (although utf16() does, at the cost of
9062 copying the raw data).
9063
9064 \sa fromUtf16(), setRawData()
9065*/
9066QString QString::fromRawData(const QChar *unicode, qsizetype size)
9067{
9068 return QString(DataPointer::fromRawData(rawData: const_cast<char16_t *>(reinterpret_cast<const char16_t *>(unicode)), length: size));
9069}

9071/*!
9072 \since 4.7
9073
9074 Resets the QString to use the first \a size Unicode characters
9075 in the array \a unicode. The data in \a unicode is \e not
9076 copied. The caller must be able to guarantee that \a unicode will
9077 not be deleted or modified as long as the QString (or an
9078 unmodified copy of it) exists.
9079
9080 This function can be used instead of fromRawData() to re-use
9081 existings QString objects to save memory re-allocations.
9082
9083 \sa fromRawData()
9084*/
9085QString &QString::setRawData(const QChar *unicode, qsizetype size)
9086{
9087 if (!unicode || !size) {
9088 clear();
9089 }
9090 *this = fromRawData(unicode, size);
9091 return *this;
9092}

9134/*! \class QLatin1StringView
9135 \inmodule QtCore
9136 \brief The QLatin1StringView class provides a thin wrapper around
9137 a US-ASCII/Latin-1 encoded string literal.
9138
9139 \ingroup string-processing
9140 \reentrant
9141
9142 Many of QString's member functions are overloaded to accept
9143 \c{const char *} instead of QString. This includes the copy
9144 constructor, the assignment operator, the comparison operators,
9145 and various other functions such as \l{QString::insert()}{insert()},
9146 \l{QString::append()}{append()}, and \l{QString::prepend()}{prepend()}.
9147 Some of these functions are optimized to avoid constructing a
9148 QString object for the \c{const char *} data. For example,
9149 assuming \c str is a QString,
9150
9151 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 3
9152
9153 is much faster than
9154
9155 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 4
9156
9157 because it doesn't construct four temporary QString objects and
9158 make a deep copy of the character data.
9159
9160 However, that is not true for all QString member functions that take
9161 \c{const char *} and therefore applications should assume a temporary will
9162 be created, such as in
9163
9164 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 4bis
9165
9166 Applications that define \l QT_NO_CAST_FROM_ASCII (as explained
9167 in the QString documentation) don't have access to QString's
9168 \c{const char *} API. To provide an efficient way of specifying
9169 constant Latin-1 strings, Qt provides the QLatin1StringView, which is
9170 just a very thin wrapper around a \c{const char *}. Using
9171 QLatin1StringView, the example code above becomes
9172
9173 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 5
9174
9175 This is a bit longer to type, but it provides exactly the same
9176 benefits as the first version of the code, and is faster than
9177 converting the Latin-1 strings using QString::fromLatin1().
9178
9179 Thanks to the QString(QLatin1StringView) constructor,
9180 QLatin1StringView can be used everywhere a QString is expected. For
9181 example:
9182
9183 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 6
9184
9185 \note If the function you're calling with a QLatin1StringView
9186 argument isn't actually overloaded to take QLatin1StringView, the
9187 implicit conversion to QString will trigger a memory allocation,
9188 which is usually what you want to avoid by using QLatin1StringView
9189 in the first place. In those cases, using QStringLiteral may be
9190 the better option.
9191
9192 \sa QString, QLatin1Char, {QStringLiteral()}{QStringLiteral},
9193 QT_NO_CAST_FROM_ASCII
9194*/
9195
9196/*!
9197 \class QLatin1String
9198 \inmodule QtCore
9199 \brief QLatin1String is the same as QLatin1StringView.
9200
9201 QLatin1String is a view to a Latin-1 string. It's the same as
9202 QLatin1StringView and is kept for compatibility reasons. It is
9203 recommended to use QLatin1StringView instead.
9204
9205 Please see the QLatin1StringView documentation for details.
9206*/

9308/*! \fn QLatin1StringView::QLatin1StringView(const char *str, qsizetype size)
9309
9310 Constructs a QLatin1StringView object that stores \a str with \a size.
9311
9312 The string data is \e not copied. The caller must be able to
9313 guarantee that \a str will not be deleted or modified as long as
9314 the QLatin1StringView object exists.
9315
9316 \note: any null ('\\0') bytes in the byte array will be included in this
9317 string, which will be converted to Unicode null characters (U+0000) if this
9318 string is used by QString. This behavior is different from Qt 5.x.
9319
9320 \sa latin1()
9321*/
9322
9323/*!
9324 \fn QLatin1StringView::QLatin1StringView(const char *first, const char *last)
9325 \since 5.10
9326
9327 Constructs a QLatin1StringView object that stores \a first with length
9328 (\a last - \a first).
9329
9330 The range \c{[first,last)} must remain valid for the lifetime of
9331 this Latin-1 string object.
9332
9333 Passing \nullptr as \a first is safe if \a last is \nullptr,
9334 too, and results in a null Latin-1 string.
9335
9336 The behavior is undefined if \a last precedes \a first, \a first
9337 is \nullptr and \a last is not, or if \c{last - first >
9338 INT_MAX}.
9339*/
9340

9618/*!
9619 \fn qsizetype QLatin1StringView::lastIndexOf(QStringView str, qsizetype from, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) const
9620 \fn qsizetype QLatin1StringView::lastIndexOf(QLatin1StringView l1, qsizetype from, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) const
9621 \fn qsizetype QLatin1StringView::lastIndexOf(QChar c, qsizetype from, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) const
9622 \since 5.14
9623
9624 Returns the index position in this Latin-1 string view of the last
9625 occurrence of the UTF-16 string viewed by \a str, the Latin-1 string
9626 viewed by \a l1, or the character \a ch, respectively, searching backward
9627 from index position \a from; returns -1 if \a str, \a l1 or \a ch is not
9628 found, respectively.
9629
9630 \include qstring.qdocinc negative-index-start-search-from-end
9631
9632 \include qstring.qdocinc {search-comparison-case-sensitivity} {search}
9633
9634 \note When searching for a 0-length \a str or \a l1, the match at
9635 the end of the data is excluded from the search by a negative \a
9636 from, even though \c{-1} is normally thought of as searching from
9637 the end of the string: the match at the end is \e after the last
9638 character, so it is excluded. To include such a final empty match,
9639 either give a positive value for \a from or omit the \a from
9640 parameter entirely.

9793/*!
9794 \fn QLatin1StringView QLatin1StringView::mid(qsizetype start, qsizetype length) const
9795 \since 5.8
9796
9797 Returns the substring of length \a length starting at position
9798 \a start in this Latin-1 string view.
9799
9800 If you know that \a start and \a length cannot be out of bounds, use
9801 sliced() instead in new code, because it is faster.
9802
9803 Returns an empty Latin-1 string view if \a start exceeds the length
9804 of this string view. If there are less than \a length characters available
9805 in this string view starting at \a start, or if \a length is negative
9806 (default), the function returns all characters that are available from
9807 \a start.
9808
9809 \sa first(), last(), sliced(), chopped(), chop(), truncate()
9810*/

9817 new code, because it is faster.

9820 0 in this Latin-1 string view.
9821
9822 The entire Latin-1 string view is returned if \a length is greater
9823 than or equal to size(), or less than zero.

9836 size() - \a length in this Latin-1 string view.

9838 The entire Latin-1 string view is returned if \a length is greater

9955 \l QT_NO_CAST_FROM_ASCII when you compile your applications. This
9956 can be useful if you want to ensure that all user-visible strings
9957 go through QObject::tr(), for example.

9978 \since 4.3

10321/*!
10322 \fn qlonglong QLatin1StringView::toLongLong(bool *ok, int base) const
10323 \fn qulonglong QLatin1StringView::toULongLong(bool *ok, int base) const
10324 \fn int QLatin1StringView::toInt(bool *ok, int base) const
10325 \fn uint QLatin1StringView::toUInt(bool *ok, int base) const
10326 \fn long QLatin1StringView::toLong(bool *ok, int base) const
10327 \fn ulong QLatin1StringView::toULong(bool *ok, int base) const
10328 \fn short QLatin1StringView::toShort(bool *ok, int base) const
10329 \fn ushort QLatin1StringView::toUShort(bool *ok, int base) const
10330
10331 \since 6.4
10332
10333 Returns this QLatin1StringView converted to a corresponding numeric value using
10334 base \a base, which is ten by default. Bases 0 and 2 through 36 are supported,
10335 using letters for digits beyond 9; A is ten, B is eleven and so on.
10336
10337 If \a base is 0, the base is determined automatically using the following
10338 rules (in this order), if the Latin-1 string view begins with:
10339
10340 \list
10341 \li \c "0x", the rest of it is read as hexadecimal (base 16)
10342 \li \c "0b", the rest of it is read as binary (base 2)
10343 \li \c "0", the rest of it is read as octal (base 8)
10344 \li otherwise it is read as decimal
10345 \endlist
10346
10347 Returns 0 if the conversion fails.
10348
10349 If \a ok is not \nullptr, failure is reported by setting *\a{ok}
10350 to \c false, and success by setting *\a{ok} to \c true.
10351
10352//! [latin1-numeric-conversion-note]
10353 \note The conversion of the number is performed in the default C locale,
10354 regardless of the user's locale. Use QLocale to perform locale-aware
10355 conversions between numbers and strings.
10356
10357 This function ignores leading and trailing spacing characters.
10358//! [latin1-numeric-conversion-note]
10359
10360 \note Support for the "0b" prefix was added in Qt 6.4.
10361*/
10362
10363/*!
10364 \fn double QLatin1StringView::toDouble(bool *ok) const
10365 \fn float QLatin1StringView::toFloat(bool *ok) const
10366 \since 6.4
10367
10368 Returns this QLatin1StringView converted to a corresponding floating-point value.
10369
10370 Returns an infinity if the conversion overflows or 0.0 if the
10371 conversion fails for other reasons (e.g. underflow).
10372
10373 If \a ok is not \nullptr, failure is reported by setting *\a{ok}
10374 to \c false, and success by setting *\a{ok} to \c true.
10375
10376 \warning The QLatin1StringView content may only contain valid numerical
10377 characters which includes the plus/minus sign, the character e used in
10378 scientific notation, and the decimal point. Including the unit or additional
10379 characters leads to a conversion error.
10380
10381 \include qstring.cpp latin1-numeric-conversion-note
10382*/
10383
10384#if !defined(QT_NO_DATASTREAM) || defined(QT_BOOTSTRAPPED)
10385/*!
10386 \fn QDataStream &operator<<(QDataStream &stream, const QString &string)
10387 \relates QString
10388
10389 Writes the given \a string to the specified \a stream.
10390
10391 \sa {Serializing Qt Data Types}
10392*/
10393
10394QDataStream &operator<<(QDataStream &out, const QString &str)
10395{
10396 if (out.version() == 1) {
10397 out << str.toLatin1();
10398 } else {
10399 if (!str.isNull() || out.version() < 3) {
10400 if ((out.byteOrder() == QDataStream::BigEndian) == (QSysInfo::ByteOrder == QSysInfo::BigEndian)) {
10401 out.writeBytes(reinterpret_cast<const char *>(str.unicode()),
10402 len: static_cast<uint>(sizeof(QChar) * str.size()));
10403 } else {
10404 QVarLengthArray<char16_t> buffer(str.size());
10405 qbswap<sizeof(char16_t)>(source: str.constData(), count: str.size(), dest: buffer.data());
10406 out.writeBytes(reinterpret_cast<const char *>(buffer.data()),
10407 len: static_cast<uint>(sizeof(char16_t) * buffer.size()));
10408 }
10409 } else {
10410 // write null marker
10411 out << (quint32)0xffffffff;
10412 }
10413 }
10414 return out;
10415}
10416
10417/*!
10418 \fn QDataStream &operator>>(QDataStream &stream, QString &string)
10419 \relates QString
10420
10421 Reads a string from the specified \a stream into the given \a string.
10422
10423 \sa {Serializing Qt Data Types}
10424*/
10425
10426QDataStream &operator>>(QDataStream &in, QString &str)
10427{
10428 if (in.version() == 1) {
10429 QByteArray l;
10430 in >> l;
10431 str = QString::fromLatin1(ba: l);
10432 } else {
10433 quint32 bytes = 0;
10434 in >> bytes; // read size of string
10435 if (bytes == 0xffffffff) { // null string
10436 str.clear();
10437 } else if (bytes > 0) { // not empty
10438 if (bytes & 0x1) {
10439 str.clear();
10440 in.setStatus(QDataStream::ReadCorruptData);
10441 return in;
10442 }
10443
10444 const quint32 Step = 1024 * 1024;
10445 quint32 len = bytes / 2;
10446 quint32 allocated = 0;
10447
10448 while (allocated < len) {
10449 int blockSize = qMin(a: Step, b: len - allocated);
10450 str.resize(size: allocated + blockSize);
10451 if (in.readRawData(reinterpret_cast<char *>(str.data()) + allocated * 2,
10452 len: blockSize * 2) != blockSize * 2) {
10453 str.clear();
10454 in.setStatus(QDataStream::ReadPastEnd);
10455 return in;
10456 }
10457 allocated += blockSize;
10458 }
10459
10460 if ((in.byteOrder() == QDataStream::BigEndian)
10461 != (QSysInfo::ByteOrder == QSysInfo::BigEndian)) {
10462 char16_t *data = reinterpret_cast<char16_t *>(str.data());
10463 qbswap<sizeof(*data)>(source: data, count: len, dest: data);
10464 }
10465 } else {
10466 str = QString(QLatin1StringView(""));
10467 }
10468 }
10469 return in;
10470}
10471#endif // QT_NO_DATASTREAM

10488/*!
10489 \since 5.11
10490 \internal
10491 \relates QStringView
10492
10493 Returns \c true if the string is read right to left.
10494
10495 \sa QString::isRightToLeft()
10496*/
10497bool QtPrivate::isRightToLeft(QStringView string) noexcept
10498{
10499 int isolateLevel = 0;
10500
10501 for (QStringIterator i(string); i.hasNext();) {
10502 const char32_t c = i.next();
10503
10504 switch (QChar::direction(ucs4: c)) {
10505 case QChar::DirRLI:
10506 case QChar::DirLRI:
10507 case QChar::DirFSI:
10508 ++isolateLevel;
10509 break;
10510 case QChar::DirPDI:
10511 if (isolateLevel)
10512 --isolateLevel;
10513 break;
10514 case QChar::DirL:
10515 if (isolateLevel)
10516 break;
10517 return false;
10518 case QChar::DirR:
10519 case QChar::DirAL:
10520 if (isolateLevel)
10521 break;
10522 return true;
10523 case QChar::DirEN:
10524 case QChar::DirES:
10525 case QChar::DirET:
10526 case QChar::DirAN:
10527 case QChar::DirCS:
10528 case QChar::DirB:
10529 case QChar::DirS:
10530 case QChar::DirWS:
10531 case QChar::DirON:
10532 case QChar::DirLRE:
10533 case QChar::DirLRO:
10534 case QChar::DirRLE:
10535 case QChar::DirRLO:
10536 case QChar::DirPDF:
10537 case QChar::DirNSM:
10538 case QChar::DirBN:
10539 break;
10540 }
10541 }
10542 return false;
10543}
10544
10545qsizetype QtPrivate::count(QStringView haystack, QStringView needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
10546{
10547 qsizetype num = 0;
10548 qsizetype i = -1;
10549 if (haystack.size() > 500 && needle.size() > 5) {
10550 QStringMatcher matcher(needle, cs);
10551 while ((i = matcher.indexIn(str: haystack, from: i + 1)) != -1)
10552 ++num;
10553 } else {
10554 while ((i = QtPrivate::findString(haystack, from: i + 1, needle, cs)) != -1)
10555 ++num;
10556 }
10557 return num;
10558}
10559
10560qsizetype QtPrivate::count(QStringView haystack, QChar needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
10561{
10562 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive)
10563 return std::count(first: haystack.cbegin(), last: haystack.cend(), value: needle);
10564
10565 needle = foldCase(ch: needle);
10566 return std::count_if(first: haystack.cbegin(), last: haystack.cend(),
10567 pred: [needle](const QChar c) { return foldAndCompare(a: c, b: needle); });
10568}
10569
10570qsizetype QtPrivate::count(QLatin1StringView haystack, QLatin1StringView needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
10571{
10572 qsizetype num = 0;
10573 qsizetype i = -1;
10574
10575 QLatin1StringMatcher matcher(needle, cs);
10576 while ((i = matcher.indexIn(haystack, from: i + 1)) != -1)
10577 ++num;
10578
10579 return num;
10580}
10581
10582qsizetype QtPrivate::count(QLatin1StringView haystack, QStringView needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
10583{
10584 if (haystack.size() < needle.size())
10585 return 0;
10586
10587 if (!QtPrivate::isLatin1(s: needle)) // won't find non-L1 UTF-16 needles in a L1 haystack!
10588 return 0;
10589
10590 qsizetype num = 0;
10591 qsizetype i = -1;
10592
10593 QVarLengthArray<uchar> s(needle.size());
10594 qt_to_latin1_unchecked(dst: s.data(), src: needle.utf16(), length: needle.size());
10595
10596 QLatin1StringMatcher matcher(QLatin1StringView(reinterpret_cast<char *>(s.data()), s.size()),
10597 cs);
10598 while ((i = matcher.indexIn(haystack, from: i + 1)) != -1)
10599 ++num;
10600
10601 return num;
10602}
10603
10604qsizetype QtPrivate::count(QStringView haystack, QLatin1StringView needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs)
10605{
10606 if (haystack.size() < needle.size())
10607 return -1;
10608
10609 QVarLengthArray<char16_t> s = qt_from_latin1_to_qvla(str: needle);
10610 return QtPrivate::count(haystack, needle: QStringView(s.data(), s.size()), cs);
10611}
10612
10613qsizetype QtPrivate::count(QLatin1StringView haystack, QChar needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
10614{
10615 // non-L1 needles cannot possibly match in L1-only haystacks
10616 if (needle.unicode() > 0xff)
10617 return 0;
10618
10619 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive) {
10620 return std::count(first: haystack.cbegin(), last: haystack.cend(), value: needle.toLatin1());
10621 } else {
10622 auto toLower = [](char ch) { return latin1Lower[uchar(ch)]; };
10623 const uchar ch = toLower(needle.toLatin1());
10624 return std::count_if(first: haystack.cbegin(), last: haystack.cend(), pred: [&toLower, ch](const char c) {
10625 return toLower(c) == ch;
10626 });
10627 }
10628}

10710qsizetype QtPrivate::findString(QStringView haystack0, qsizetype from, QStringView needle0, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
10711{
10712 const qsizetype l = haystack0.size();
10713 const qsizetype sl = needle0.size();
10714 if (from < 0)
10715 from += l;
10716 if (std::size_t(sl + from) > std::size_t(l))
10717 return -1;
10718 if (!sl)
10719 return from;
10720 if (!l)
10721 return -1;
10722
10723 if (sl == 1)
10724 return qFindChar(str: haystack0, ch: needle0[0], from, cs);
10725
10726 /*
10727 We use the Boyer-Moore algorithm in cases where the overhead
10728 for the skip table should pay off, otherwise we use a simple
10729 hash function.
10730 */
10731 if (l > 500 && sl > 5)
10732 return qFindStringBoyerMoore(haystack: haystack0, from, needle: needle0, cs);
10733
10734 auto sv = [sl](const char16_t *v) { return QStringView(v, sl); };
10735 /*
10736 We use some hashing for efficiency's sake. Instead of
10737 comparing strings, we compare the hash value of str with that
10738 of a part of this QString. Only if that matches, we call
10739 qt_string_compare().
10740 */
10741 const char16_t *needle = needle0.utf16();
10742 const char16_t *haystack = haystack0.utf16() + from;
10743 const char16_t *end = haystack0.utf16() + (l - sl);
10744 const std::size_t sl_minus_1 = sl - 1;
10745 std::size_t hashNeedle = 0, hashHaystack = 0;
10746 qsizetype idx;
10747
10748 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive) {
10749 for (idx = 0; idx < sl; ++idx) {
10750 hashNeedle = ((hashNeedle<<1) + needle[idx]);
10751 hashHaystack = ((hashHaystack<<1) + haystack[idx]);
10752 }
10753 hashHaystack -= haystack[sl_minus_1];
10754
10755 while (haystack <= end) {
10756 hashHaystack += haystack[sl_minus_1];
10757 if (hashHaystack == hashNeedle
10758 && QtPrivate::compareStrings(lhs: needle0, rhs: sv(haystack), cs: Qt::CaseSensitive) == 0)
10759 return haystack - haystack0.utf16();
10760
10761 REHASH(*haystack);
10762 ++haystack;
10763 }
10764 } else {
10765 const char16_t *haystack_start = haystack0.utf16();
10766 for (idx = 0; idx < sl; ++idx) {
10767 hashNeedle = (hashNeedle<<1) + foldCase(ch: needle + idx, start: needle);
10768 hashHaystack = (hashHaystack<<1) + foldCase(ch: haystack + idx, start: haystack_start);
10769 }
10770 hashHaystack -= foldCase(ch: haystack + sl_minus_1, start: haystack_start);
10771
10772 while (haystack <= end) {
10773 hashHaystack += foldCase(ch: haystack + sl_minus_1, start: haystack_start);
10774 if (hashHaystack == hashNeedle
10775 && QtPrivate::compareStrings(lhs: needle0, rhs: sv(haystack), cs: Qt::CaseInsensitive) == 0)
10776 return haystack - haystack0.utf16();
10777
10778 REHASH(foldCase(haystack, haystack_start));
10779 ++haystack;
10780 }
10781 }
10782 return -1;
10783}
10784
10785qsizetype QtPrivate::findString(QStringView haystack, qsizetype from, QLatin1StringView needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
10786{
10787 if (haystack.size() < needle.size())
10788 return -1;
10789
10790 QVarLengthArray<char16_t> s = qt_from_latin1_to_qvla(str: needle);
10791 return QtPrivate::findString(haystack0: haystack, from, needle0: QStringView(reinterpret_cast<const QChar*>(s.constData()), s.size()), cs);
10792}
10793
10794qsizetype QtPrivate::findString(QLatin1StringView haystack, qsizetype from, QStringView needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
10795{
10796 if (haystack.size() < needle.size())
10797 return -1;
10798
10799 if (!QtPrivate::isLatin1(s: needle)) // won't find non-L1 UTF-16 needles in a L1 haystack!
10800 return -1;
10801
10802 if (needle.size() == 1) {
10803 const char n = needle.front().toLatin1();
10804 return QtPrivate::findString(haystack, from, needle: QLatin1StringView(&n, 1), cs);
10805 }
10806
10807 QVarLengthArray<char> s(needle.size());
10808 qt_to_latin1_unchecked(dst: reinterpret_cast<uchar *>(s.data()), src: needle.utf16(), length: needle.size());
10809 return QtPrivate::findString(haystack, from, needle: QLatin1StringView(s.data(), s.size()), cs);
10810}
10811
10812qsizetype QtPrivate::findString(QLatin1StringView haystack, qsizetype from, QLatin1StringView needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity cs) noexcept
10813{
10814 if (from < 0)
10815 from += haystack.size();
10816 if (from < 0)
10817 return -1;
10818 qsizetype adjustedSize = haystack.size() - from;
10819 if (adjustedSize < needle.size())
10820 return -1;
10821 if (needle.size() == 0)
10822 return from;
10823
10824 if (cs == Qt::CaseSensitive) {
10825
10826 if (needle.size() == 1) {
10827 Q_ASSUME(haystack.data() != nullptr); // see size check above
10828 if (auto it = memchr(s: haystack.data() + from, c: needle.front().toLatin1(), n: adjustedSize))
10829 return static_cast<const char *>(it) - haystack.data();
10830 return -1;
10831 }
10832
10833 const QLatin1StringMatcher matcher(needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity::CaseSensitive);
10834 return matcher.indexIn(haystack, from);
10835 }
10836
10837 // If the needle is sufficiently small we simply iteratively search through
10838 // the haystack. When the needle is too long we use a boyer-moore searcher
10839 // from the standard library, if available. If it is not available then the
10840 // QLatin1Strings are converted to QString and compared as such. Though
10841 // initialization is slower the boyer-moore search it employs still makes up
10842 // for it when haystack and needle are sufficiently long.
10843 // The needle size was chosen by testing various lengths using the
10844 // qstringtokenizer benchmark with the
10845 // "tokenize_qlatin1string_qlatin1string" test.
10846#ifdef Q_CC_MSVC
10847 const qsizetype threshold = 1;
10848#else
10849 const qsizetype threshold = 13;
10850#endif
10851 if (needle.size() <= threshold) {
10852 const auto begin = haystack.begin();
10853 const auto end = haystack.end() - needle.size() + 1;
10854 const uchar needle1 = latin1Lower[uchar(needle[0].toLatin1())];
10855 auto ciMatch = [needle1](const char ch) {
10856 return latin1Lower[uchar(ch)] == needle1;
10857 };
10858 const qsizetype nlen1 = needle.size() - 1;
10859 for (auto it = std::find_if(first: begin + from, last: end, pred: ciMatch); it < end;
10860 it = std::find_if(first: it + 1, last: end, pred: ciMatch)) {
10861 // In this comparison we skip the first character because we know it's a match
10862 if (!nlen1 || QLatin1StringView(it + 1, nlen1).compare(other: needle.sliced(pos: 1), cs) == 0)
10863 return std::distance(first: begin, last: it);
10864 }
10865 return -1;
10866 }
10867
10868 QLatin1StringMatcher matcher(needle, Qt::CaseSensitivity::CaseInsensitive);
10869 return matcher.indexIn(haystack, from);
10870}

10892#if QT_CONFIG(regularexpression)
10893qsizetype QtPrivate::indexOf(QStringView viewHaystack, const QString *stringHaystack, const QRegularExpression &re, qsizetype from, QRegularExpressionMatch *rmatch)
10894{
10895 if (!re.isValid()) {
10896 qtWarnAboutInvalidRegularExpression(pattern: re.pattern(), where: "QString(View)::indexOf");
10897 return -1;
10898 }
10899
10900 QRegularExpressionMatch match = stringHaystack
10901 ? re.match(subject: *stringHaystack, offset: from)
10902 : re.matchView(subjectView: viewHaystack, offset: from);
10903 if (match.hasMatch()) {
10904 const qsizetype ret = match.capturedStart();
10905 if (rmatch)
10906 *rmatch = std::move(match);
10907 return ret;
10908 }
10909
10910 return -1;
10911}

10913qsizetype QtPrivate::indexOf(QStringView haystack, const QRegularExpression &re, qsizetype from, QRegularExpressionMatch *rmatch)

10917
10918qsizetype QtPrivate::lastIndexOf(QStringView viewHaystack, const QString *stringHaystack, const QRegularExpression &re, qsizetype from, QRegularExpressionMatch *rmatch)
10919{
10920 if (!re.isValid()) {
10921 qtWarnAboutInvalidRegularExpression(pattern: re.pattern(), where: "QString(View)::lastIndexOf");
10922 return -1;
10923 }
10924
10925 qsizetype endpos = (from < 0) ? (viewHaystack.size() + from + 1) : (from + 1);
10926 QRegularExpressionMatchIterator iterator = stringHaystack
10927 ? re.globalMatch(subject: *stringHaystack)
10928 : re.globalMatchView(subjectView: viewHaystack);
10929 qsizetype lastIndex = -1;
10930 while (iterator.hasNext()) {
10931 QRegularExpressionMatch match = iterator.next();
10932 qsizetype start = match.capturedStart();
10933 if (start < endpos) {
10934 lastIndex = start;
10935 if (rmatch)
10936 *rmatch = std::move(match);
10937 } else {
10938 break;
10939 }
10940 }
10941
10942 return lastIndex;
10943}

10947 return lastIndexOf(viewHaystack: haystack, stringHaystack: nullptr, re, from, rmatch);

10950bool QtPrivate::contains(QStringView viewHaystack, const QString *stringHaystack, const QRegularExpression &re, QRegularExpressionMatch *rmatch)
10951{
10952 if (!re.isValid()) {
10953 qtWarnAboutInvalidRegularExpression(pattern: re.pattern(), where: "QString(View)::contains");
10954 return false;
10955 }
10956 QRegularExpressionMatch m = stringHaystack
10957 ? re.match(subject: *stringHaystack)
10958 : re.matchView(subjectView: viewHaystack);
10959 bool hasMatch = m.hasMatch();
10960 if (hasMatch && rmatch)
10961 *rmatch = std::move(m);
10962 return hasMatch;
10963}
10964
10965bool QtPrivate::contains(QStringView haystack, const QRegularExpression &re, QRegularExpressionMatch *rmatch)
10966{
10967 return contains(viewHaystack: haystack, stringHaystack: nullptr, re, rmatch);
10968}
10969
10970qsizetype QtPrivate::count(QStringView haystack, const QRegularExpression &re)
10971{
10972 if (!re.isValid()) {
10973 qtWarnAboutInvalidRegularExpression(pattern: re.pattern(), where: "QString(View)::count");
10974 return 0;
10975 }
10976 qsizetype count = 0;
10977 qsizetype index = -1;
10978 qsizetype len = haystack.size();
10979 while (index <= len - 1) {
10980 QRegularExpressionMatch match = re.matchView(subjectView: haystack, offset: index + 1);
10981 if (!match.hasMatch())
10982 break;
10983 count++;
10984
10985 // Search again, from the next character after the beginning of this
10986 // capture. If the capture starts with a surrogate pair, both together
10987 // count as "one character".
10988 index = match.capturedStart();
10989 if (index < len && haystack[index].isHighSurrogate())
10990 ++index;
10991 }
10992 return count;
10993}

10997/*!
10998 \since 5.0
10999
11000 Converts a plain text string to an HTML string with
11001 HTML metacharacters \c{<}, \c{>}, \c{&}, and \c{"} replaced by HTML
11002 entities.
11003
11004 Example:
11005
11006 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 7
11007*/
11008QString QString::toHtmlEscaped() const
11009{
11010 QString rich;
11011 const qsizetype len = size();
11012 rich.reserve(asize: qsizetype(len * 1.1));
11013 for (QChar ch : *this) {
11014 if (ch == u'<')
11015 rich += "&lt;"_L1;
11016 else if (ch == u'>')
11017 rich += "&gt;"_L1;
11018 else if (ch == u'&')
11019 rich += "&amp;"_L1;
11020 else if (ch == u'"')
11021 rich += "&quot;"_L1;
11022 else
11023 rich += ch;
11024 }
11025 rich.squeeze();
11026 return rich;
11027}

11029/*!
11030 \macro QStringLiteral(str)
11031 \relates QString
11032
11033 The macro generates the data for a QString out of the string literal \a str
11034 at compile time. Creating a QString from it is free in this case, and the
11035 generated string data is stored in the read-only segment of the compiled
11036 object file.
11037
11038 If you have code that looks like this:
11039
11040 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 9
11041
11042 then a temporary QString will be created to be passed as the \c{hasAttribute}
11043 function parameter. This can be quite expensive, as it involves a memory
11044 allocation and the copy/conversion of the data into QString's internal
11045 encoding.
11046
11047 This cost can be avoided by using QStringLiteral instead:
11048
11049 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 10
11050
11051 In this case, QString's internal data will be generated at compile time; no
11052 conversion or allocation will occur at runtime.
11053
11054 Using QStringLiteral instead of a double quoted plain C++ string literal can
11055 significantly speed up creation of QString instances from data known at
11056 compile time.
11057
11058 \note QLatin1StringView can still be more efficient than QStringLiteral
11059 when the string is passed to a function that has an overload taking
11060 QLatin1StringView and this overload avoids conversion to QString. For
11061 instance, QString::operator==() can compare to a QLatin1StringView
11062 directly:
11063
11064 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp 11
11065
11066 \note Some compilers have bugs encoding strings containing characters outside
11067 the US-ASCII character set. Make sure you prefix your string with \c{u} in
11068 those cases. It is optional otherwise.
11069
11070 \sa QByteArrayLiteral
11071*/
11072
11073#if QT_DEPRECATED_SINCE(6, 8)
11074/*!
11075 \fn QtLiterals::operator""_qs(const char16_t *str, size_t size)
11076
11077 \relates QString
11078 \since 6.2
11079 \deprecated [6.8] Use \c _s from Qt::StringLiterals namespace instead.
11080
11081 Literal operator that creates a QString out of the first \a size characters in
11082 the char16_t string literal \a str.
11083
11084 The QString is created at compile time, and the generated string data is stored
11085 in the read-only segment of the compiled object file. Duplicate literals may
11086 share the same read-only memory. This functionality is interchangeable with
11087 QStringLiteral, but saves typing when many string literals are present in the
11088 code.
11089
11090 The following code creates a QString:
11091 \code
11092 auto str = u"hello"_qs;
11093 \endcode
11094
11095 \sa QStringLiteral, QtLiterals::operator""_qba(const char *str, size_t size)
11096*/
11097#endif // QT_DEPRECATED_SINCE(6, 8)

11174/*!
11175 \macro const char *qPrintable(const QString &str)
11176 \relates QString
11177
11178 Returns \a str as a \c{const char *}. This is equivalent to
11179 \a{str}.toLocal8Bit().constData().
11180
11181 The char pointer will be invalid after the statement in which
11182 qPrintable() is used. This is because the array returned by
11183 QString::toLocal8Bit() will fall out of scope.
11184
11185 \note qDebug(), qInfo(), qWarning(), qCritical(), qFatal() expect
11186 %s arguments to be UTF-8 encoded, while qPrintable() converts to
11187 local 8-bit encoding. Therefore qUtf8Printable() should be used
11188 for logging strings instead of qPrintable().
11189
11190 \sa qUtf8Printable()
11191*/
11192
11193/*!
11194 \macro const char *qUtf8Printable(const QString &str)
11195 \relates QString
11196 \since 5.4
11197
11198 Returns \a str as a \c{const char *}. This is equivalent to
11199 \a{str}.toUtf8().constData().
11200
11201 The char pointer will be invalid after the statement in which
11202 qUtf8Printable() is used. This is because the array returned by
11203 QString::toUtf8() will fall out of scope.
11204
11205 Example:
11206
11207 \snippet code/src_corelib_text_qstring.cpp qUtf8Printable
11208
11209 \sa qPrintable(), qDebug(), qInfo(), qWarning(), qCritical(), qFatal()
11210*/
11211
11212/*!
11213 \macro const wchar_t *qUtf16Printable(const QString &str)
11214 \relates QString
11215 \since 5.7
11216
11217 Returns \a str as a \c{const ushort *}, but cast to a \c{const wchar_t *}
11218 to avoid warnings. This is equivalent to \a{str}.utf16() plus some casting.
11219
11220 The only useful thing you can do with the return value of this macro is to
11221 pass it to QString::asprintf() for use in a \c{%ls} conversion. In particular,
11222 the return value is \e{not} a valid \c{const wchar_t*}!
11223
11224 In general, the pointer will be invalid after the statement in which
11225 qUtf16Printable() is used. This is because the pointer may have been
11226 obtained from a temporary expression, which will fall out of scope.
11227
11228 Example:
